f the following which you do or cause to occur: (a) distribution of this or any Project Gutenberg-tm work, (b) alteration, modification, or additions or deletions to any Project Gutenberg-tm work, and (c) any Defect you cause. Section 2. Information about the Mission of Project Gutenberg-tm Project Gutenberg-tm is synonymous with the free distribution of electronic works in formats readable by the widest variety of computers including obsolete, old, middle-aged and new computers. It exists because of the efforts of hundreds of volunteers and donations from people in all walks of life. Volunteers and financial support to provide volunteers with the assistance they need, are critical to reaching Project Gutenberg-tm's goals and ensuring that the Project Gutenberg-tm collection will remain freely available for generations to come. In 2001, the Project Gutenberg Literary Archive Foundation was created to provide a secure and permanent future for Project Gutenberg-tm and future generations. To learn more about the Project Gutenberg Literary Archive Foundation and how your efforts and donations can help, see Sections 3 and 4 and the Foundation web page at http://www.pglaf.org. Section 3. Information about the Project Gutenberg Literary Archive Foundation The Project Gutenberg Literary Archive Foundation is a non profit 501(c)(3) educational corporation organized under the laws of the state of Mississippi and granted tax exempt status by the Internal Revenue Service. The Foundation's EIN or federal tax identification number is 64-6221541. Its 501(c)(3) letter is posted at http://pglaf.org/fundraising. Contributions to the Project Gutenberg Literary Archive Foundation are tax deductible to the full extent permitted by U.S. federal laws and your state's laws. The Foundation's principal office is located at 4557 Melan Dr. S. Fairbanks, AK, 99712., but its volunteers and employees are scattered throughout numerous locations. Its business office is located at 809 North 1500 West, Salt Lake City, UT 84116, (801) 596-1887, email business@pglaf.org. Email contact links and up to date contact information can be found at the Foundation's web site and official page at http://pglaf.org For additional contact information: Dr. Gregory B. Newby Chief Executive and Director gbnewby@pglaf.org Section 4. Information about Donations to the Project Gutenberg Literary Archive Foundation Project Gutenberg-tm depends upon and cannot survive without wide spread public support and donations to carry out its mission of increasing the number of public domain and licensed works that can be freely distributed in machine readable form accessible by the widest array of equipment including outdated equipment. Many small donations ($1 to $5,000) are particularly important to maintaining tax exempt status with the IRS. The Foundation is committed to complying with the laws regulating charities and charitable donations in all 50 states of the United States. Compliance requirements are not uniform and it takes a considerable effort, much paperwork and many fees to meet and keep up with these requirements. We do not solicit donations in locations where we have not received written confirmation of compliance. To SEND DONATIONS or determine the status of compliance for any particular state visit http://pglaf.org While we cannot and do not solicit contributions from states where we have not met the solicitation requirements, we know of no prohibition against accepting unsolicited donations from donors in such states who approach us with offers to donate. International donations are gratefully accepted, but we cannot make any statements concerning tax treatment of donations received from outside the United States. U.S. laws alone swamp our small staff. Please check the Project Gutenberg Web pages for current donation methods and addresses. Donations are accepted in a number of other ways including checks, online payments and credit card donations. To donate, please visit: http://pglaf.org/donate Section 5. General Information About Project Gutenberg-tm electronic works. Professor Michael S. Hart is the originator of the Project Gutenberg-tm concept of a library of electronic works that could be freely shared with anyone. For thirty years, he produced and distributed Project Gutenberg-tm eBooks with only a loose network of volunteer support. Project Gutenberg-tm eBooks are often created from several printed editions, all of which are confirmed as Public Domain in the U.S. unless a copyright notice is included. Thus, we do not necessarily keep eBooks in compliance with any particular paper edition. Most people start at our Web site which has the main PG search facility: http://www.gutenberg.org This Web site includes information about Project Gutenberg-tm, including how to make donations to the Project Gutenberg Literary Archive Foundation, how to help produce our new eBooks, and how to subscribe to our email newsletter to hear about new eBooks.","author":"Seneca","source":"On Benefits 7.32","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:gratitude","theme:justice","theme:leadership","theme:mindfulness","theme:resilience","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"groups":{"work":"On Benefits","book":"7","section":"7.32"},"sequenceIndex":689,"isVerified":true},{"id":"stoic-ext-000001","text":"Of my grandfather Verus I have learned to be gentle and meek, and to refrain from all anger and passion... I have learned both shamefastness and manlike behaviour. Of my mother I have learned to be religious, and bountiful; and to forbear, not only to do, but to intend any evil; to content myself with a spare diet, and to fly all such excess as is incidental to great wealth.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000002","text":"Her reverence for the divine, her generosity, her inability not only to do wrong but even to conceive of doing it. And the simple way she lived—not in the least like the rich. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000003","text":"From Apollonius, true liberty, and unvariable steadfastness, and not to regard anything at all, though never so little, but right and reason: and always..that it was possible for the same man to be both vehement and remiss: a man not subject to be vexed, and offended with the incapacity of his scholars and auditors in his lectures and expositions.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000004","text":"Of Fronto, to how much envy and fraud and hypocrisy the state of a tyrannous king is subject unto, and how they who are commonly called [Eupatridas Gk.], i.e. nobly born, are in some sort incapable, or void of natural affection.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000005","text":"Not to display anger or other emotions. To be free of passion and yet full of love. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000006","text":"Self-control and resistance to distractions. Optimism in adversity—especially illness. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:resilience","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000007","text":"He was a man who looked at what ought to be done, not to the reputation which is got by a man's acts.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000008","text":"Ἕωθεν προλέγειν ἑαυτῷ: συντεύξομαι περιέργῳ, ἀχαρίστῳ, ὑβριστῇ, δολερῷ, βασκάνῳ, ἀκοινωνήτῳ: πάντα ταῦτα συμβέβηκεν ἐκείνοις παρὰ τὴν ἄγνοιαν τῶν ἀγαθῶν καὶ κακῶν.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000009","text":"γεγόναμεν γὰρ πρὸς συνεργίαν ὡς πόδες, ὡς χεῖρες, ὡς βλέφαρα, ὡς οἱ στοῖχοι τῶν ἄνω καὶ κάτω ὀδόντων. τὸ οὖν ἀντιπράσσειν ἀλλήλοις παρὰ φύσιν.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000010","text":"Whatever this is that I am, it is flesh and a little spirit and an intelligence. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000011","text":"What is divine is full of Providence. Even chance is not divorced from nature, from the inweaving and enfolding of things governed by Providence. Everything proceeds from it. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000012","text":"There is a limit to the time assigned you, and if you don't use it to free yourself it will be gone and never return. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000013","text":"Concentrate every minute like a Roman—like a man—on doing what's in front of you with precise and genuine seriousness, tenderly, willingly, with justice. And on freeing yourself from all other distractions. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000014","text":"Yes, you can--if you do everything as if it were the last thing you were doing in your life, and stop being aimless, stop letting your emotions override what your mind tells you, stop being hypocritical, self-centered, irritable. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000015","text":"You see how few things you have to do to live a satisfying and reverent life? If you can manage this, that's all even the gods can ask of you. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000016","text":"Give thyself time to learn something new and good, and cease to be whirled around.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000017","text":"This thou must always bear in mind, what is the nature of the whole...","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000018","text":"You could leave life right now. Let that determine what you do and say and think. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000019","text":"Yet living and dying, honour and dishonour, pain and pleasure, riches and poverty, and so forth are equally the lot of good men and bad. Things like these neither elevate nor degrade; and therefore they are no more good than they are evil.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000020","text":"The longest-lived and the shortest-lived man, when they come to die, lose one and the same thing.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000021","text":"Remember that all is opinion.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000022","text":"No state sorrier than that of the man who keeps up a continual round, and pries into \"the secrets of the nether world,\" as saith the poet, and is curious in conjecture of what is in his neighbour's heart.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000023","text":"Though thou be destined to live three thousand years and as many myriads besides, yet remember that no man loseth other life than that which he liveth, nor liveth other than that which he loseth.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000024","text":"For a man can lose neither the past nor the future; for how can one take from him that which is not his? So remember these two points: first, that each thing is of like form from everlasting and comes round again in its cycle, and that it signifies not whether a man shall look upon the same things for a hundred years or two hundred, or for an infinity of time; second, that the longest lived and the shortest lived man, when they come to die, lose one and the same thing.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000025","text":"Human life. Duration: momentary. Nature: changeable. Perception: dim. Condition of Body: decaying. Soul: spinning around. Fortune: unpredictable. Lasting Fame: uncertain. Sum Up: The body and its parts are a river, the soul a dream and mist, life is warfare and a journey far from home, lasting reputation is oblivion. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000026","text":"As for life, it is a battle and a sojourning in a strange land; but the fame that comes after is oblivion.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000027","text":"What means all this?","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000028","text":"Waste not the remnant of thy life in those imaginations touching other folk, whereby thou contributest not to the common weal.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000029","text":"...undefiled by pleasures, invulnerable to any pain, untouched by arrogance, unaffected by meanness, an athlete in the greatest of all contests—the struggle not to be overwhelmed by anything that happens. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000030","text":"The lot assigned to every man is suited to him, and suits him to itself.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000031","text":"For we carry our fate with us — and it carries us. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000032","text":"Be not unwilling in what thou doest, neither selfish nor unadvised nor obstinate; let not over-refinement deck out thy thought; be not wordy nor a busybody.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000033","text":"A man should be upright, not kept upright.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000034","text":"But that which is useful is the better.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000035","text":"Choose what's best.—Best is what benefits me. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000036","text":"Never esteem anything as of advantage to you that will make you break your word or lose your self-respect.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000037","text":"Respect the faculty that forms thy judgments.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000038","text":"Remember that man lives only in the present, in this fleeting instant; all the rest of his life is either past and gone, or not yet revealed. Short, therefore, is man's life, and narrow is the corner of the earth wherein he dwells.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000039","text":"Each of us lives only now, this brief instant. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000040","text":"The span we live is small—small as the corner of the earth in which we live it. Small as even the greatest renown, passed from mouth to mouth by short-lived stick figures, ignorant alike of themselves and those long dead. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000041","text":"Nothing has such power to broaden the mind as the ability to investigate systematically and truly all that comes under thy observation in life.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000042","text":"If you do the job in a principled way, with diligence, energy and patience, if you keep yourself free of distractions, and keep the spirit inside you undamaged, as if you might have to give it back at any moment— If you can embrace this without fear or expectation—can find fulfillment in what you're doing now, as Nature intended, and in superhuman truthfulness (every word, every utterance)—then your life will be happy. (Hays translation)—","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000043","text":"As surgeons keep their instruments and knives always at hand for cases requiring immediate treatment, so shouldst thou have thy thoughts ready to understand things divine and human, remembering in thy every act, even the smallest, how close is the bond that unites the two.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000044","text":"Nothing earthly succeeds by ignoring heaven, nothing heavenly by ignoring the earth. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000045","text":"The ruling power within, when it is in its natural state, is so related to outer circumstances that it easily changes to accord with what can be done and what is given it to do.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000046","text":"Let no act be done at haphazard, nor otherwise than according to the finished rules that govern its kind.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000047","text":"By a tranquil mind I mean nothing else than a mind well ordered.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000048","text":"Men seek retreats for themselves, houses in the country, sea-shores, and mountains; and thou too art wont to desire such things very much. But this is altogether a mark of the most common sort of men, for it is in thy power whenever thou shalt choose to retire into thyself. For nowhere either with more quiet or more freedom from trouble does a man retire than into his own soul.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000049","text":"The universe is flux, life is opinion.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000050","text":"Think on this doctrine,—that reasoning beings were created for one another's sake; that to be patient is a branch of justice, and that men sin without intending it.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000051","text":"People try to get away from it all—to the country, to the beach, to the mountains. You always wish that you could too. Which is idiotic: you can get away from it anytime you like. By going within. Nowhere you can go is more peaceful—more free of interruptions—than your own soul. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000052","text":"The abyss of endless time that swallows it all. The emptiness of all those applauding hands. The people who praise us—how capricious they are, how arbitrary. And the tiny region in which it all takes place. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000053","text":"Be straightforward. Look at things like a man, like a human being, like a citizen, like a mortal. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000054","text":"Disturbance comes only from within—from our own perceptions. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000055","text":"“The world is nothing but change. Our life is only perception.” (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000056","text":"Nothing can come out of nothing, any more than a thing can go back to nothing.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000057","text":"If mind is common to us, then also the reason, whereby we are reasoning beings, is common. If this be so, then also the reason which enjoins what is to be done or left undone is common. If this be so, law also is common; if this be so, we are citizens; if this be so, we are partakers in one constitution; if this be so, the Universe is a kind of Commonwealth.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000058","text":"Death, like generation, is a secret of Nature.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000059","text":"Choose not to be harmed—and you won't feel harmed. Don't feel harmed—and you haven't been. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000060","text":"That which makes the man no worse than he was makes his life no worse: it has no power to harm, without or within.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000061","text":"Whatever happens at all happens as it should; you will find this true, if you watch narrowly.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000062","text":"You have a mind? —Yes. Well, why not use it? (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000063","text":"Death hangs over thee: whilst yet thou livest, whilst thou mayest, be good.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000064","text":"Many the lumps of frankincense on the same altar; one falls there early and another late, but it makes no difference.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000065","text":"Not to live as if you had endless years ahead of you. Death overshadows you. While you're alive and able—be good. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000066","text":"How much time he gains who does not look to see what his neighbor says or does or thinks, but only at what he does himself, to make it just and holy.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000067","text":"Doth perfect beauty stand in need of praise at all? Nay; no more than law, no more than truth, no more than loving kindness, nor than modesty.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000068","text":"Whatever is in any way beautiful hath its source of beauty in itself, and is complete in itself; praise forms no part of it. So it is none the worse nor the better for being praised.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000069","text":"Does anything genuinely beautiful need supplementing? No more than justice does—or truth, or kindness, or humility. Are any of those improved by being praised? Or damaged by contempt? Is an emerald suddenly flawed if no one admires it? Or gold, or ivory, or purple? Lyres? Knives? Flowers? Bushes? (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:justice","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000070","text":"All that is harmony for you, my Universe, is in harmony with me as well. Nothing that comes at the right time for you is too early or too late for me. Everything is fruit to me that your seasons bring, Nature. All things come of you, have their being in you, and return to you.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000071","text":"\"Let your occupations be few,\" says the sage, \"if you would lead a tranquil life.\"","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000072","text":"Because most of what we say and do is not essential. If you can eliminate it, you'll have more time, and more tranquillity. Ask yourself at every moment, “Is this necessary?” But we need to eliminate unnecessary assumptions as well. To eliminate the unnecessary actions that follow. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000073","text":"Love the little trade which thou hast learned, and be content therewith.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000074","text":"Remember this— that there is a proper dignity and proportion to be observed in the performance of every act of life.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000075","text":"You're better off not giving the small things more time than they deserve. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000076","text":"Then what should we work for? Only this: proper understanding; unselfish action; truthful speech. A resolve to accept whatever happens as necessary and familiar, flowing like water from that same source and spring. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000077","text":"All is ephemeral — fame and the famous as well.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000078","text":"Observe always that everything is the result of a change, and get used to thinking that there is nothing Nature loves so well as to change existing forms and to make new ones like them.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000079","text":"Search men's governing principles, and consider the wise, what they shun and what they cleave to.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000080","text":"It needs to realize that what happens to everyone—bad and good alike—is neither good nor bad. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000081","text":"Constantly regard the universe as one living being, having one substance and one soul; and observe how all things have reference to one perception, the perception of this one living being; and how all things act with one movement; and how all things are the cooperating causes of all things which exist; observe too the continuous spinning of the thread and the contexture of the web.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000082","text":"Thou art a little soul bearing about a corpse, as Epictetus used to say.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000083","text":"Time is a sort of river of passing events, and strong is its current; no sooner is a thing brought to sight than it is swept by and another takes its place, and this too will be swept away.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000084","text":"All that happens is as usual and familiar as the rose in spring and the crop in summer.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000085","text":"That which comes after ever conforms to that which has gone before.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000086","text":"“Those who have forgotten where the road leads.” “They are at odds with what is all around them”—the all-directing logos. And “they find alien what they meet with every day.” (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000087","text":"Mark how fleeting and paltry is the estate of man - yesterday in embryo, tomorrow a mummy or ashes. So for the hairsbreadth of time assigned to thee, live rationally, and part with life cheerfully, as drops the ripe olive, extolling the season that bore it and the tree that matured it.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000088","text":"Don't let yourself forget how many doctors have died, after furrowing their brows over how many deathbeds. How many astrologers, after pompous forecasts about others' ends. How many philosophers, after endless disquisitions on death and immortality. How many warriors, after inflicting thousands of casualties themselves. How many tyrants, after abusing the power of life and death atrociously, as if they were themselves immortal. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mortality","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000089","text":"To be like the rock that the waves keep crashing over. It stands unmoved and the raging of the sea falls still around it.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000090","text":"It's unfortunate that this has happened. No. It's fortunate that this has happened and I've remained unharmed by it—not shattered by the present or frightened of the future. It could have happened to anyone. But not everyone could have remained unharmed by it.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000091","text":"So remember this principle when something threatens to cause you pain: the thing itself was no misfortune at all; to endure it and prevail is great good fortune.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:resilience","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000092","text":"Deem not life a thing of consequence. For look at the yawning void of the future, and at that other limitless space, the past.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000093","text":"Always take the short cut; and that is the rational one. Therefore say and do everything according to soundest reason.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000094","text":"At dawn, when you have trouble getting out of bed, tell yourself: ‘I have to go to work – as a human being. What do I have to complain of, if I’m going to do what I was born for – the things I was brought into the world to do? Or is this what I was created for? To huddle under the blankets and stay warm?’ (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000095","text":"How easy it is to repel and to wipe away every impression which is troublesome or unsuitable, and immediately to be in all tranquility.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000096","text":"Some people, when they do someone a favor, are always looking for a chance to call it in. And some aren't, but they're still aware of it--still regard it as a debt. But others don't even do that. They're like a vine that produces grapes without looking for anything in return. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000097","text":"A horse at the end of the race...A dog when the hunt is over...A bee with its honey stored...And a human being after helping others. They don't make a fuss about it. They just go on to something else, as the vine looks forward to bearing fruit again in season. We should be like that. Acting almost unconsciously. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000098","text":"The other reason is that what happens to the individual is a cause of well-being in what directs the world--of its well-being, its fulfillment, or its very existence, even. Because the whole is damaged if you cut away anything--anything at all--from its continuity and its coherence. Not only its parts, but its purposes. And that's what you're doing when you complain: hacking and destroying. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000099","text":"Not to feel exasperated, or defeated, or despondent because your days aren't packed with wise and moral actions. But to get back up when you fail, to celebrate behaving like a human--however imperfectly--and fully embrace the pursuit that you've embarked on. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000100","text":"The things you think about determine the quality of your mind. Your soul takes on the color of your thoughts. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000101","text":"It is crazy to want what is impossible. And impossible for the wicked not to do so. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000102","text":"Nothing happens to anyone that he can't endure. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000103","text":"Things have no hold on the soul. They have no access to it, cannot move or direct it. It is moved and directed by itself alone. It takes the things before it and interprets them as it sees fit. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000104","text":"Prize that which is best in the universe; and this is that which useth everything and ordereth everything.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000105","text":"The mind is the ruler of the soul. It should remain unstirred by agitations of the flesh--gentle and violent ones alike. Not mingling with them, but fencing itself off and keeping those feelings in their place. When they make their way into our thoughts, through the sympathetic link between mind and body, don't try to resist the sensation. The sensation is natural. But don't let the mind start in with judgments, calling it 'good' or 'bad.' (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000106","text":"Art thou angry with him whose arm-pits stink? art thou angry with him whose mouth smells foul? What good will this anger do thee?","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000107","text":"The intelligence of the universe is social.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000108","text":"Consider all that you've gone through, all that you've survived. And that the story of your life is done, your assignment complete. How many good things have you seen? How much pain and pleasure have you resisted? How many honors have you declined? How many unkind people have you been kind to? (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000109","text":"...be tolerant with others and strict with yourself. Remember, nothing belongs to you but your flesh and blood—and nothing else is under your control. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000110","text":"But true good fortune is what you make for yourself. Good fortune: good character, good intentions, and good actions. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000111","text":"Just that you do the right thing. The rest doesn't matter. Cold or warm. Tired or well-rested. Despised or honored. Dying . . . or busy with other assignments. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000112","text":"Ἔσω βλέπε· μηδενὸς πράγματος μήτε ἡ ἰδία ποιότης μήτε ἡ ἀξία παρατρεχέτω σε.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000113","text":"The controlling Intelligence understands its own nature, and what it does, and whereon it works.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000114","text":"The best revenge is not to be like your enemy.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000115","text":"Μή, εἴ τι αὐτῷ σοὶ δυσκαταπόνητον, τοῦτο ἀνθρώπῳ ἀδύνατον ὑπολαμβάνειν, ἀλλ εἴ τι ἀνθρώπῳ δυνατὸν καὶ οἰκεῖον, τοῦτο καὶ σεαυτῷ ἐφικτὸν νομίζειν.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000116","text":"If any man can convince me and bring home to me that I do not think or act aright, gladly will I change; for I search after truth, by which man never yet was harmed. But he is harmed who abideth on still in his deception and ignorance.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000117","text":"I do what is mine to do; the rest doesn't disturb me. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000118","text":"Death,—a stopping of impressions through the senses, and of the pulling of the cords of motion, and of the ways of thought, and of service to the flesh.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000119","text":"Ὅρα μὴ ἀποκαισαρωθῇς, μὴ βαφῇς· γίνεται γάρ. τήρησον οὖν σεαυτὸν ἁπλοῦν, ἀγαθόν, ἀκέραιον, σεμνόν, ἄκομψον, τοῦ δικαίου φίλον, θεοσεβῆ, εὐμενῆ, φιλόστοργον, ἐρρωμένον πρὸς τὰ πρέποντα ἔργα. ἀγώνισαι, ἵνα τοιοῦτος συμμείνῃς, οἷόν σε ἠθέλησε ποιῆσαι φιλοσοφία. αἰδοῦ θεούς, σῷζε ἀνθρώπους. βραχὺς ὁ βίος· εἷς καρπὸς τῆς ἐπιγείου ζωῆς, διάθεσις ὁσία καὶ πράξεις κοινωνικαί.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000120","text":"Reverence the gods, and help men. Short is life.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000121","text":"I consist of a little body and a soul.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000122","text":"Οἷς συγκεκλήρωσαι πράγμασι, τούτοις συνάρμοζε σεαυτόν, καὶ οἷς συνείληχας ἀνθρώποις, τούτους φίλει, ἀλλ ἀληθινῶς.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000123","text":"But if we judge only those things which are in our power to be good or bad, there remains no reason either for finding fault with God or standing in a hostile attitude to man.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000124","text":"The only thing that isn't worthless: to live this life out truthfully and rightly. And be patient with those who don't. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000125","text":"What is not good for the swarm is not good for the bee.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000126","text":"How many together with whom I came into the world are already gone out of it.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000127","text":"I can control my thoughts as necessary; then how can I be troubled? (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000128","text":"Understand however that every man is worth just so much as the things are worth about which he busies himself.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000129","text":"How many, once lauded in song, are given over to the forgotten; and how many who sung their praises are clean gone long ago!","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000130","text":"Never let the future disturb you. You will meet it, if you have to, with the same weapons of reason which today arm you against the present.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000131","text":"Πάντα ἀλλήλοις ἐπιπέπλεκται καὶ ἡ σύνδεσις ἱερά, καὶ σχεδόν τι οὐδὲν ἀλλότριον ἄλλο ἄλλωι· συγκατατέτακται γὰρ καὶ συγκοσμεῖ τὸν αὐτὸν κόσμον. κόσμος τε γὰρ εἷς ἐξ ἁπάντων καὶ θεὸς εἷς δι᾽ ἁπάντων καὶ οὐσία μία καὶ νόμος εἷς, λόγος κοινὸς πάντων τῶν νοερῶν ζώιων, καὶ ἀλήθεια μία, εἴγε καὶ τελειότης μία τῶν ὁμογενῶν καὶ τοῦ αὐτοῦ λόγου μετεχόντων ζώιων.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000132","text":"..If you are troubled by external circumstances, it is not the circumstances that trouble you, but your own perception of them - and they are in your power to change at any time.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000133","text":"If you are distressed by anything external, the pain is not due to the thing itself, but to your estimate of it; and this you have the power to revoke at any moment.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000134","text":"Remember, that to change thy mind upon occasion, and to follow him that is able to rectify thee, is equally ingenuous, as to find out at the first, what is right and just, without help. For of thee nothing is required, that is beyond the extent of thine own deliberation and judgment, and of thine own understanding.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000135","text":"No matter what anyone says or does, my task is to be good. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000136","text":"An angry countenance is much against nature, and it is oftentimes the proper countenance of them that are at the point of death. But were it so, that all anger and passion were so thoroughly quenched in thee, that it were altogether impossible to kindle it any more, yet herein must not thou rest satisfied, but further endeavour by good consequence of true ratiocination, perfectly to conceive and understand, that all anger and passion is against reason.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000137","text":"Is any man afraid of change? Why what can take place without change?","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000138","text":"Ἐγγὺς μὲν ἡ σὴ περὶ πάντων λήθη, ἐγγὺς δὲ ἡ πάντων περὶ σοῦ λήθη.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000139","text":"Ἴδιον ἀνθρώπου φιλεῖν καὶ τοὺς πταίοντας.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000140","text":"Nature which governs the whole will soon change all things which thou seest, and out of there substance will make other things, and again other things from the substance of them, in order that the world may ever be new.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000141","text":"Think not so much of what thou hast not as of what thou hast: but of the things which thou hast, select the best, and then reflect how eagerly they would have been sought, if thou hadst them not. At the same time, however, take care that thou dost not, through being so pleased with them, accustom thyself to overvalue them, so as to be disturbed if ever thou shouldst not have them.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000142","text":"Retire into thyself. The rational principle which rules has this nature, that it is content with itself when it does what is just, and so secures tranquility.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000143","text":"Wipe out the imagination. Stop pulling the strings. Confine thyself to the present. ...Divide and distribute every object into the causal [formal] and the material. ...Let the wrong which is done by a man stay there where the wrong was done.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000144","text":"Direct thy attention to what is said. Let thy understanding enter into the things that are doing and the things which do them.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000145","text":"Adorn thyself with simplicity and with indifference towards the things which lie between virtue and vice. Love mankind. Follow God. The poet says that Law rules all. And it is enough to remember that law rules all.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000146","text":"About fame... Just as the sand-dunes, heaped one upon another, hide each the first, so in life the former deeds are quickly hidden by those that follow after.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000147","text":"From Plato: the man who has an elevated mind and takes a view of all time and of all substance, dost thou suppose it possible for him to think that human life is anything great? It is not possible, he said. Such a man then will think that death also is no evil.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000148","text":"From Antisthenes: It is royal to do good and be abused.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000149","text":"It is a base thing for the countenance to be obedient and to regulate and compose itself as the mind commands, and for the mind not to be regulated and composed by itself.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000150","text":"It is not right to vex ourselves at things, For they care not about it.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000151","text":"If the gods care not for me and for my children, There is a reason for it.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000152","text":"For thus it is, men of Athens, in truth: wherever a man has placed himself thinking it is the best place for him, or has been placed by a commander, there in my opinion he ought to stay and to abide the hazard, taking nothing into the reckoning, either death or anything else, before the baseness [of deserting his post].","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:self-knowledge","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000153","text":"Look round at the courses of the stars, as if thou wert going along with them; and constantly consider the changes of the elements into one another; for such thoughts purge away the filth of the terrene life.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000154","text":"This is a fine saying of Plato: That he who is discoursing about men should look also at earthly things as if he viewed them from some higher place; should look at them... a mixture of all things and an orderly combination of contraries.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000155","text":"Thou mayest foresee... the things which will be. For they will certainly be of like form, and it is not possible that they should deviate from the order of things now: accordingly to have contemplated human life for forty years is the same as to have contemplated it for ten thousand years.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000156","text":"That which had grown from the earth, to the earth, But that which has sprung from heavenly seed, Back to the heavenly realms returns. This is either a dissolution of the mutual involution of the atoms, or a similar dispersion of the unsentient elements.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000157","text":"Another may be more expert in casting [throwing] his opponent; but he is not more social, nor more modest, nor better disciplined to meet all that happens, nor more considerate with respect to the faults of his neighbors.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000158","text":"Where any work can be done conformably to the reason which is common to gods and men, there we have nothing to fear; for where we are able to get profit by means of the activity which is successful and proceeds according to our constitution, there no harm is to be suspected.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000159","text":"Everywhere and at all times it is in thy power piously to acquiesce in thy present condition, and to behave justly to those who are about thee, and to exert thy skill upon thy present thoughts, that nothing shall steal into them without being well examined.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000160","text":"Every being ought to do that which is according to its constitution; and all other things have been constituted for the sake of the superior, but the rational for the sake of one another.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000161","text":"Consider thyself to be dead, and to have completed thy life up to the present time; and live according to nature the remainder which is allowed thee.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000162","text":"Love that only which happens to thee and is spun with the thread of thy destiny. For what is more suitable?","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000163","text":"Why then dost thou choose to act in the same way? and why dost thou not leave these agitations which are foreign to nature, to those who cause them and those who are moved by them? And why art thou not altogether intent upon the right way of making use of things which happen to thee? for then thou wilt use them well, and they will be material for thee. Only attend to thyself, and resolve to be a good man in every act which thou doest; and remember...","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000164","text":"Look within. Within is the fountain of the good, and it will ever bubble up, if thou wilt ever dig.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000165","text":"The art of life is more like the wrestler's art than the dancer's, in respect of this, that it should stand ready and firm to meet onsets which are sudden and unexpected.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000166","text":"Every soul, the philosopher says, is involuntarily deprived of truth; consequently in the same way it is deprived of justice and temperance and benevolence and everything of the kind. It is most necessary to keep this in mind, for thus thou wilt be more gentle towards all.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:justice","theme:self-knowledge","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000167","text":"In the case of most pains let this remark of Epicurus aid thee, that the pain is neither intolerable nor everlasting, if thou bear in mind that it has its limits, and if thou addest nothing to it in imagination...","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000168","text":"Very little is needed to make a happy life.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000169","text":"To live each day as though one's last, never flustered, never apathetic, never attitudinizing – here is perfection of character.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000170","text":"It's silly to try to escape other people's faults. They are inescapable. Just try to escape your own. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000171","text":"The nature of the All moved to make the universe.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000172","text":"On the occasion of every act ask thyself, How is this with respect to me? Shall I repent of it? A little time and I am dead, and all is gone.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000173","text":"You may break your heart, but men will still go on as before.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000174","text":"Constantly and, if it be possible, on the occasion of every impression on the soul, apply to it the principles of Physic, of Ethic, and of Dialectic.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000175","text":"To change your mind and to follow him who sets you right is to be nonetheless the free agent that you were before.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000176","text":"Nature has had regard in everything no less to the end than to the beginning and the continuance, just like a man who throws up a ball. What good is it then for the ball to be thrown up, or harm for it to come down... what good is it to the bubble while it holds together, or what harm when it is burst?","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000177","text":"Short-lived are both the praiser and the praised, and rememberer and the remembered: and all this in a nook of this part of the world; and not even here do all agree, no, not any one with himself: and the whole earth too is a point.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000178","text":"Look to the essence of a thing, whether it be a point of doctrine, of practice, or of interpretation.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000179","text":"Thou sufferest justly: for thou choosest rather to become good to-morrow than to be good to-day.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000180","text":"Remember this, then, that this little compound, thyself, must either be dissolved, or thy poor breath must be extinguished, or be removed and placed elsewhere.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000181","text":"Where have they gone, the brilliant, the insightful ones, the proud? (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000182","text":"It is satisfaction to a man to do the proper works of a man.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000183","text":"There are three relations [between thee and other things]: the one to the body which surrounds thee; the second to the divine cause from which all things come to all; and the third to those who live with thee.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000184","text":"To accept it without arrogance, to let it go with indifference. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000185","text":"Suppose that thou hast detached thyself from the natural unity... yet here there is this beautiful provision, that it is in thy power again to unite thyself. God has allowed this to no other part, after it has been separated and cut asunder, to come together again. ...he has distinguished man, for he has put it in his power not to be separated at all from the universal ...he has allowed him to be returned and to be united and to resume his place as a part.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:leadership","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000186","text":"As the nature of the universal has given to every rational being all the powers that it has, so we have received from it this power also. For as the universal nature converts and fixes in its predestined place everything which stands in the way and opposes it, and makes such things a part of itself, so also the rational animal is able to make every hindrance its own material, and to use it for such purpose as it may have designed.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000187","text":"Remember that neither the future nor the past pains thee, but only the present. But this is reduced to a very little, if thou only circumscribest it, and chidest thy mind, if it is unable to hold out against even this.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000188","text":"If thou canst see sharp, look and judge wisely, says the philosopher.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000189","text":"In the constitution of that rational animal I see no virtue which is opposed to justice, but I see a virtue which is opposed to love of pleasure, and that is temperance.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000190","text":"The things... which are proper to the understanding no other man is used to impede, for neither fire, nor iron, nor tyrant, nor abuse, touches it in any way. When it has been made a sphere, it continues a sphere.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000191","text":"It is not fit that I should give myself pain, for I have never intentionally given pain even to another.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000192","text":"If...it be a thing external that causes thy grief, know, that it is not that properly that doth cause it, but thine own conceit and opinion concerning the thing: which thou mayest rid thyself of, when thou wilt.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000193","text":"External things are not the problem. It's your assessment of them. Which you can erase right now. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000194","text":"The mind which is free from passions is a citadel, for man has nothing more secure to which he can fly for refuge and for the future be inexpugnable. He then who has not seen this is an ignorant man: but he who has seen it and does not fly to this refuge is unhappy.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000195","text":"The universal nature has no external space; but the wondrous part of her art is that though she has circumscribed herself, everything which is within her which appears to decay and to grow old and to be useless she changes into herself, and again makes other new things from these very same, so that she requires neither substance from without nor wants a place into which she may cast that which decays. She is content then with her own space, and her own matter, and her own art.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000196","text":"The cucumber is bitter? Then throw it out. There are brambles in the path? Then go around them. That's all you need to know. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000197","text":"No carelessness in your actions. No confusion in your words. No imprecision in your thoughts. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000198","text":"A man standing by a spring of clear, sweet water and cursing it. While the fresh water keeps on bubbling up. He can shovel mud into it, or dung, and the stream will carry it away, wash itself clean, remain unstained. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000199","text":"He who does not know what the world is, does not know where he is. And he who does not know for what purpose the world exists, does not know who he is, nor what the world is. But he who has failed in any one of these things could not even say for what purpose he exists himself. What then dost thou think of him who [avoids or] seeks the praise of those who applaud, of men who know not either where they are or who they are?","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000200","text":"You want praise from people who kick themselves every fifteen minutes, the approval of people who despise themselves. (Is it a sign of self-respect to regret nearly everything you do?) (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000201","text":"No longer let thy breathing only act in concert with the air which surrounds thee, but let thy intelligence also now be in harmony with the intelligence which embraces all things. For the intelligent power is no less diffused in all parts and pervades all things for him who is willing to draw it to him than the aërial power for him who is able to respire it.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000202","text":"He who fears death either fears to lose all sensation or fears new sensations. In reality, you will either feel nothing at all, and therefore nothing evil, or else, if you can feel any sensations, you will be a new creature, and so will not have ceased to have life.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000203","text":"Men exist for the sake of one another. Teach them then or bear with them. (Long translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000204","text":"An arrow has one motion and the mind another. Even when pausing, even when weighing conclusions, the mind is moving forward, toward its goal. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000205","text":"The nature of the universe is the nature of things that are. Now, things that are have kinship with things that are from the beginning. Further, this nature is styled Truth; and it is the first cause of all that is true.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000206","text":"He would be the finer gentleman that should leave the world without having tasted of lying or pretence of any sort, or of wantonness or conceit.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000207","text":"Think not disdainfully of death, but look on it with favor; for even death is one of the things that Nature wills.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000208","text":"A wrongdoer is often a man who has left something undone, not always one who has done something.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000209","text":"And you can also commit injustice by doing nothing. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000210","text":"Objective judgment, now, at this very moment. Unselfish action, now, at this very moment. Willing acceptance—now, at this very moment—of all external events. That's all you need. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000211","text":"Blot out vain pomp; check impulse; quench appetite; keep reason under its own control.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000212","text":"Things that have a common quality ever quickly seek their kind.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000213","text":"Today I escaped from anxiety. Or no, I discarded it, because it was within me, in my own perceptions—not outside. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mental-health","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000214","text":"All things are the same,—familiar in enterprise, momentary in endurance, coarse in substance. All things now are as they were in the day of those whom we have buried.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000215","text":"The happiness and unhappiness of the rational, social animal depends not on what he feels but on what he does; just as his virtue and vice consist not in feeling but in doing.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000216","text":"All things are changing; and thou thyself art in continuous mutation and in a manner in continuous destruction and the whole universe to.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000217","text":"Turn thy thoughts now to the consideration of thy life, thy life as a child, as a youth, thy manhood, thy old age, for in these also every change was a death. Is this anything to fear?","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000218","text":"Hasten [to examine] thy own ruling faculty and that of the universe and that of thy neighbor: thy own, that thy may make it just; and that of the universe, that thou mayst remember of what thou art a part; and that of thy neighbor, that thy mayst know whether he has acted ignorantly or with knowledge, and that thou mayst also consider that his ruling faculty is akin to thine.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000219","text":"As thou thyself art a component part of a social system, so let every act of thine be a component part of social life. Whatever act of thine that has no reference, either immediately or remotely, to a social end, this tears asunder thy life, and does not allow it to be one, and it is of the nature of a mutiny, just as when in a popular assembly a man acting by himself stands apart from the general agreement.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000220","text":"The universal intelligence puts itself in motion for every separate effect... or it puts itself in motion once, and everything else comes by way of a sequence in a manner; or individual elements are the origin of all things. In a word, if there is a god, all is well; and if chance rules, do not thou be governed by it.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000221","text":"If man reflects on the changes and transformations which follow one another like wave after wave and their rapidity, he will despise everything which is perishable.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000222","text":"Do what nature now requires. Set thyself in motion, if it is in thy power, and do not look about thee to see if any one will observe it; nor yet expect Plato's Republic: but be content if the smallest thing goes on well, and consider such an event to be no small matter.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000223","text":"Let there be freedom from perturbations with respect to the things which come from the external cause; and let there be justice in the things done by virtue of the internal cause, that is, let there be movement and action terminating in this, in social acts, for this is according to thy nature.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000224","text":"He that dies in extreme old age will be reduced to the same state with him that is cut down untimely.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000225","text":"The rottenness of the matter which is the foundation of everything!","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000226","text":"Either all things proceed from one intelligent source and come together as in one body, and the part ought not to find fault with what is done for the benefit of the whole; or there are only atoms, and nothing else than a mixture and dispersion. Why, then, art thou disturbed? Say to this ruling faculty, Art thou dead, art thou corrupted, art thou playing the hypocrite, art thou become a beast, dost thou herd and feed with the rest?","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000227","text":"Why dost thou not pray... to give thee the faculty of not fearing any of the things which thou fearest, or of not desiring any of the things which thou desirest, or not being pained at anything, rather than pray that any of these things should not happen or happen?","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000228","text":"Is it not better to use what is in thy power like a free man than to desire in a slavish and abject way what is not in thy power?","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000229","text":"One man prays thus: How shall I be able to lie with that woman? Do thou pray thus: How shall I not desire to lie with her? Another prays: How shall I be released from this? Another prays: How shall I not desire to be released? Another thus: How shall I not lose my little son? Thou thus: How shall I not be afraid to lose him? In fine, turn thy prayers this way, and see what comes.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000230","text":"Art thy not content that thou hast done something conformable to thy nature, and dost thou seek to be paid for it? Just as if the eye demanded recompense for seeing, or the feet for walking. For as these members are formed for a particular purpose... so also is man formed by nature to acts of benevolence.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000231","text":"Yes, boorish people do boorish things. What's strange or unheard-of about that? Isn't it yourself you should reproach—for not anticipating that they'd act this way? (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000232","text":"Use these rules then, and trouble thyself about nothing else.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000233","text":"Everything that happens is either endurable or not. If it's endurable, then endure it. Stop complaining. If it's unendurable . . . then stop complaining. Your destruction will mean its end as well. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000234","text":"If a man is mistaken, instruct him kindly and show him his error. But if thou art not able, blame thyself, or blame not even thyself.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000235","text":"Whatever may happen to thee, it was prepared for thee from all eternity; and the implication of causes was from eternity spinning the thread of thy being, and of that which is incident to it.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000236","text":"The whole contains nothing which is not or its advantage; and all natures indeed have this common principle, but the nature of the universe has this principle besides, that it cannot be compelled even by any external cause to generate anything harmful to itself.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000237","text":"By remembering then that I am a part of such a whole, I shall be content with everything that happens. And inasmuch as I am in a manner intimately related to the parts which are of the same kind with myself, I shall do nothing unsocial, but I shall rather direct myself to the things which are of the same kind with myself, and I shall turn all my efforts to the common interest, and divert them from the contrary.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000238","text":"Rememberest the gods, and that they wish not to be flattered, but wish all reasonable beings to be made like themselves; and... rememberest that what does the work of a fig-tree is a fig-tree, and that what does the work of a dog is a dog, and that what does the work of a bee is a bee, and that what does the work of a man is a man.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000239","text":"To her who gives and takes back all, to nature, the man who is instructed and modest says, Give what thou wilt; take back what thou wilt. And he says this not proudly, but obediently and well pleased with her.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000240","text":"Live as on a mountain. ...Let men see, let them know a real man who lives according to nature. If they cannot endure him, let them kill him. For that is better than to live thus.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000241","text":"Waste no more time arguing what a good man should be. Be one.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000242","text":"Constantly contemplate the whole of time and the whole of substance, and consider that all individual things as to substance are a grain of a fig, and as to time the turning of a gimlet.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000243","text":"Look at everything that exists, and observe that it is already in dissolution and change, and as it were putrefaction or dispersion, or that everything is so constituted in nature as to die.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000244","text":"Let this always be plain to thee, that this piece of land is like any other; and that all things here are the same with all things on the top of a mountain, or on the sea-shore, or wherever thou chooses to be. For thou wilt find just what Plato says, Dwelling within the walls of the city as in a shepherd's fold on a mountain.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000245","text":"What is my ruling faculty now to me? and of what nature am I now making it? and for what purpose am I now using it? is it void of understanding? is it loosed and rent asunder from social life? is it melted and mixed with the poor flesh so as to move together with it?","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000246","text":"He who flies from his master is a runaway; but the law is master, and he who breaks the law is a runaway. And he also who is grieved or angry or afraid, is dissatisfied because something has been or is or shall be of the things which are appointed by Him who rules all things, and He is Law, and assigns to every man what is fit. He then who fears or is grieved or is angry is a runaway.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000247","text":"All those [events in history] were such dramas as we see now, only with different actors.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000248","text":"Only to the rational animal is it given to follow voluntarily what happens; but simply to follow is a necessity imposed on all.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000249","text":"When thou art offended at any man's fault, forthwith turn to thyself and reflect in what manner thou doest error thyself... For by attending to this thou wilt quickly forget thy anger, if this consideration is also added, that the man is compelled; for what else could he do? or, if thou art able, take away from him the compulsion.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000250","text":"Continuously thou wilt look at human things as smoke and nothing at all; especially if thou reflectest at the same time, that what has once changed will never exist again in the infinite duration of time. But thou, in what a brief space of time is thy existence? And why art thou not content to pass through this short time in an orderly way?","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000251","text":"What matter and opportunity [for thy activity] art thou avoiding? For what else are all these things, except exercises for the reason, when it has viewed carefully and by examination into their nature the things which happen in life? Persevere then until thou shalt have made these things thy own, as the stomach which is strengthened makes all things its own, as the blazing fire makes flame and brightness out of everything that is thrown into it.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000252","text":"To live your brief life rightly, isn't that enough? (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000253","text":"Let it not be in any man's power to say truly of thee that thou art not simple or that thou art not good; but let him be a liar whoever shall think anything of this kind about thee; and this is altogether in thy power.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000254","text":"In the case of all things which have a certain constitution, whatever harm may happen to any of them, that which is affected becomes consequently worse; but in like case, a man becomes both better... and more worthy of praise, by making the right use of these accidents.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000255","text":"And finally remember that nothing harms him who is really a citizen, which does not harm the state; nor yet does anything harm the state which does not harm law [order]; and of these things which are called misfortunes not one harms law. What then does not harm law does not harm either state or citizen.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000256","text":"A little time, and thou shalt close thy eyes; and him who has attended thee to thy grave, another soon will lament.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000257","text":"Learn to ask of all actions, “Why are they doing that?” Starting with your own. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000258","text":"Remember that what pulls the strings is the force hidden within; there lies the power to persuade, there the life,—there, if one must speak out, the real man.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000259","text":"In contemplating thyself never include the vessel which surrounds thee, and these instruments which are attached about it. For they are like an ax, differing only in this, that they grow to the body. For indeed there is no more use in these parts without the cause which moves and checks them than in the weaver's shuttle, and the writer's pen, and the driver's whip.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000260","text":"Have I done something for the general interest? Well then I have had my reward. Let this always be present to thy mind, and never stop doing such good.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000261","text":"There is no nature which is inferior to art, the arts imitate the nature of things.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000262","text":"Someone despises me. That's their problem. Mine: not to do or say anything despicable. Someone hates me. Their problem. Mine: to be patient and cheerful with everyone, including them. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000263","text":"The man who is honest and good ought to be exactly like a man who smells strong, so that the bystander as soon as he comes near him must smell whether he choose or not.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000264","text":"A straightforward, honest person should be like someone who stinks: when you're in the same room with him, you know it. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000265","text":"How much more damage anger and grief do than the things that cause them. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000266","text":"Pain is the opposite of strength, and so is anger. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000267","text":"That to expect bad people not to injure others is crazy. It's to ask the impossible. And to let them behave like that to other people but expect them to exempt you is arrogant—the act of a tyrant. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000268","text":"“If you don’t have a consistent goal in life, you can’t live it in a consistent way.” (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000269","text":"Socrates used to call the opinions of the many by the name of Lamiae, bugbears to frighten children.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000270","text":"And virtue they will curse, speaking harsh words.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000271","text":"“No thefts of free will reported.” (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000272","text":"All those things at which thou wishest to arrive by a circuitous road, thou canst have now, if thou dost not refuse them to thyself.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000273","text":"I have often wondered how it should come to pass, that every man loving himself best, should more regard other men's opinions concerning himself than his own.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000274","text":"...that to expect a bad person not to harm others is like expecting fig trees not to secrete juice, babies not to cry, horses not to neigh—the inevitable not to happen. (Hays translation)","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000275","text":"If it is not right, do not do it, if it is not true, do not say it. For let thy efforts be —","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000276","text":"Consider that everything is opinion, and opinion is in thy power. Take away then, when thou choosest, thy opinion, and like a mariner, who has doubled the promontory, thou wilt find calm, everything stable, and a waveless bay.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000277","text":"Know the joy of life by piling good deed on good deed until no rift or cranny appears between them.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000278","text":"Depart then satisfied, for he also who releases thee is satisfied.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000279","text":"A little flesh, a little breath, and a Reason to rule all – that is myself.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000280","text":"Be like a rocky promontory against which the restless surf continually pounds; it stands fast while the churning sea is lulled to sleep at its feet. I hear you say, \"How unlucky that this should happen to me!\" Not at all! Say instead, \"How lucky that I am not broken by what has happened and am not afraid of what is about to happen. The same blow might have struck anyone, but not many would have absorbed it without capitulation or complaint.\"","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000281","text":"If thou art pained by any external thing, it is not this that disturbs thee, but thy own judgment about it. And it is in thy power to wipe out this judgment now.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000282","text":"A cucumber is bitter. Throw it away. There are briars in the road. Turn aside from them. This is enough. Do not add, \"And why were such things made in the world?\"","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000283","text":"Put an end once for all to this discussion of what a good man should be, and be one.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000284","text":"Soon you'll be ashes or bones. A mere name at most—and even that is just a sound, an echo. The things we want in life are empty, stale, trivial.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000285","text":"Never regard something as doing you good if it makes you betray a trust or lose your sense of shame or makes you show hatred, suspicion, ill-will or hypocrisy or a desire for things best done behind closed doors.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000286","text":"Not to feel exasperated or defeated or despondent because your days aren't packed with wise and moral actions. But to get back up when you fail, to celebrate behaving like a human—however imperfectly—and fully embrace the pursuit you've embarked on.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000287","text":"Let opinion be taken away, and no man will think himself wronged. If no man shall think himself wronged, then is there no more any such thing as wrong.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000288","text":"Take away your opinion, and there is taken away the complaint, [...] Take away the complaint, [...] and the hurt is gone","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000289","text":"[...] As for others whose lives are not so ordered, he reminds himself constantly of the characters they exhibit daily and nightly at home and abroad, and of the sort of society they frequent; and the approval of such men, who do not even stand well in their own eyes has no value for him.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000290","text":"Shame on the soul, to falter on the road of life while the body still perseveres.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000291","text":"Whatever happens to you has been waiting to happen since the beginning of time. The twining strands of fate wove both of them together: your own existence and the things that happen to you.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000292","text":"In your actions, don't procrastinate. In your conversations, don't confuse. In your thoughts, don't wander. In your soul, don't be passive or aggressive. In your life, don't be all about business.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000293","text":"What if someone despises me? Let me see to it. But I will see to it that I won't be found doing or saying anything contemptible. What if someone hates me? Let me see to that. But I will see to it that I'm kind and good-natured to all, and prepared to show even the hater where they went wrong. Not in a critical way, or to show off my patience, but genuinely and usefully.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000294","text":"Do not act as if thou wert going to live ten thousand years. Death hangs over thee. While thou livest, while it is in thy power, be good.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000295","text":"Of the life of man the duration is but a point.","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000296","text":"A person who doesn't know what the universe is doesn't know who they are. A person who doesn't know their purpose in life doesn't know who they are or what the universe is. A person who doesn't know any of these things doesn't know why they are here. So what to make of people who seek or avoid the praise of those who have no knowledge of where or who they are?","author":"Marcus Aurelius","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000297","text":"To be angry with a man is to hate him; to hate him is to wish him harm; but to wish him well, even if he has done you harm, is the mark of a great mind.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000298","text":"Quaeris Alcidae parem? Nemo est nisi ipse.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000299","text":"rursus prosperum ac felix scelus virtus vocatur; sontibus parent boni, ius est in armis, opprimit leges timor.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000300","text":"inveniet viam aut faciet.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000301","text":"Iniqua raro maximis virtutibus fortuna parcit ; nemo se tuto diu periculis offerre tam crebris potest; quem saepe transit casus, aliquando invenit.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000302","text":"qui genus iactat suum, aliena laudat.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000303","text":"ars prima regni est posse invidiam pati.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000304","text":"arma non servant modum; nec temperari facile nec reprimi potest stricti ensis ira; bella delectat cruor.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000305","text":"quaeritur belli exitus, non causa.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000306","text":"Cogi qui potest nescit mori.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000307","text":"Non est ad astra mollis e terris via.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000308","text":"quae fuit durum pati, meminisse dulce est.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000309","text":"Qui non vetat peccare cum possit, iubet.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000310","text":"Mortem misericors saepe pro vita dabit.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000311","text":"Pyrrhus: Lex nulla capto parcit aut poenam impedit.Agamemnon: Quod non vetat lex, hoc vetat fieri pudor.Pyr: Quodcumque libuit facere victori licet.Agam.: Minimum decet libere cui multum licet.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000312","text":"Levis est dolor qui capere consilium potest.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000313","text":"Qui nil potest sperare, desperate nihil.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000314","text":"Iniqua nunquam regna perpetuo manent.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000315","text":"Cui prodest scelus, is fecit.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000316","text":"Curae leues locuntur, ingentes stupent.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000317","text":"scelere velandum est scelus.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000318","text":"Mens impudicam facere, non casus, solet.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000319","text":"mens regnum bona possidet.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000320","text":"Illi mors gravis incubat Qui notus nimis omnibus Ignotus moritur sibi","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000321","text":"peior est bello timor ipse belli.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000322","text":"Quem mihi dabis qui aliquod pretium tempori ponat, qui diem aestimet, qui intellegat se cotidie mori?","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000323","text":"In hoc enim fallimur, quod mortem prospicimus: magna pars eius iam praeterit; quidquid aetatis retro est mors tenet.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000324","text":"Lay hold of today’s task, and you will not need to depend so much upon tomorrow’s. While we are postponing, life speeds by.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000325","text":"Tanta stultitia mortalium est.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000326","text":"Sera parsimonia in fundo est.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000327","text":"The primary indication, to my thinking, of a well-ordered mind is a man’s ability to remain in one place and linger in his own company.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000328","text":"Nusquam est qui ubique est. Vitam in peregrinatione exigentibus hoc evenit, ut multa hospitia habeant, nullas amicitias.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000329","text":"Non qui parum habet, sed qui plus cupit, pauper est.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000330","text":"Nam illa tumultu gaudens non est industria sed exagitatae mentis concursatio.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000331","text":"Nulli potest secura vita contingere qui de producenda nimis cogitat.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000332","text":"Most men ebb and flow in wretchedness between the fear of death and the hardships of life; they are unwilling to live, and yet they do not know how to die.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000333","text":"No man has ever been so far advanced by Fortune that she did not threaten him as greatly as she had previously indulged him.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000334","text":"I commend you and rejoice in the fact that you are persistent in your studies, and that, putting all else aside, you make it each day your endeavour to become a better man.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000335","text":"Plus tamen tibi et viva vox et convictus quam oratio proderit; in rem praesentem venias oportet, primum quia homines amplius oculis quam auribus credunt, deinde quia longum iter est per praecepta, breve et efficax per exempla.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000336","text":"“What progress, you ask, have I made? I have begun to be a friend to myself.” That was indeed a great benefit; such a person can never be alone. You may be sure that such a man is a friend to all mankind.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000337","text":"But both courses are to be avoided; you should not copy the bad simply because they are many, nor should you hate the many because they are unlike you.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000338","text":"Recede in te ipse quantum potes; cum his versare qui te meliorem facturi sunt, illos admitte quos tu potes facere meliores. Mutuo ista fiunt, et homines dum docent discunt.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000339","text":"sic vive cum hominibus tamquam deus videat, si loquere cum deo tamquam homines audiant.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000340","text":"sciant quae optima sunt esse communia.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000341","text":"... the only contestant who can confidently enter the lists is the man who has seen his own blood, who has felt his teeth rattle beneath his opponent’s fist, who has been tripped and felt the full force of his adversary’s charge, who has been downed in body but not in spirit, one who, as often as he falls, rises again with greater defiance than ever.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000342","text":"Let another say. “Perhaps the worst will not happen.” You yourself must say. “Well, what if it does happen? Let us see who wins! Perhaps it happens for my best interests; it may be that such a death will shed credit upon my life.”","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mortality","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000343","text":"Socrates was ennobled by the hemlock draught. Wrench from Cato's hand his sword, the vindicator of liberty, and you deprive him of the greatest share of his glory.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000344","text":"Plura sunt, Lucili, quae nos terrent quam quae premunt, et saepius opinione quam re laboramus.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000345","text":"Mos antiquis fuit, usque ad meam servatus aetatem, primis epistulae verbis adicere 'si vales bene est, ego valeo'. Recte nos dicimus 'si philosopharis, bene est'. Valere enim hoc demum est. Sine hoc aeger est animus.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000346","text":"There is no reason why poverty should call us away from philosophy—no, nor even actual want. For when hastening after wisdom, we must endure even hunger. Men have endured hunger when their towns were besieged, and what other reward for their endurance did they obtain than that they did not fall under the conqueror’s power? How much greater is the promise of the prize of everlasting liberty, and the assurance that we need fear neither God nor man! Even though we starve, we must reach that goal.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000347","text":"Armies have endured all manner of want, have lived on roots, and have resisted hunger by means of food too revolting to mention. All this they have suffered to gain a kingdom, and—what is more marvellous—to gain a kingdom that will be another’s. Will any man hesitate to endure poverty, in order that he may free his mind from madness?","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000348","text":"If you would not have a man flinch when the crisis comes, train him before it comes.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000349","text":"Leve aes alienum debitorem facit, grave inimicum.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000350","text":"Prove your words by your deeds.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000351","text":"quid est sapienta? semper idem velle atque idem nolle.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000352","text":"Press on, therefore, as you have begun; perhaps you will be led to perfection, or to a point which you alone understand is still short of perfection.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000353","text":"Nemo quam bene vivat sed quam diu curat, cum omnibus possit contingere ut bene vivant, ut diu nulli.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000354","text":"It is indeed foolish to be unhappy now because you may be unhappy at some future time.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000355","text":"You will thus understand that what you fear is either insignificant or short-lived.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000356","text":"Mucius put his hand into the fire. It is painful to be burned; but how much more painful to inflict such suffering upon oneself!","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000357","text":"[Mucius] might have accomplished something more successful in that camp, but never anything more brave.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:courage","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000358","text":"It was a great deed to conquer Carthage, but a greater deed to conquer death.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000359","text":"Illud autem ante omnia memento, demere rebus tumultum ac videre quid in quaque re sit: scies nihil esse in istis terribile nisi ipsum timorem.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000360","text":"I may become a poor man; I shall then be one among many. I may be exiled; I shall then regard myself as born in the place to which I shall be sent. They may put me in chains. What then? Am I free from bonds now? Behold this clogging burden of a body, to which nature has fettered me! “I shall die,” you say; you mean to say “I shall cease to run the risk of sickness; I shall cease to run the risk of imprisonment; I shall cease to run the risk of death.”","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:nature","theme:relationships","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000361","text":"I do not know whether I shall make progress; but I should prefer to lack success rather than to lack faith.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000362","text":"You do not know where death awaits you; so be ready for it everywhere.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000363","text":"Tu me' inquis 'mones? iam enim te ipse monuisti, iam correxisti? ideo aliorum emendationi vacas?' Non sum tam improbus ut curationes aeger obeam, sed, tamquam in eodem valetudinario iaceam, de communi tecum malo colloquor et remedia communico.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000364","text":"Sola virtus praestat gaudium perpetuum, securum; etiam si quid obstat, nubium modo intervenit, quae infra feruntur nec umquam diem vincunt.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000365","text":"You need a change of soul rather than a change of climate.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000366","text":"You must lay aside the burdens of the mind; until you do this, no place will satisfy you.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000367","text":"Nam qui peccare se nescit, corrigi non vult.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000368","text":"Magnus gubernator et scisso navigat velo.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000369","text":"He who does not wish to die cannot have wished to live.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000370","text":"I forbid you to be cast down or depressed. It is not enough if you do not shrink from work; ask for it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000371","text":"Would you know what makes men greedy for the future? It is because no one has yet found himself.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000372","text":"Praeterea qui alium sequitur nihil invenit, immo nec quaerit.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000373","text":"Quid ergo? non ibo per priorum vestigia? ego vero utar via vetere, sed si propiorem planioremque invenero, hanc muniam. Qui ante nos ista moverunt non domini nostri sed duces sunt. Patet omnibus veritas; nondum est occupata; multum ex illa etiam futuris relictum est.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000374","text":"Amicitia semper prodest, amor aliquando etiam nocet","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000375","text":"You must die erect and unyielding.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000376","text":"It is disgraceful, instead of proceeding ahead, to be carried along, and then suddenly, amid the whirlpool of events, to ask in a dazed way: “How did I get into this condition?”","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000377","text":"It is the quality of a great soul to scorn great things and to prefer that which is ordinary rather than that which is too great.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000378","text":"Then it is that the height of unhappiness is reached, when men are not only attracted, but even pleased, by shameful things, and when there is no longer any room for a cure, now that those things which once were vices have become habits.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000379","text":"Facis rem optimam et tibi salutarem, si, ut scribis, perseveras ire ad bonam mentem, quam stultum est optare, cum possis a te impetrare. Non sunt ad caelum elevandae inarms nee exorandus aedituus, ut nos ad aurem simulacri, quasi magis exaudiri possimus, admittat; Prope est a te deus, tecum est, intus est. Ita dico, Lucili: sacer intra nos spiritus sedet, malorum bonorumque nostrorum observator et custos...","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000380","text":"Non faciunt meliorem equum aurei freni.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000381","text":"If you see a man who is unterrified in the midst of dangers, untouched by desires, happy in adversity, peaceful amid the storm, who looks down upon men from a higher plane, and views the gods on a footing of equality, will not a feeling of reverence for him steal over you, will you not say: “This quality is too great and too lofty to be regarded as resembling this petty body in which it dwells? A divine power has descended upon that man.”","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:mindfulness","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000382","text":"No man ought to glory except in that which is his own.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000383","text":"Rationale enim animal est homo.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000384","text":"Very often the things that cost nothing cost us the most heavily; I can show you many objects the quest and acquisition of which have wrested freedom from our hands.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000385","text":"“You will have less money.” Yes, and less trouble. “Less influence.” Yes, and less envy.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000386","text":"He that owns himself has lost nothing. But how few men are blessed with ownership of self!","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000387","text":"Is qui scit plurimum, rumor.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000388","text":"Non refert quam multos sed quam bonos habeas.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000389","text":"“They are slaves,” people declare. Nay, rather they are men. “Slaves!” No, comrades. “Slaves!” No, they are unpretentious friends. “Slaves!” No, they are our fellow-slaves, if one reflects that Fortune has equal rights over slaves and free men alike.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:justice","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000390","text":"Vis tu cogitare istum quem servum tuum vocas ex isdem seminibus ortum eodem frui caelo, aeque spirare, aeque vivere, aeque mori! tam tu illum videre ingenuum potes quam ille te servum.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000391","text":"sic cum inferiore vivas quemadmodum tecum superiorem velis vivere.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000392","text":"I propose to value them according to their character, and not according to their duties. Each man acquires his character for himself, but accident assigns his duties.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000393","text":"“He is a slave.” His soul, however, may be that of a freeman. “He is a slave.” But shall that stand in his way? Show me a man who is not a slave; one is a slave to lust, another to greed, another to ambition, and all men are slaves to fear.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000394","text":"Would you really know what philosophy offers to humanity? Philosophy offers counsel.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000395","text":"Show me that the good in life does not depend upon life’s length, but upon the use we make of it; also, that it is possible, or rather usual, for a man who has lived long to have lived too little. Say to me when I lie down to sleep: “You may not wake again!” And when I have waked: “You may not go to sleep again!” Say to me when I go forth from my house: “You may not return!” And when I return: “You may never go forth again!”","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000396","text":"For what else are you busied with except improving yourself every day, laying aside some error, and coming to understand that the faults which you attribute to circumstances are in yourself?","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000397","text":"And what is freedom, you ask? It means not being a slave to any circumstance, to any constraint, to any chance; it means compelling Fortune to enter the lists on equal terms.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000398","text":"Would not anyone who is a man have his slumbers broken by a war-trumpet rather than by a chorus of serenaders?","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000399","text":"qualis quisque sit scies, si quemadmodum laudet, quemadmodum laudetur aspexeris.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000400","text":"Our luxuries have condemned us to weakness; we have ceased to be able to do that which we have long declined to do.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000401","text":"numquam vacat lascivire districtis, nihilque tam certum est quam otii vitia negotio discuti.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000402","text":"We are weak, watery beings standing in the midst of unrealities; therefore let us turn our minds to the things that are everlasting.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000403","text":"But the wise man is fortified against all inroads; he is alert; he will not retreat before the attack of poverty, or of sorrow, or of disgrace, or of pain. He will walk undaunted both against them and among them.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000404","text":"The wise man is joyful, happy and calm, unshaken, he lives on a plane with the gods.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000405","text":"That which Fortune has not given, she cannot take away.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000406","text":"I am endeavouring to live every day as if it were a complete life.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000407","text":"Ante senectutem curavi ut bene viverem, in senectute ut bene moriar; bene autem mori est libenter mori.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000408","text":"Brevissima ad divitias per contemptum divitiarum via est.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000409","text":"Fortune has taken away, but Fortune has given.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000410","text":"Let us greedily enjoy our friends, because we do not know how long this privilege will be ours.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000411","text":"Nulla res citius in odium venit quam dolor, qui recens consolatorem invenit et aliquos ad se adducit, inveteratus vero deridetur, nec inmerito.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000412","text":"Whatever can happen at any time can happen today.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000413","text":"Not lost, but gone before.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000414","text":"Omnis ars naturae imitatio est.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000415","text":"Great also are the souls of the defenders—men who know that, as long as the path to death lies open, the blockade is not complete, men who breathe their last in the arms of liberty.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:mortality","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000416","text":"Allow me, excellent Lucilius, to utter a still bolder word: if any goods could be greater than others, I should prefer those which seem harsh to those which are mild and alluring, and should pronounce them greater. For it is more of an accomplishment to break one’s way through difficulties than to keep joy within bounds.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:courage","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000417","text":"There stood Mucius, despising the enemy and despising the fire, and watched his hand as it dripped blood over the fire on his enemy’s altar, until Porsenna, envying the fame of the hero whose punishment he was advocating, ordered the fire to be removed against the will of the victim.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000418","text":"I cannot help believing that Mucius was all the more lucky because he manipulated the flames as calmly as if he were holding out his hand to the manipulator. He had wiped out all his previous mistakes; he finished the war unarmed and maimed; and with that stump of a hand he conquered two kings.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000419","text":"Now a life of honour includes various kinds of conduct; it may include the chest in which Regulus was confined, or the wound of Cato which was torn open by Cato’s own hand, or the exile of Rutilius, or the cup of poison which removed Socrates from gaol to heaven.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000420","text":"Clothe yourself with a hero’s courage, and withdraw for a little space from the opinions of the common man. Form a proper conception of the image of virtue, a thing of exceeding beauty and grandeur; this image is not to be worshipped by us with incense or garlands, but with sweat and blood.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:courage","theme:creativity","theme:resilience","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000421","text":"“I should prefer that Fortune keep me in her camp rather than in the lap of luxury. If I am tortured, but bear it bravely, all is well; if I die, but die bravely, it is also well.”","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:courage","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000422","text":"Why should I not regard this as desirable—not because the fire, burns me, but because it does not overcome me?","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000423","text":"Sapiens vivit quantum debet, non quantum potest.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000424","text":"errant consilia nostra, quia non habent quo derigantur; ignoranti quem portum petat nullus suus ventus est.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000425","text":"Scire debet quid petat ille, qui sagittam vult mittere, et tunc derigere ac moderari manu telum. Errant consilia nostra, quia non habent, quo derigantur. Ignoranti, quem portum petat, nullus suus ventus est. Necesse est multum in vita nostra casus possit, quia vivimus casu. Quibusdam autem evenit, ut quaedam scire se nesciant. Quemadmodum quaerimus saepe eos, cum quibus stamus, ita plerumque finem summi boni ignoramus adpositum.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000426","text":"These actions are not essentially difficult; it is we ourselves that are soft and flabby.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000427","text":"He knows his own strength; he knows that he was born to carry burdens.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000428","text":"Do you ask me whom I have conquered? Neither the Persians, nor the far-off Medes, nor any warlike race that lies beyond the Dahae; not these, but greed, ambition, and the fear of death that has conquered the conquerors of the world.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000429","text":"But no wall can be erected against Fortune which she cannot take by storm; let us strengthen our inner defences. If the inner part be safe, man can be attacked, but never captured.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:resilience","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000430","text":"But the wise man knows that all things are in store for him. Whatever happens, he says: “I knew it.”","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000431","text":"Tamdiu, discendum est, quemadmodum vivas, quamdiu vivas.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000432","text":"Would you not think him an utter fool who wept because he was not alive a thousand years ago? And is he not just as much of a fool who weeps because he will not be alive a thousand years from now? It is all the same; you will not be, and you were not. Neither of these periods of time belongs to you.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000433","text":"So near at hand is freedom, and is anyone still a slave?","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000434","text":"What else is there which you would regret to have taken from you? Friends? But who can be a friend to you? Country? What? Do you think enough of your country to be late to dinner? The light of the sun? You would extinguish it, if you could; for what have you ever done that was fit to be seen in the light?","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000435","text":"Aliquando enim et vivere fortiter facere est","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000436","text":"There is no sorrow in the world, when we have escaped from the fear of death.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000437","text":"You will die, not because you are ill, but because you are alive; even when you have been cured, thesame end awaits you; when you have recovered, it will be not death, but ill health, that you have escaped.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","audience:recovery","language:en","theme:mental-health","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000438","text":"No man can suffer both severely and for a long time; Nature, who loves us most tenderly, has so constituted us as to make pain either endurable or short.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000439","text":"“It is nothing—a trifling matter at most; keep a stout heart and it will soon cease”; then in thinking it slight, you will make it slight. Everything depends on opinion; ambition, luxury, greed, hark back to opinion. It is according to opinion that we suffer.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000440","text":"Two elements must therefore be rooted out once for all—the fear of future suffering, and the recollection of past suffering; since the latter no longer concerns me, and the former concerns me not yet.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000441","text":"Is it for this purpose that we are strong—that we may have light burdens to bear?","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000442","text":"Meanwhile, hold fast to this thought, and grip it close: yield not to adversity; trust not to prosperity; keep before your eyes the full scope of Fortune’s power, as if she would surely do whatever is in her power to do.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:relationships","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000443","text":"Eo animo quidque debetur quo datur, nec quantum sit sed a quali profectum voluntate perpenditur.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000444","text":"Quemadmodum Attalus noster dicere solebat, 'malitia ipsa maximam partem veneni sui bibit'. Illud venenum quod serpentes in alienam perniciem proferunt, sine sua continent, non est huic simile: hoc habentibus pessimum est.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000445","text":"“You must go now, fellow-soldiers, to yonder place, whence there is no ‘must’ about your returning!”","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000446","text":"Nihil aliud esse ebrietatem quam voluntariam insaniam.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000447","text":"Confragosa in fastigium dignitatis via est.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000448","text":"But he has no fear; unconquered he looks down from a lofty height upon his sufferings.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000449","text":"Thus no fortune, no external circumstance, can shut off the wise man from action. For the very thing which engages his attention prevents him from attending to other things. He is ready for either outcome: if it brings goods, he controls them; if evils, he conquers them.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000450","text":"So the wise man will develop virtue, if he may, in the midst of wealth, or, if not, in poverty; if possible, in his own country—if not, in exile; if possible, as a commander—if not, as a common soldier; if possible, in sound health—if not, enfeebled. Whatever fortune he finds, he will accomplish therefrom something noteworthy.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mental-health","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000451","text":"quemadmodum gladius neminem occidit: occidentis telum est.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000452","text":"Satius est supervacua scire quam nihil.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000453","text":"Quemadmodum perniciosior est hostis fugientibus, sic omne fortuitum incommodum magis instat cedenti et averso.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000454","text":"A thatched roof once covered free men; under marble and gold dwells slavery.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000455","text":"It would be some consolation for the feebleness of our selves and our works, if all things should perish as slowly as they come into being; but as it is, increases are of sluggish growth, but the way to ruin is rapid.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000456","text":"Perhaps its destruction has been brought about only that it may be raised up again to a better destiny. Oftentimes a reverse has but made room for more prosperous fortune. Many structures have fallen only to rise to a greater height.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000457","text":"Alexander, king of Macedon, began to study geometry; unhappy man, because he would thereby learn how puny was that earth of which he had seized but a fraction! Unhappy man, I repeat, because he was bound to understand that he was bearing a false title. For who can be “great” in that which is puny?","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000458","text":"Imagine that nature is saying to us: “Those things of which you complain are the same for all. I cannot give anything easier to any man, but whoever wishes will make things easier for himself.” In what way? By equanimity. You must suffer pain, and thirst, and hunger, and old age too, if a longer stay among men shall be granted you; you must be sick, and you must suffer loss and death.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:mortality","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000459","text":"That man, I declare, is happy whom nothing makes less strong than he is; he keeps to the heights, leaning upon none but himself; for one who sustains himself by any prop may fall.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000460","text":"Nemo liber est qui corpori servit.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000461","text":"postea noli rogare quod inpetrare nolueris.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000462","text":"Saepe aliud volumus, aliud optamus, et verum ne dis quidem dicimus.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000463","text":"As our acts and our thoughts are, so will our lives be.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000464","text":"Atqui vivere, Lucili, militare est.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000465","text":"For this reason those who are tossed about at sea, who proceed uphill and downhill over toilsome crags and heights, who go on campaigns that bring the greatest danger, are heroes and front-rank fighters; but persons who live in rotten luxury and ease while others toil, are mere turtle-doves safe only because men despise them.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000466","text":"“All the Good of mortals is mortal.”","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000467","text":"“Of all these experiences that seem so frightful, none is insuperable. Separate trials have been over- come by many: fire by Mucius, crucifixion by Regulus, poison by Socrates, exile by Rutilius, and a sword-inflicted death by Cato; therefore, let us also overcome something.”","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000468","text":"Pain he endures, death he awaits.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:mortality","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000469","text":"Whoever complains about the death of anyone, is complaining that he was a man. Everyone is bound by the same terms: he who is privileged to be born, is destined to die.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000470","text":"Accept in an unruffled spirit that which is inevitable.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000471","text":"But how foolish it is to set out one’s life, when one is not even owner of the morrow!","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000472","text":"Therefore, my dear Lucilius, begin at once to live, and count each separate day as a separate life.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000473","text":"The point is, not how long you live, but how nobly you live. And often this living nobly means that you cannot live long.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000474","text":"Socrates is reported to have replied, when a certain person complained of having received no benefit from his travels: “It serves you right! You travelled in your own company!”","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000475","text":"What profit is there in crossing the sea and in going from one city to another? If you would escape your troubles, you need not another place but another personality. Perhaps you have reached Athens, or perhaps Rhodes; choose any state you fancy, how does it matter what its character may be? You will be bringing to it your own.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000476","text":"“New friends, however, will not be the same.” No, nor will you yourself remain the same; you change with every day and every hour.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000477","text":"Si sapis, alterum alteri misce: nec speraveris sine desperatione nec desperaveris sine spe.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000478","text":"This spirit thrusts itself forward, confident of commendation and esteem. It is superior to all, monarch of all it surveys; hence it should be subservient to nothing, finding no task too heavy, and nothing strong enough to weigh down the shoulders of a man.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000479","text":"At quanto ego de illis melius existimo! ipsi quoque haec possunt facere, sed nolunt. Denique quem umquam ista destituere temptantem? cui non faciliora apparuere in actu? Non quia difficilia sunt non audemus, sed quia non audemus difficilia sunt.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000480","text":"He maintained this attitude up to the very end, and no man ever saw Socrates too much elated or too much depressed. Amid all the disturbance of Fortune, he was undisturbed.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000481","text":"Do you desire another case? Take that of the younger Marcus Cato, with whom Fortune dealt in a more hostile and more persistent fashion. But he withstood her, on all occasions, and in his last moments, at the point of death, showed that a brave man can live in spite of Fortune, can die in spite of her. His whole life was passed either in civil warfare, or under a political regime which was soon to breed civil war.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:courage","theme:mindfulness","theme:mortality","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000482","text":"No one ever saw Cato change, no matter how often the state changed: he kept himself the same in all circumstances—in the praetorship, in defeat, under accusation, in his province, on the platform, in the army, in death.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000483","text":"And this is the vote which [Cato] casts concerning them both: “If Caesar wins, I slay myself; if Pompey, I go into exile.” What was there for a man to fear who, whether in defeat or in victory, had assigned to himself a doom which might have been assigned to him by his enemies in their utmost rage? So he died by his own decision.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000484","text":"If you set a high value on liberty, you must set a low value on everything else.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000485","text":"Besides, he who is feared, fears also; no one has been able to arouse terror and live in peace of mind.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000486","text":"Quemadmodum omnium rerum, sic litterarum quoque intemperantia laboramus: non vitae sed scholae discimus.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000487","text":"And we cannot change this order of things; but what we can do is to acquire stout hearts, worthy of good men, thereby courageously enduring chance and placing ourselves in harmony with Nature.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:courage","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000488","text":"It is to this law that our souls must adjust themselves, this they should follow, this they should obey. Whatever happens, assume that it was bound to happen, and do not be willing to rail at Nature. That which you cannot reform, it is best to endure, and to attend uncomplainingly upon the God under whose guidance everything progresses; for it is a bad soldier who grumbles when following his commander.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:nature","theme:resilience","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000489","text":"Optimum est pati quod emendare non possis.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:courage","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000490","text":"They have been spoken by Plato, spoken by Zeno, spoken by Chrysippus or by Posidonius, and by a whole host of Stoics as numerous as excellent. I shall show you how men can prove their words to be their own: it is by doing what they have been talking about.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000491","text":"Let words proceed as they please, provided only your soul keeps its own sure order, provided your soul is great and holds unruffled to its ideals, pleased with itself on account of the very things which displease others, a soul that makes life the test of its progress, and believes that its knowledge is in exact proportion to its freedom from desire and its freedom from fear.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000492","text":"Why then do you occupy me with the words rather than with the works of wisdom? Make me braver, make me calmer, make me the equal of Fortune, make me her superior.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:courage","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000493","text":"Magna pars libertatis est bene moratus venter et contumeliae patiens.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000494","text":"The customs of that most criminal nation have gained such strength that they have now been received in all lands. The conquered have given laws to the conquerors.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000495","text":"Qui grate beneficium accipit, primam eius pensionem solvit.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000496","text":"Marcet sine adversario virtus.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000497","text":"Patrium deus habet adversus bonos viros animum et illos fortiter amat et \"Operibus,\" inquit, \"doloribus, damnis exagitentur, ut verum colligant robur.\" Languent per inertiam saginata nec labore tantum sed motu et ipso sui onere deficiunt. Non fert ullum ictum inlaesa felicitas; at cui assidua fuit cum incommodis suis rixa, callum per iniurias duxit nec ulli malo cedit sed etiam si cecidit de genu pugnat.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000498","text":"\"Licet,\" inquit, \"omnia in unius dicionem concesserint, custodiantur legionibus terrae, classibus maria, Caesarianus portas miles obsideat; Cato qua exeat habet; una manu latam libertati viam faciet. Ferrum istud, etiam civili bello purum et innoxium, bonas tandem ac nobiles edet operas: libertatem, quam patriae non potuit, Catoni dabit.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000499","text":"Quare deus optimum quemque aut mala valetudine aut luctu aut aliis incommodis adficit? quia in castris quoque periculosa fortissimis imperantur: dux lectissimos mittit qui nocturnis hostes adgrediantur insidiis aut explorent iter aut praesidium loco deiciant. Nemo eorum qui exeunt dicit 'male de me imperator mervit', sed 'bene iudicavit'.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000500","text":"Ignis aurum probat, miseria fortes uiros.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000501","text":"We put down mad dogs; we kill the wild, untamed ox; we use the knife on sick sheep to stop their infecting the flock; we destroy abnormal offspring at birth; children, too, if they are born weak or deformed, we drown. Yet this is not the work of anger, but of reason – to separate the sound from the worthless.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000502","text":"bonus iudex damnat inprobanda, non odit.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000503","text":"nemo autem regere potest nisi qui et regi.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000504","text":"Contra primus itaque causas pugnare debemus; causa autem iracundiae opinio iniuriae est, cui non facile credendum est. Ne apertis quidem manifestisque statim accedendum; quaedam enim falsa ueri speciem ferunt. Dandum semper est tempus: ueritatem dies aperit.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000505","text":"fidei acerrimus exactor est perfidus","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000506","text":"Magna pars hominum est quae non peccatis irascitur, sed peccantibus.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000507","text":"Hoc habent pessimum animi magna fortuna insolentes: quos laeserunt et oderunt.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000508","text":"Irascetur aliquis: tu contra beneficiis prouoca; cadit statim simultas ab altera parte deserta; nisi paria non pugnant.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000509","text":"Aut potentior te aut inbecillior laesit: si inbecillior, parce illi, si potentior, tibi.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000510","text":"Oculis de homine non credo, habeo melius et certius lumen quo a falsis uera diiudicem: animi bonum animus inueniat.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000511","text":"Omnis enim ex infirmitate feritas est.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000512","text":"Non exiguum temporis habemus, sed multum perdidimus. Satis longa vita.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000513","text":"Denique inter omnes convenit nullam rem bene exerceri posse ab homine occupato, non eloquentiam, non liberales disciplinas, quando districtus animus nihil altius recipit, sed omnia velut inculcata respuit.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000514","text":"Male vivet quisquis nesciet bene mori.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000515","text":"Numquam me in re bona mali pudebit auctoris.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000516","text":"Virtue runs no risk of becoming contemptible by being exposed to view, and it is better to be despised for simplicity than to be tormented by continual hypocrisy.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000517","text":"Our minds must have relaxation: rested, they will rise up better and keener. Just as we must not force fertile fields (for uninterrupted production will quickly exhaust them), so continual labor will break the power of our minds. They will recover their strength, however, after they have had a little freedom and relaxation.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","audience:recovery","language:en","theme:action","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000518","text":"Quid opus est partes deflere? Tota flebilis uita est.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000519","text":"By Hercules, the state would have sustained a great loss if you had not brought him forth from the oblivion to which his two splendid qualities, eloquence and independence, had consigned him: he is now read, is popular, is received into men’s hands and bosoms, and fears no old age: but as for those who butchered him, before long men will cease to speak even of their crimes, the only things by which they are remembered.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000520","text":"What madness this is, to punish oneself because one is unfortunate, and not to lessen, but to increase one’s ills! You ought to display, in this matter also, that decent behaviour and modesty which has characterised all your life: for there is such a thing as self-restraint in grief also.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000521","text":"When we leave you and assemble together by ourselves, we talk freely about his sayings and doings, treating them with the respect which they deserve: in your presence deep silence is observed about him, and thus you lose that greatest of pleasures, the hearing the praises of your son, which I doubt not you would be willing to hand down to all future ages, had you the means of so doing, even at the cost of your own life.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000522","text":"Some of the wisest of men have in consequence of this called anger a short madness: for it is equally devoid of self control, regardless of decorum, forgetful of kinship, obstinately engrossed in whatever it begins to do, deaf to reason and advice, excited by trifling causes, awkward at perceiving what is true and just, and very like a falling rock which breaks itself to pieces upon the very thing which it crushes.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000523","text":"That you may know that they whom anger possesses are not sane, look at their appearance; for as there are distinct symptoms which mark madmen, such as a bold and menacing air, a gloomy brow, a stern face","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:courage","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000524","text":"Next, if you choose to view its results and the mischief that it does, no plague has cost the human race more dear","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000525","text":"See the foundations of the most celebrated cities hardly now to be discerned; they were ruined by anger. See deserts extending for many miles without an inhabitant: they have been desolated by anger.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000526","text":"What, if you were to pass from the consideration of those single men against whom anger has broken out to view whole assemblies cut down by the sword, the people butchered by the soldiery let loose upon it, and whole nations condemned to death in one common ruin... as though by men who either freed themselves from our charge or despised our authority?","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000527","text":"Everything of this sort is not anger, but the semblance of anger, like that of boys who want to beat the ground when they have fallen upon it, and who often do not even know why they are angry, but are merely angry without any reason or having received any injury, yet not without some semblance of injury received, or without some wish to exact a penalty for it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000528","text":"Thus they are deceived by the likeness of blows, and are appeased by the pretended tears of those who deprecate their wrath, and thus an unreal grief is healed by an unreal revenge.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:mental-health","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000529","text":"We must admit, however, that neither wild beasts nor any other creature except man is subject to anger: for, whilst anger is the foe of reason, it nevertheless does not arise in any place where reason cannot dwell. Wild beasts have impulses, fury, cruelty, combativeness: they have not anger any more than they have luxury: yet they indulge in some pleasures with less self-control than human beings.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000530","text":"Dumb creatures have not human feelings, but have certain impulses which resemble them: for if it were not so, if they could feel love and hate, they would likewise be capable of friendship and enmity, of disagreement and agreement. Some traces of these qualities exist even in them, though properly all of them, whether good or bad, belong to the human breast alone.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000531","text":"To no creature besides man has been given wisdom, foresight, industry, and reflection.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000532","text":"Let us now enquire whether anger be in accordance with nature, and whether it be useful and worth entertaining in some measure.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000533","text":"What is more affectionate to others than man? Yet what is more savage against them than anger?","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000534","text":"Mankind is born for mutual assistance, anger for mutual ruin: the former loves society, the latter estrangement.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000535","text":"The one loves to do good, the other to do harm; the one to help even strangers, the other to attack even its dearest friends.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000536","text":"The one is ready even to sacrifice itself for the good of others, the other to plunge into peril provided it drags others with it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000537","text":"Who, then, can be more ignorant of nature than he who classes this cruel and hurtful vice as belonging to her best and most polished work?","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000538","text":"Anger, as we have said, is eager to punish; and that such a desire should exist in man’s peaceful breast is least of all according to his nature; for human life is founded on benefits and harmony and is bound together into an alliance for the common help of all, not by terror, but by love towards one another.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000539","text":"The mind must be indulged, and leisure must be given from time to time, which is the place of food and strength.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000540","text":"To roam in open walks, that the soul may increase and lift itself up in the free air and with much spirit; sometimes travel and a change of country will give vigor, and marriage and more liberal drink. Sometimes even to the point of drunkenness, not that it drowns us, but that it depresses us: for it washes away cares and moves the mind from below, and, as with certain diseases, so it heals sadness.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mental-health","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000541","text":"You have, dearest Serene, things that can protect tranquility, things that restore it, things that resist creeping escapes. Be it known, however, that none of these things is sufficient for those who hold a feeble matter, unless a constant concern surrounds the slipping mind.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000542","text":"Nihil perpetuum, pauca diuturna sunt; aliud alio modo fragile est, rerum exitus variantur, ceterum quicquid coepit et desinit.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000543","text":"Magna servitus est magna fortuna.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000544","text":"Growth is slow but collapse is rapid.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000545","text":"Religion is regarded by the common people as true, by the wise as false, and by rulers as useful.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000546","text":"Luck is what happens when preparation meets opportunity.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000547","text":"Servare cives, major est virtus patriae patri.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000548","text":"[Seneca] would have denounced the opinion to which most philosophers, tacitly or otherwise, have come round in the last half-century, that it is no part of the business of philosophy to turn people into better persons, as tantamount to desertion or lèse-majesté.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000549","text":"[Seneca’s] tremendous faith in philosophy … was grounded on a belief that her end was the practical one of curing souls, of bringing peace and order to the feverish minds of men pursuing the wrong aims in life.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000550","text":"Seneca's virtue shows forth so live and vigorous in his writings, and the defense is so clear there against some of these imputations, as that of his wealth and excessive spending, that I would not believe any testimony to the contrary.","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000551","text":"Caligula used to say that Seneca, who was very popular just then, composed \"mere school exercises,\" and that he was \"sand without lime.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000552","text":"Essays by Seneca at Quotidiana.org","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000553","text":"Seneca's essays in English (at Stoics.com)","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000554","text":"Original texts of Seneca's works at The Latin Library","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000555","text":"Modern Commentaries on Seneca's Epistulae Morales","author":"Seneca","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000556","text":"To the rational being only the irrational is unendurable, but the rational is endurable.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000557","text":"\"But to be hanged—is that not unendurable?\" Even so, when a man feels that it is reasonable, he goes off and hangs himself.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000558","text":"Yet God hath not only granted these faculties, by which we may bear every event without being depressed or broken by it, but like a good prince and a true father, hath placed their exercise above restraint, compulsion, or hindrance, and wholly within our own control.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000559","text":"In a word, neither death, nor exile, nor pain, nor anything of this kind is the real cause of our doing or not doing any action, but our inward opinions and principles.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000560","text":"Reason is not measured by size or height, but by principle.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000561","text":"O slavish man! will you not bear with your own brother, who has God for his Father, as being a son from the same stock, and of the same high descent? But if you chance to be placed in some superior station, will you presently set yourself up for a tyrant?","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000562","text":"When you close your doors, and make darkness within, remember never to say that you are alone, for you are not alone; nay, God is within, and your genius is within. And what need have they of light to see what you are doing?","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000563","text":"No thing great is created suddenly, any more than a bunch of grapes or a fig. If you tell me that you desire a fig, I answer you that there must be time. Let it first blossom, then bear fruit, then ripen.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000564","text":"Any one thing in the creation is sufficient to demonstrate a Providence to an humble and grateful mind.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:gratitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000565","text":"Were I a nightingale, I would act the part of a nightingale; were I a swan, the part of a swan.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000566","text":"Since it is Reason which shapes and regulates all other things, it ought not itself to be left in disorder.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000567","text":"If what the philosophers say be true,—that all men's actions proceed from one source; that as they assent from a persuasion that a thing is so, and dissent from a persuasion that it is not, and suspend their judgment from a persuasion that it is uncertain,—so likewise they seek a thing from a persuasion that it is for their advantage.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000568","text":"Practice yourself, for heaven's sake, in little things; and thence proceed to greater.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000569","text":"It is unlikely that the good of a snail should reside in its shell: so is it likely that the good of a man should?","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000570","text":"Who are those people by whom you wish to be admired? Are they not these about whom you are in the habit of saying that they are mad? What then? Do you wish to be admired by the mad?","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000571","text":"If it is my interest to have a farm, it is my interest to take it away from my neighbour; if it is my interest to have a cloak, it is my interest also to steal it from a bath. This is the source of wars, seditions, tyrannies, plots.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000572","text":"It is difficulties that show what men are.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000573","text":"If we are not stupid or insincere when we say that the good or ill of man lies within his own will, and that all beside is nothing to us, why are we still troubled?","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000574","text":"\"If the room is smoky, if only moderately, I will stay; if there is too much smoke I will go. Remember this, keep a firm hold on it, the door is always open.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000575","text":"In theory there is nothing to hinder our following what we are taught; but in life there are many things to draw us aside.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000576","text":"Appearances to the mind are of four kinds. Things either are what they appear to be; or they neither are, nor appear to be; or they are, and do not appear to be; or they are not, and yet appear to be. Rightly to aim in all these cases is the wise man's task.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000577","text":"For human beings, the measure of every action is the impression of the senses.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000578","text":"The essence of the good is a certain kind of moral purpose, and that of the evil is a certain kind of moral purpose.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000579","text":"For what is lacking now is not quibbles; nay, the books of the Stoics are full of quibbles","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000580","text":"For it is not death or pain that is to be feared, but the fear of pain or death.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000581","text":"For what is a child? Ignorance. What is a child? Want of instruction. For where a child has knowledge, he is no worse than we are.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000582","text":"For on these matters we should not trust the multitude who say that none ought to be educated but the free, but rather to philosophers, who say that the educated alone are free.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:relationships","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000583","text":"Show that you know this only—how you may never either fail to get what you desire or fall into what you avoid.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000584","text":"Materials are indifferent, but the use which we make of them is not a matter of indifference.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000585","text":"Although life is a matter of indifference, the use which you make of it is not a matter of indifference.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000586","text":"Shall I show you the sinews of a philosopher? \"What sinews are those?\" — A will undisappointed; evils avoided; powers daily exercised, careful resolutions; unerring decisions.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000587","text":"Look now, this is the starting point of philosophy: the recognition that different people have conflicting opinions, the rejection of mere opinion so that it comes to be viewed with mistrust, an investigation of opinion to determine whether it is rightly held, and the discovery of a standard of judgement, comparable to the balance that we have devised for the determining of weights, or the carpenter's rule for determining whether things are straight or crooked.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000588","text":"When I see someone in anxiety, I say to myself, What can it be that this fellow wants? For if he did not want something that was outside of his control, how could he still remain in anxiety?","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mental-health","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000589","text":"Why, then, do we wonder any longer that, although in material things we are thoroughly experienced, nevertheless in our actions we are dejected, unseemly, worthless, cowardly, unwilling to stand the strain, utter failures one and all?","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000590","text":"Be bold to look towards God and say, \"Use me henceforward for whatever you want; I am of one mind with you; I am yours; I refuse nothing that seems good to you; lead me where you will; wrap me in what clothes you will.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:courage","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000591","text":"What is the first business of one who practices philosophy? To get rid of self-conceit. For it is impossible for anyone to begin to learn that which he thinks he already knows.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000592","text":"Every habit and faculty is confirmed and strengthened by the corresponding actions, that of walking by walking, that of running by running.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000593","text":"If you would be a good reader, read; if a writer, write.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000594","text":"Whatever you would make habitual, practice it; and if you would not make a thing habitual, do not practice it, but accustom yourself to something else.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000595","text":"Be not swept off your feet by the vividness of the impression, but say, \"Impression, wait for me a little. Let me see what you are and what you represent. Let me try you.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000596","text":"Show me someone who is ill and yet happy, in danger and yet happy, dying and yet happy, exiled and yet happy. Show me such a person; by the gods, how greatly I long to see a Stoic!","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000597","text":"The propositions which are true and evident must of necessity be employed even by those who contradict them","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000598","text":"Some of their faults people readily admit, but others not so readily.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000599","text":"Who is not tempted by attractive and wide-awake children to join their sports, and crawl on all fours with them, and talk baby talk with them?","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000600","text":"Know, first, who you are, and then adorn yourself accordingly.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000601","text":"Why, what is weeping and sighing? A judgement. What is misfortune? A judgement. What are strife, disagreement, fault-finding, accusing, impiety, foolishness? They are all judgements.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000602","text":"What should a philosopher say, then, in the face of each of the hardships of life? \"It was for this that I've been training myself, it was for this that I was practising.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000603","text":"Two principles we should always have ready — that there is nothing good or evil save in the will; and that we are not to lead events, but to follow them.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000604","text":"In each separate thing that you do consider the matters which come first, and those which follow after, and only then approach the thing itself.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000605","text":"Do you suppose that you can do the things you do now, and yet be a philosopher? Do you suppose that you can eat in the same fashion, drink in the same fashion, give way to anger and to irritation, just as you do now?","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000606","text":"For he who is unmusical is a child in music; he who is without letters is a child in learning; he who is untaught, is a child in life.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000607","text":"Τίς εἶναι θέλεις, σαυτῷ πρῶτον εἰπέ: εἶθ' οὕτως ποίει ἃ ποιεῖς.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000608","text":"Don't you know that a good and excellent person does nothing for the sake of appearances, but only for the sake of having acted right?","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000609","text":"For this too is a very pleasant strand woven into the Cynic's pattern of life; he must needs be flogged like an ass, and while he is being flogged he must love the men who flog him, as though he were the father or brother of them all.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000610","text":"Let not that which in the case of another is contrary to nature become an evil for you; for you are born not to be humiliated along with others, nor to share in their misfortunes, but to share in their good fortune. If, however, someone is unfortunate, remember that his misfortune concerns himself. For God made all mankind to be happy, to be serene.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000611","text":"But tell me this: did you never love any person... were you never commanded by the person beloved to do something which you did not wish to do? Have you never flattered your little slave? Have you never kissed her feet? And yet if any man compelled you to kiss Caesar's feet, you would think it an insult and excessive tyranny. What else then is slavery?","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000612","text":"For what is it that everyone is seeking? To live securely, to be happy, to do everything as they wish to do, not to be hindered, not to be subject to compulsion.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000613","text":"For freedom is not acquired by satisfying yourself with what you desire, but by destroying your desire.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000614","text":"Little is needed to ruin and upset everything, only a slight aberration from reason.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000615","text":"Some things are in our control and others not. Things in our control are opinion, pursuit, desire, aversion, and, in a word, whatever are our own actions. Things not in our control are body, property, reputation, command, and, in one word, whatever are not our own actions. (1).","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000616","text":"Men are disturbed, not by things, but by the principles and notions which they form concerning things. (5). (Enchiridion 5)","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000617","text":"It is the act of an ill-instructed man to blame others for his own bad condition; it is the act of one who has begun to be instructed, to lay the blame on himself; and of one whose instruction is completed, neither to blame another, nor himself. (5) [tr. George Long (1888)].","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000618","text":"Ἐφ' ἑκάστου τῶν προσπιπτόντων μέμνησο ἐπιστρέφων ἐπὶ σεαυτὸν ζητεῖν, τίνα δύναμιν ἔχεις πρὸς τὴν χρῆσιν αὐτοῦ. ἐὰν καλὸν ἴδῃς ἢ καλήν, εὑρήσεις δύναμιν πρὸς ταῦτα ἐγκράτειαν· ἐὰν πόνος προσφέρηται, εὑρήσεις καρτερίαν· ἂν λοιδορία, εὑρήσεις ἀνεξικακίαν. καὶ οὕτως ἐθιζόμενόν σε οὐ συναρπάσουσιν αἱ φαντασίαι.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000619","text":"Remember that you ought to behave in life as you would at a banquet. As something is being passed around it comes to you; stretch out your hand, take a portion of it politely. It passes on; do not detain it. Or it has not come to you yet; do not project your desire to meet it, but wait until it comes in front of you. So act toward children, so toward a wife, so toward office, so toward wealth. (15).","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000620","text":"Remember that it is not he who gives abuse or blows who affronts, but the view we take of these things as insulting. When, therefore, any one provokes you, be assured that it is your own opinion which provokes you. (20).","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000621","text":"If a person gave your body to any stranger he met on his way, you would certainly be angry. And do you feel no shame in handing over your own mind to be confused and mystified by anyone who happens to verbally attack you? (28) [tr. Elizabeth Carter]","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000622","text":"If a man has reported to you, that a certain person speaks ill of you, do not make any defense (answer) to what has been told you: but reply, The man did not know the rest of my faults, for he would not have mentioned these only. (33) [tr. George Long (1888)].","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000623","text":"When you do anything from a clear judgment that it ought to be done, never shun the being seen to do it, even though the world should make a wrong supposition about it; for, if you don't act right, shun the action itself; but, if you do, why are you afraid of those who censure you wrongly? (35).","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000624","text":"Everything has two handles, the one by which it may be carried, the other by which it cannot. If your brother acts unjustly, don't lay hold on the action by the handle of his injustice, for by that it cannot be carried; but by the opposite, that he is your brother, that he was brought up with you; and thus you will lay hold on it, as it is to be carried. (43).","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000625","text":"These reasonings are unconnected: \"I am richer than you, therefore I am better\"; \"I am more eloquent than you, therefore I am better.\" The connection is rather this: \"I am richer than you, therefore my property is greater than yours;\" \"I am more eloquent than you, therefore my style is better than yours.\" But you, after all, are neither property nor style. (44).","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000626","text":"Does anyone bathe in a mighty little time? Don't say that he does it ill, but in a mighty little time. Does anyone drink a great quantity of wine? Don't say that he does ill, but that he drinks a great quantity. For, unless you perfectly understand the principle from which anyone acts, how should you know if he acts ill? Thus you will not run the hazard of assenting to any appearances but such as you fully comprehend. (45).","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000627","text":"Upon all occasions we ought to have these maxims ready at hand:","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000628","text":"You are a little soul carrying a corpse around, as Epictetus used to say.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000629","text":"We ought neither to fasten our ship to one small anchor nor our life to a single hope.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000630","text":"Those of our pleasures which come most rarely give the greatest delight.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000631","text":"No man is free who is not master of himself.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000632","text":"The greater the difficulty, the more glory in surmounting it. Skilful pilots gain their reputation from storms and tempests.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000633","text":"Other people’s views and troubles can be contagious. Don’t sabotage yourself by unwittingly adopting negative, unproductive attitudes through your associations with others.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000634","text":"You become what you give your attention to.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000635","text":"Tentative efforts lead to tentative outcomes. Therefore, give yourself fully to your endeavors. Decide to construct your character through excellent actions, and determine to pay the price for a worthy goal. The trials you encounter will introduce you to your strengths. Remain steadfast... and one day you will build something that endures, something worthy of your potential.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:resilience","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000636","text":"Don't explain your philosophy. Embody it.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000637","text":"The manner in which Epictetus, Montaigne, and Salomon de Tultie wrote, is the most usual, the most suggestive, the most remembered, and the oftener quoted; because it is entirely composed of thoughts born from the common talk of life.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000638","text":"The phenomenon of the will [in Epictetus ] [...] a different mental ability whose chief characteristic is that it speaks an imperative even when it commands nothing but our ability to think. The goal is to annihilate reality insofar it concerns me.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000639","text":"Epictetus is a thinker we cannot forget, once we have encountered him, because he gets under our skin. He provokes and he irritates, but he deals so trenchantly with life’s everyday challenges that no one who knows his work can simply dismiss it as theoretically invalid or practically useless. In times of stress, as modern Epictetans have attested, his recommendations make their presence felt.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000640","text":"Epictetus at The Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000641","text":"Discourses at The Internet Classics Archive","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000642","text":"Epictetus at Theosophy Library Online","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000643","text":"The Encheiridion online","author":"Epictetus","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000644","text":"Happiness is a good flow of life.","author":"Zeno of Citium","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000645","text":"No one entrusts a secret to a drunken man; but one will entrust a secret to a good man; therefore, the good man will not get drunk.","author":"Zeno of Citium","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000646","text":"(The end is) life in agreement with nature","author":"Zeno of Citium","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000647","text":"Love is a God, who cooperates in securing the safety of the city.","author":"Zeno of Citium","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000648","text":"All the good are friends of one another.","author":"Zeno of Citium","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000649","text":"We have two ears and one mouth, so we should listen more than we say.","author":"Zeno of Citium","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000650","text":"No evil is honorable; but death is honorable; therefore death is not evil.","author":"Zeno of Citium","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000651","text":"A bad feeling is a commotion of the mind repugnant to reason, and against nature.","author":"Zeno of Citium","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000652","text":"That which exercises reason is more excellent than that which does not exercise reason; there is nothing more excellent than the universe, therefore the universe exercises reason.","author":"Zeno of Citium","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000653","text":"If melodiously piping flutes sprang from the olive, would you doubt that a knowledge of flute-playing resided in the olive? And what if plane trees bore harps which gave forth rhythmical sounds? Clearly you would think in the same way that the art of music was possessed by plane trees. Why, then, seeing that the universe gives birth to beings that are animate and wise, should it not be considered animate and wise itself?","author":"Zeno of Citium","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000654","text":"Man conquers the world by conquering himself","author":"Zeno of Citium","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000655","text":"Zeno of Cittium - founder of Stoicism by Paul Harrison.","author":"Zeno of Citium","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000656","text":"Shipwrecks occur in other of Verne's tales; but this is his only story devoted wholly to such a disaster.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000657","text":"In it the author has gathered all the tragedy, the mystery, and the suffering possible to the sea.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000658","text":"All the various forms of disaster, all the possibilities of horror, the depths of shame and agony, are heaped upon these unhappy voyagers.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000659","text":"The accumulation is mathematically complete and emotionally unforgettable.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000660","text":"The tale has well been called the \"imperishable epic of shipwreck.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000661","text":"The idea of the book is said to have originated in the celebrated French painting by Gericault, \"the Wreck of the Medusa,\" now in the Louvre gallery.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000662","text":"The Medusa was a French frigate wrecked off the coast of Africa in 1816.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000663","text":"Some of the survivors, escaping on a raft, were rescued by a passing ship after many days of torture.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000664","text":"Verne, however, seems also to have drawn upon the terrifying experiences of the British ship Sarah Sands in 1857, her story being fresh in the public mind at the time he wrote.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000665","text":"The Sarah Sands caught fire off the African coast while on a voyage to India carrying British troops.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000666","text":"Some of it did indeed explode, tearing a huge hole in the vessel's side.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000667","text":"A storm added to the terror, and the waters entering the breach caused by the explosion, combated with the fire.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000668","text":"After ten days of desperate struggle, the charred and sinking vessel reached a port.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000669","text":"The extreme length of life which Verne allows his people in their starving, thirsting condition is proven possible by medical science and recent \"fasting\"' experiments.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000670","text":"The dramatic climax of the tale wherein the castaways find fresh water in the ocean is based upon a fact, one of those odd geographical facts of which the author made such frequent, skillful and instructive use.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000671","text":"\"Michael Strogoff\" which, through its use as a stage play, has become one of the best known books of all the world, was first published in 1876.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000672","text":"Its vivid, powerful story has made it a favorite with every red-blooded reader.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000673","text":"Its two well-drawn female characters, the courageous heroine, and the stern, endurant, yearning mother, show how well Verne could depict the tenderer sex when he so willed.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:courage","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000674","text":"Though usually the rapid movement and adventure of his stories leave women in subordinate parts.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000675","text":"As to the picture drawn in \"Michael Strogoff\" of Russia and Siberia, it is at once instructive and sympathetic.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000676","text":"The horrors are not blinked at, yet neither is Russian patriotism ignored.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000677","text":"The loyalty of some of the Siberian exiles to their mother country is a side of life there which is too often ignored by writers who dwell only on the darker view.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000678","text":"The Czar, in our author's hands, becomes the hero figure to the erection of which French \"hero worship\" is ever prone.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000679","text":"The sarcasms thrown occasionally at the British newspaper correspondent of the story, show the changing attitude of Verne toward England, and reflect the French spirit of his day.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000680","text":"CHARLESTON, September 27, 1898.--It is high tide, and three o'clock in the afternoon when we leave the Battery quay; the ebb carries us off shore, and as Captain Huntly has hoisted both main and top sails, the northerly breeze drives the Chancellor briskly across the bay.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000681","text":"Fort Sumter ere long is doubled, the sweeping batteries of the mainland on our left are soon passed, and by four o'clock the rapid current of the ebbing tide has carried us through the harbor mouth.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000682","text":"But as yet we have not reached the open sea we have still to thread our way through the narrow channels which the surge has hollowed out amongst the sand-banks.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000683","text":"The captain takes a southwest course, rounding the lighthouse at the corner of the fort; the sails are closely trimmed; the last sandy point is safely coasted, and at length, at seven o'clock in the evening, we are out free upon the wide Atlantic.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000684","text":"The Chancellor is a fine square-rigged three-master, of 900 tons burden, and belongs to the wealthy Liverpool firm of Laird Brothers.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000685","text":"She is two years old, is sheathed and secured with copper, her decks being of teak, and the base of all her masts, except the mizzen, with all their fittings, being of iron.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000686","text":"She is registered first class, A1, and is now on her third voyage between Charleston and Liverpool.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000687","text":"I must now relate how it happens that I have taken my passage on board the Chancellor on her return voyage to England.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000688","text":"At present there is no direct steamship service between South Carolina and Great Britain, and all who wish to cross must go either northward to New York or southward to New Orleans.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000689","text":"One day, as I was loitering about the Charleston quays, my eye lighted on this vessel.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000690","text":"There was something about the Chancellor that pleased me, and a kind of involuntary impulse took me on board, where I found the internal arrangements perfectly comfortable.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000691","text":"Have I done right or wrong? Whether I shall have reason to regret my determination is a problem to be solved in the future. However, I will begin to record the incidents of our daily experience, dubious as I feel whether the lines of my chronicle will ever find a reader.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000692","text":"SEPTEMBER 28.--John Silas Huntly, the captain of the Chancellor, has the reputation of being a most experienced navigator of the Atlantic.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000693","text":"He is a Scotchman by birth, a native of Dundee, and is about fifty years of age.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000694","text":"He is of the middle height and slight build, and has a small head, which he has a habit of holding a little over his left shoulder.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000695","text":"I do not pretend to be much of a physiognomist, but I am inclined to believe that my few hours' acquaintance with our captain has given me considerable insight into his character.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000696","text":"I observed a certain heaviness and dejection about his whole carriage.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000697","text":"His wavering glances, the listless motion of his hands, and his slow, unsteady gait, all seem to me to indicate a weak and sluggish disposition.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000698","text":"He does not appear as though he could be energetic enough ever to be stubborn; he never frowns, sets his teeth, or clenches his fists.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000699","text":"There is something enigmatical about him; however, I shall study him closely, and do what I can to understand the man who, as commander of a vessel, should be to those around him \"second only to God.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000700","text":"Unless I am greatly mistaken there is another man on board who, if circumstances should require it, would take the more prominent position--I mean the mate.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000701","text":"I have hitherto, however, had so little opportunity of observing his character, that I must defer saying more about him at present.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000702","text":"Besides the captain and this mate, whose name is Robert Curtis, our crew consists of Walter, the lieutenant, the boatswain, and fourteen sailors, all English or Scotch, making eighteen altogether, a number quite sufficient for working a vessel of 900 tons burden.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000703","text":"Up to this time my sole experience of their capabilities is, that under the command of the mate, they brought us skillfully enough through the narrow channels of Charleston; and I have no reason to doubt that they are well up to their work.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000704","text":"My list of the ship's officials is incomplete unless I mention Hobart the steward and Jynxstrop the negro cook.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000705","text":"In addition to these, the Chancellor carries eight passengers, including myself.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000706","text":"Two days have elapsed and I have not even seen all the passengers.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000707","text":"Probably sea-sickness has prevented some of them from making an appearance at the common table.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000708","text":"One thing, however, I do know; namely, that there are two ladies occupying the stern cabin, the windows of which are in the aft-board of the vessel.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000709","text":"I have seen the ship's list, and subjoin a list of the passengers. They are as follows:","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000710","text":"Mr. and Mrs. Kear, Americans, of Buffalo. Miss Herbey, a young English lady, companion to Mrs. Kear. M. Letourneur and his son Andre, Frenchmen, of Havre. William Falsten, a Manchester engineer. John Ruby, a Cardiff merchant; and myself, J. R. Kazallon, of London.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000711","text":"SEPTEMBER 29.--Captain Huntly's bill of lading, that is to say, the document that describes the Chancellor's cargo and the conditions of transport, is couched in the following terms:","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000712","text":"I do hereby acknowledge that I have received from you, Messrs.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000713","text":"Laird Brothers, or to their order, or to their representatives, who shall on due delivery of the said freight pay me the sum of 2,000 L.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000714","text":"inclusive, according to the charter-party, and damages in addition, according to the usages and customs of the sea.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000715","text":"And for the fulfillment of the above covenant, I have pledged and do pledge my person, my property, and my interest in the vessel aforesaid, with all its appurtenances.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000716","text":"In witness whereof, I have signed three agreements all of the same purport, on the condition that when the terms of one are accomplished, the other two shall be absolutely null and void.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000717","text":"From the foregoing document it will be understood that the Chancellor is conveying 1,700 bales of cotton to Liverpool; that the shippers are Bronsfield, of Charleston, and the consignees are Laird Brothers of Liverpool.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000718","text":"The ship was constructed with the especial design of carrying cotton, and the entire hold, with the exception of a very limited space reserved for passenger's luggage, is closely packed with the bales.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000719","text":"SEPTEMBER 30 to October 6.--The Chancellor is a rapid sailer, and more than a match for many a vessel of the same dimensions.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000720","text":"She scuds along merrily in the freshening breeze, leaving in her wake, far as the eye can reach, a long white line of foam as well defined as a delicate strip of lace stretched upon an azure ground.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000721","text":"The Atlantic is not visited by many gales, and I have every reason to believe that the rolling and pitching of the vessel no longer incommode any of the passengers, who are all more or less accustomed to the sea.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000722","text":"A vacant seat at our table is now very rare; we are beginning to know something about each other, and our daily life, in consequence, is becoming somewhat less monotonous.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000723","text":"Letourneur, our French fellow-passenger, often has a chat with me.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000724","text":"He is a fine tall man, about fifty years of age, with white hair and a grizzly beard.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000725","text":"To say the truth, he looks older than he really is: his drooping head, his dejected manner, and his eye, ever and again suffused with tears, indicate that he is haunted by some deep and abiding sorrow.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000726","text":"He never laughs; he rarely even smiles, and then only on his son; his countenance ordinarily bearing a look of bitterness tempered by affection, while his general expression is one of caressing tenderness.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000727","text":"Letourneur is consuming himself by exaggerated reproaches on account of the infirmity of an afflicted son.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000728","text":"Andre Letourneur is about twenty years of age, with a gentle, interesting countenance, but, to the irrepressible grief of his father, is a hopeless cripple.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000729","text":"His left leg is miserably deformed, and he is quite unable to walk without the assistance of a stick.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000730","text":"M. Letourneur seems to have taken a peculiar fancy to myself, and constantly talks about Andre. This morning, in the course of conversation, I said:","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000731","text":"\"You have a good son, M. Letourneur. I have just been talking to him. He is a most intelligent young man.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000732","text":"\"Yes, Mr. Kazallon,\" replied M. Letourneur, brightening up into a smile, \"his afflicted frame contains a noble mind. He is like his mother, who died at his birth.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000733","text":"\"He is full of reverence and love for you, sir,\" I remarked.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000734","text":"\"Dear boy!\" muttered the father half to himself. \"Ah, Mr. Kazallon,\" he continued, \"you do not know what it is to a father to have a son a cripple, beyond hope of cure.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000735","text":"Letourneur,\" I answered, \"you take more than your share of the affliction which has fallen upon you and your son.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000736","text":"Andre is entitled to the very greatest commiseration no one can deny; but you should remember, that after all a physical infirmity is not so hard to bear as mental grief.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000737","text":"Now, I have watched your son pretty closely, and unless I am much mistaken there is nothing that troubles him so much as the sight of your own sorrow.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000738","text":"I have discovered that, in spite of his physical weakness, he delights in traveling; so for the last few years we have been constantly on the move.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000739","text":"We first went all over Europe, and are now returning from visiting the principal places in the United States.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000740","text":"I never allowed my son to go to college, but instructed him entirely myself, and these travels, I hope, will serve to complete his education.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000741","text":"He is very intelligent, and has a lively imagination, and I am sometimes tempted to hope that in contemplating the wonders of nature he forgets his own infirmity.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000742","text":"\"But,\" continued M. Letourneur, taking my hand, \"although, perhaps, HE may forget, I can never forget. Ah, sir, do you suppose that Andre can ever forgive his parents for bringing him into the world a cripple?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000743","text":"The remorse of the unhappy father was very distressing, and I was about to say a few kind words of sympathy when Andre himself made his appearance. M. Letourneur hastened toward him and assisted him up the few steep steps that led to the poop.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000744","text":"Letourneur's estimate of Captain Huntly's character very much coincides with my own, and that, like me, he is impressed with the man's undecided manner and sluggish appearance.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000745","text":"Like me, too, he has formed a very favorable opinion of Robert Curtis, the mate, a man of about thirty years of age, of great muscular power, with a frame and a will that seem ever ready for action.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000746","text":"He seems a kind-hearted fellow, too, and is always ready to assist and amuse young Letourneur, who evidently enjoys his company.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000747","text":"After he had scanned the weather and examined the trim of the sails, he joined our party and proceeded to give us some information about those of our fellow-passengers with whom at present we have made but slight acquaintance.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000748","text":"Kear, the American, who is accompanied by his wife, has made a large fortune in the petroleum springs in the United States.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000749","text":"He is a man of about fifty, a most uninteresting companion, being overwhelmed with a sense of his own wealth and importance, and consequently supremely indifferent to all around him.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000750","text":"His hands are always in his pockets, and the chink of money seems to follow him wherever he goes.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000751","text":"The wife is an insignificant, insipid woman, of about forty years of age.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000752","text":"She never reads, never talks, and I believe I am not wrong in saying, never thinks.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000753","text":"She seems to look without seeing, and listen without hearing, and her sole occupation consists in giving her orders to her companion, Miss Herbey, a young English girl of about twenty.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000754","text":"Her complexion is fair and her eyes deep blue, while her pleasing countenance is altogether free from that insignificance of feature which is not unfrequently alleged to be characteristic of English beauty.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:justice","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000755","text":"Her mouth would be charming if she ever smiled, but, exposed as she is to the ridiculous whims and fancies of a capricious mistress, her lips rarely relax from their ordinary grave expression.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000756","text":"Yet, humiliating as her position must be, she never utters a word of open complaint, but quietly and gracefully performs her duties, accepting without a murmur the paltry salary which the bumptious petroleum-merchant condescends to allow her.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000757","text":"The Manchester engineer, William Falsten, looks like a thorough Englishman.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000758","text":"He has the management of some extensive hydraulic works in South Carolina, and is now on his way to Europe to obtain some improved apparatus, and more especially to visit the mines worked by centrifugal force, belonging to the firm of Messrs.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000759","text":"He is forty-five years of age, with all his interests so entirely absorbed by his machinery that he seems to have neither a thought nor a care beyond his mechanical calculations.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000760","text":"Once let him engage you in conversation, and there is no chance of escape; you have no help for it but to listen as patiently as you can until he has completed the explanation of his designs.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000761","text":"Without any originality or magnanimity in his composition, he has spent twenty years of his life in mere buying and selling, and as he has generally contrived to do business at a profit, he has realized a considerable fortune.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000762","text":"What he is going to do with the money, he does not seem able to say: his ideas do not go beyond retail trade, his mind having been so long closed to all other impressions that it appears incapable of thought or reflection on any subject besides.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000763","text":"OCTOBER 7.--This is the tenth day since we left Charleston, and I should think our progress has been very rapid.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000764","text":"Robert Curtis, the mate, with whom I continue to have many a friendly chat, informed me that we could not be far off the Bermudas; the ship's bearings, he said, were lat.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000765","text":"so that he had every reason to believe that we should sight St.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000766","text":"\"The Bermudas!\" I exclaimed. \"But how is it we are off the Bermudas? I should have thought that a vessel sailing from Charleston to Liverpool, would have kept northward, and have followed the track of the Gulf Stream.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000767","text":"\"Yes, indeed, sir,\" replied Curtis, \"that is the usual course; but you see that this time the captain hasn't chosen to take it.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000768","text":"\"That's not for me to say, sir; he ordered us eastward, and eastward we go.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000769","text":"Curtis acknowledged that he had already pointed out what an unusual route they were taking, but that the captain had said that he was quite aware what he was about.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000770","text":"The mate made no further remark; but the knit of his brow, as he passed his hand mechanically across his forehead, made me fancy that he was inclined to speak out more strongly.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000771","text":"\"All very well, Curtis,\" I said, \"but I don't know what to think about trying new routes. Here we are at the 7th of October, and if we are to reach Europe before the bad weather sets in, I should suppose there is not a day to be lost.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000772","text":"Struck by his manner, I ventured to add, \"Do you mind, Curtis, giving me your honest opinion of Captain Huntly?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000773","text":"He hesitated a moment, and then replied shortly, \"He is my captain, sir.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000774","text":"This evasive answer of course put an end to any further interrogation on my part.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000775","text":"At about three o'clock the look-out man sung out that there was land to windward, and descried what seemed as if it might be a line of smoke in the northeast horizon.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000776","text":"Letourneur and his son, and we could then distinctly make out the low group of the Bermudas, encircled by their formidable chain of breakers.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000777","text":"\"There,\" said Andre Letourneur to me, as we stood gazing at the distant land, \"there lies the enchanted archipelago, sung by your poet Moore.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000778","text":"The exile Waller, too, as long ago as 1643, wrote an enthusiastic panegyric on the islands, and I have been told that at one time English ladies would wear no other bonnets than such as were made of the leaves of the Bermuda palm.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000779","text":"\"Yes,\" I replied, \"the Bermudas were all the rage in the seventeenth century, although latterly they have fallen into comparative oblivion.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000780","text":"Andre,\" interposed Curtis, who had as usual joined our party, \"that although poets may rave, and be as enthusiastic as they like about these islands, sailors will tell a different tale.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000781","text":"The hidden reefs that lie in a semicircle about two or three leagues from shore make the attempt to land a very dangerous piece of business.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000782","text":"Let the natives boast as they will about their splendid climate, they are visited by the most frightful hurricanes.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000783","text":"They get the fag-end of the storms that rage over the Antilles; and the fag-end of a storm is like the tail of a whale; it's just the strongest bit of it.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000784","text":"I don't think you'll find a sailor listening much to your poets--your Moores, and your Wallers.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000785","text":"Curtis,\" said Andre, smiling, \"but poets are like proverbs; you can always find one to contradict another.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000786","text":"Although Waller and Moore have chosen to sing the praises of the Bermudas, it has been supposed that Shakspeare was depicting them in the terrible scenes that are found in 'The Tempest.'\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000787","text":"I may mention that there was not another of our fellow-passengers who took the trouble to come on deck and give a glance at this strange cluster of islands.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000788","text":"Miss Herbey, it is true, was making an attempt to join us, but she had barely reached the poop, when Mrs.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000789","text":"Kear's languid voice was heard recalling her for some trifling service to her side.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000790","text":"OCTOBER 8 to October 13.--The wind is blowing hard from the northeast, and the Chancellor, under low-reefed top-sail and fore-sail, and laboring against a heavy sea, has been obliged to be brought ahull.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000791","text":"The joists and girders all creak again until one's teeth are set on edge.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000792","text":"I am the only passenger not remaining below; but I prefer being on deck notwithstanding the driving rain, fine as dust, which penetrates to the very skin.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000793","text":"We have been driven along in this fashion for the best part of two days; the \"stiffish breeze\" has gradually freshened into \"a gale\"; the topgallants have been lowered, and, as I write, the wind is blowing with a velocity of fifty or sixty miles an hour.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000794","text":"Although the Chancellor has many good points, her drift is considerable, and we have been carried far to the south; we can only guess at our precise position, as the cloudy atmosphere entirely precludes us from taking the sun's altitude.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000795","text":"All along, throughout this period, my fellow-passengers are totally ignorant of the extraordinary course that we are taking.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000796","text":"I was alone with Robert Curtis to-day upon the poop, and could not help saying to him, \"Curtis, is your captain mad?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000797","text":"\"Perhaps, sir, I might be allowed to ask what YOU think upon that matter,\" was his cautious reply.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000798","text":"\"Well, to say the truth,\" I answered. \"I can hardly tell; but I confess there is every now and then a wandering in his eye, and an odd look on his face that I do not like. Have you ever sailed with him before?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000799","text":"\"No; this is our first voyage together. Again last night I spoke to him about the route we were taking, but he only said he knew all about it, and that it was all right.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000800","text":"\"What do Lieutenant Walter and your boatswain think of it all?\" I inquired.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000801","text":"\"Think; why, they think just the same as I do,\" replied the mate; \"but if the captain chooses to take the ship to China we should obey his orders.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000802","text":"\"But surely,\" I exclaimed, \"there must be some limit to your obedience! Suppose the man is actually mad, what then?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000803","text":"\"If he should be mad enough, Mr. Kazallon, to bring the vessel into any real danger, I shall know what to do.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000804","text":"Matters, however, have taken a different turn to what I bargained for when I took my passage on board the Chancellor.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000805","text":"As I have already said, the ship under her large low-reefed top-sail and fore stay-sail has been brought ahull, that is to say, she copes directly with the wind, by presenting her broad bows to the sea; and so we go on still drift, drift, continually to the south.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000806","text":"How southerly our course has been is very apparent; for upon the night of the 11th we fairly entered upon that portion of the Atlantic which is known as the Sargasso Sea.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:justice","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000807","text":"An extensive tract of water is this, inclosed by the warm current of the Gulf Stream, and thickly covered with the wrack, called by the Spaniards \"sargasso,\" the abundance of which so seriously impeded the progress of Columbus's vessel on his first voyage.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000808","text":"Each morning at daybreak the Atlantic has presented an aspect so remarkable, that at my solicitation, M.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000809","text":"Letourneur and his son have ventured upon deck to witness the unusual spectacle.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000810","text":"The squally gusts make the metal shrouds vibrate like harp-strings; and unless we were on our guard to keep our clothes wrapped tightly to us, they would have been torn off our backs in shreds.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000811","text":"The scene presented to our eyes is one of strangest interest.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000812","text":"The sea, carpeted thickly with masses of prolific fucus, is a vast unbroken plain of vegetation, through which the vessel makes her way as a plow.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000813","text":"OCTOBER 14.--At last we are free from the sea of vegetation, the boisterous gale has moderated into a steady breeze, the sun is shining brightly, the weather is warm and genial, and thus, two reefs in her top-sails, briskly and merrily sails the Chancellor.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000814","text":"Under conditions so favorable, we have been able to take the ship's bearings: our latitude, we find, is 21 deg. 33' N., our longitude, 50 deg. 17' W.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000815","text":"Incomprehensible altogether is the conduct of Captain Huntly.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000816","text":"Here we are, already more than ten degrees south of the point from which we started, and yet still we are persistently following a southeasterly course!","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000817","text":"I cannot bring myself to the conclusion that the man is mad.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000818","text":"I have had various conversations with him: he has always spoken rationally and sensibly.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000819","text":"Perhaps his case is one of those in which insanity is partial, and where the mania is of a character which extends only to the matters connected with his profession.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000820","text":"Last evening I went to my cabin about eight o'clock, and after an hour's reading by the light of my cabin-lamp, I retired to my berth and was soon asleep.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000821","text":"Some hours later I was aroused by an unaccustomed noise on deck.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000822","text":"There were heavy footsteps hurrying to and fro, and the voices of the men were loud and eager, as if the crew were agitated by some strange disturbance.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000823","text":"My first impression was, that some tacking had been ordered which rendered it needful to fathom the yards; but the vessel continuing to lie to starboard convinced me that this was not the origin of the commotion.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000824","text":"I was curious to know the truth, and made all haste I could to go on deck; but before I was ready, the noise had ceased.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000825","text":"I heard Captain Huntly return to his cabin, and accordingly I retired again to my own berth.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000826","text":"Whatever may have been the meaning of the maneuver, I cannot tell; it did not seem to result in any improvement in the ship's pace; still it must be owned there was not much wind to speed us along.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000827","text":"At six o'clock this morning I mounted the poop and made as keen a scrutiny as I could of everything on board.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000828","text":"The Chancellor was running on the larboard tack, and carried low-sails, top-sails, and gallant-sails.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000829","text":"Well braced she was; and under a fresh, but not uneasy breeze, was making no less than eleven knots an hour.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000830","text":"The young man enjoyed the early morning air, laden with its briny fragrance, and I assisted him to mount the poop.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000831","text":"In answer to my inquiry as to whether they had been disturbed by any bustle in the night, Andre replied that he did not wake at all, and had heard nothing.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000832","text":"\"I am glad, my boy,\" said the father, \"that you have slept so soundly.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000833","text":"It must have been about three o'clock this morning, and it seemed to me as though they were shouting.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000834","text":"I thought I heard them say; 'Here, quick, look to the hatches!' but as nobody was called up, I presumed that nothing serious was the matter.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000835","text":"As he spoke I cast my eye at the panel-slides, which fore and aft of the main-mast open into the hold.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000836","text":"They seemed to be all close as usual, but I now observed for the first time that they were covered with heavy tarpauling.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000837","text":"Wondering in my own mind what could be the reason for these extra precautions I did not say anything to M.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000838","text":"Letourneur, but determined to wait until the mate should come on watch, when he would doubtless give me, I thought, an explanation of the mystery.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000839","text":"The sun rose gloriously, with every promise of a fine dry day.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000840","text":"The waning moon was yet above the western horizon, for as it still wants three days to her last quarter she does not set until 10:57 A.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000841","text":"On consulting my almanac, I find that there will be a new moon on the 24th, and that on that day, little as it may affect us here in mid-ocean, the phenomenon of the high syzygian tides will take place on the shores of every continent and island.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000842","text":"Letourneur and Andre went below for a cup of tea, and I remained on the poop alone.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000843","text":"As I expected, Curtis appeared, that he might relieve Lieutenant Walter of the watch.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000844","text":"I advanced to meet him, but before he even wished me good morning, I saw him cast a quick and searching glance upon the deck, and then, with a slightly contracted brow, proceed to examine the state of the weather and the trim of the sails.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000845","text":"\"I have seen nothing of him,\" answered the lieutenant; \"is there anything fresh up?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000846","text":"They then conversed for a few moments in an undertone, and I could see that Walter by his gesture gave a negative answer to some question which the mate had asked him. \"Send me the boatswain, Walter,\" said Curtis aloud as the lieutenant moved away.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000847","text":"The boatswain immediately appeared, and another conversation was carried on in whispers.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000848","text":"The man repeatedly shook his head as he replied to Curtis's inquiries, and then, in obedience to orders, called the men who were on watch, and made them plentifully water the tarpauling that covered the great hatchway.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000849","text":"Curious to fathom the mystery I went up to Curtis and began to talk with him upon ordinary topics, hoping that he would himself introduce the subject that was uppermost in my mind; finding, however, that he did not allude to it, I asked him point blank:","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000850","text":"\"What was it?\" I repeated. \"M. Letourneur and myself were both of us disturbed by a very unusual commotion overhead.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000851","text":"\"Oh, a mere nothing,\" he said at length; \"the man at the helm had made a false move, and we had to pipe hands to brace the ship a bit; but it was soon all put to rights. It was nothing, nothing at all.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:justice","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000852","text":"I said no more; but I can not resist the impression that Robert Curtis has not acted with me in his usual straight-forward manner.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000853","text":"OCTOBER 15 to October 18.--The wind is still in the northeast.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000854","text":"There is no change in the Chancellor's course, and to an unprejudiced eye all would appear to be going on as usual.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000855","text":"But I have an uneasy consciousness that something is not quite right.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000856","text":"Why should the hatchways be so hermetically closed as though a mutinous crew was imprisoned between decks?","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000857","text":"I can not help thinking too that there is something in the sailors so constantly standing in groups and breaking off their talk so suddenly whenever we approach; and several times I have caught the word \"hatches\" which arrested M.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000858","text":"On the 15th, while I was walking on the forecastle, I overheard one of the sailors, a man named Owen, say to his mates:","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000859","text":"\"Now I just give you all warning that I am not going to wait until the last minute. Everyone for himself, say I.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000860","text":"\"Pshaw!\" said Owen, \"do you suppose that longboats were only made for porpoises?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000861","text":"Something at that moment occurred to interrupt the conversation, and I heard no more.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000862","text":"It occurred to me whether there was not some conspiracy among the crew, of which probably Curtis had already detected the symptoms.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000863","text":"I am quite aware that some sailors are most rebelliously disposed, and required to be ruled with a rod of iron.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000864","text":"Captain Huntly is undoubtedly laboring under strong nervous excitement; and M.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000865","text":"Letourneur has more than once remarked how silent he has become at meal-times; for although Curtis continually endeavors to start some subject of general interest, yet neither Mr.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000866","text":"Ruby are the men to take it up, and consequently the conversation flags hopelessly, and soon drops.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000867","text":"The passengers too are now, with good cause, beginning to murmur at the length of the voyage, and Mr.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000868","text":"Kear, who considers that the very elements ought to yield to his convenience, lets the captain know by his consequential and haughty manner that he holds him responsible for the delay.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000869","text":"The tarpaulins on the hatches have thus been kept continually wet, so that their close and heavy texture is rendered quite impervious to the air.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000870","text":"The Chancellor's pumps afford a copious supply of water, so that I should not suppose that even the daintiest and most luxurious craft belonging to an aristocratic yacht club was ever subject to a more thorough scouring.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000871","text":"The sun had scarcely risen, and the air was fresh and cool, in strange contrast to the heat which below the poop had been quite oppressive.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000872","text":"A great sheet of water, supplied continuously by the pumps, was rolling in tiny wavelets, and escaping now to starboard, now to larboard through the scupper-holes.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000873","text":"After watching the men for a while as they ran about bare-footed, I could not resist the desire to join them, so taking off my shoes and stockings, I proceeded to dabble in the flowing water.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000874","text":"Great was my amazement to find the deck perfectly hot to my feet! Curtis heard my exclamation of surprise, and before I could put my thoughts into words, said:","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000875","text":"OCTOBER 19.--Everything, then, is clear. The uneasiness of the crew, their frequent conferences, Owen's mysterious words, the constant scourings of the deck and the oppressive heat of the cabins which had been noticed even by my fellow-passengers, all are explained.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000876","text":"I shivered with a thrill of horror; a calamity the most terrible that can befall a voyager stared me in the face, and it was some seconds before I could recover sufficient composure to inquire when the fire was first discovered.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","audience:recovery","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000877","text":"\"Six days ago!\" I exclaimed; \"why, then, it was that night.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000878","text":"\"Yes,\" he said, interrupting me; \"it was the night you heard the disturbance upon deck.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000879","text":"The men on watch noticed a slight smoke issuing from the large hatchway and immediately called Captain Huntly and myself.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000880","text":"We found beyond all doubt, that the cargo was on fire, and what was worse, that there was no possibility of getting at the seat of the combustion.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000881","text":"Why, we took the only precaution that was practicable under the circumstances, and resolved most carefully to exclude every breath of air from penetrating into the hold.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000882","text":"I thought that the fire was stifled; but during the last three days there is every reason to make us know that it has been gaining strength.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000883","text":"Do what we will, the deck gets hotter and hotter, and unless it were kept constantly wet, it would be unbearable to the feet.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000884","text":"It is better that you should know it.\" I listened in silence.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000885","text":"I was now fully aroused to the gravity of the situation and thoroughly comprehended how we were in the very face of a calamity which it seemed that no human power could avert.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000886","text":"\"Do you know what has caused the fire?\" I presently inquired.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000887","text":"\"It probably arose,\" he answered, \"from the spontaneous combustion of the cotton.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000888","text":"Unless the cotton is perfectly dry when it is shipped, its confinement in a damp or ill-ventilated hold will sometimes cause it to ignite; and I have no doubt it is this that has brought about our misfortune.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000889","text":"\"But after all,\" I said, \"the cause matters very little. Is there no remedy? Is there nothing to be done?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000890","text":"\"As I told you before, we have adopted the only possible measure within our power to check the fire.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000891","text":"During the night, I had the deck bored in various places and water poured down through the holes; but that again seemed of no use.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000892","text":"There is only one thing that can be done; we must persevere in excluding most carefully every breath of outer air, so that perhaps the conflagration, deprived of oxygen, may smoulder itself out.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000893","text":"\"Yes; and that shows that in spite of all our care there is some aperture which we have not been able to discover, by which, somehow or other, air gets into the hold.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000894","text":"\"Have you ever heard of a vessel surviving such circumstances?\" I asked.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000895","text":"But, in such cases, of course the fire has been more or less under control throughout the voyage; with us, it is increasing day by day, and I tell you I am convinced there is an aperture somewhere which has escaped our notice.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000896","text":"\"But would it not be advisable for us to retrace our course, and make for the nearest land?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000897","text":"\"Walter and I, and the boatswain, are going to talk the matter over seriously with the captain to-day.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000898","text":"But, between ourselves, I have taken the responsibility upon myself; I have already changed the tack to the southwest; we are now straight before the wind, and consequently we are sailing toward the coast.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000899","text":"\"I need hardly ask,\" I added; \"whether any of the other passengers are at all aware of the imminent danger in which we are placed.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000900","text":"\"None of them,\" he said; \"not in the least; and I hope you will not enlighten them. We don't want terrified women and cowardly men to add to our embarrassment; the crew are under orders to keep a strict silence on the subject. Silence is indispensable.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000901","text":"I promised to keep the matter a profound secret, as I fully entered into Curtis's views as to the absolute necessity for concealment.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000902","text":"OCTOBER 20 and 21.--The Chancellor is now crowded with all the canvas she can carry, and at times her topmasts threaten to snap with the pressure.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000903","text":"But Curtis is ever on the alert; he never leaves his post beside the man at the helm, and without compromising the safety of the vessel, he contrives, by tacking to the breeze, to urge her on at her utmost speed.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000904","text":"All day long on the 20th the passengers were assembled on the poop.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000905","text":"Evidently they found the heat of the cabins painfully oppressive, and most of them lay stretched upon benches and quietly enjoyed the gentle rolling of the vessel.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000906","text":"The increasing heat of the deck did not reveal itself to their well-shod feet, and the constant scouring of the boards did not excite any suspicion in their torpid minds.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000907","text":"Letourneur, it is true, did express his surprise that the crew of an ordinary merchant vessel should be distinguished by such extraordinary cleanliness; but as I replied to him in a very casual tone, he passed no further remark.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000908","text":"The important consultation between captain, mate, lieutenant and boatswain has taken place.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000909","text":"He says that Huntly, the captain, is completely demoralized; he has lost all power and energy; and practically leaves the command of the ship to him.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000910","text":"It is now certain the fire is beyond control, and that sooner or later it will burst out in full violence.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000911","text":"The temperature of the crew's quarters has already become almost unbearable.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000912","text":"One solitary hope remains; it is that we may reach the shore before the final catastrophe occurs.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000913","text":"The Lesser Antilles are the nearest land; and although they are some five or six hundred miles away, if the wind remains northeast there is yet a chance of reaching them in time.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000914","text":"Carrying royals and studding-sails, the Chancellor during the last four-and-twenty hours has held a steady course.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000915","text":"Letourneur is the only one of all the passengers who has remarked the change of tack; Curtis, however, has set all speculation on his part at rest by telling him that he wanted to get ahead of the wind, and that he was tacking to the west to catch a favorable current.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000916","text":"To-day, the 21st, all has gone on as usual; and as far as the observation of the passengers has reached, the ordinary routine has been undisturbed.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000917","text":"Altogether, he considers it a good sign that the combustion has not betrayed itself by some external issue of smoke.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000918","text":"The day would have passed without any incident worth recording, if I had not chanced to overhear a fragment of a conversation which demonstrated that our situation, hitherto precarious enough, had now become most appalling.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000919","text":"As I was sitting on the poop, two of my fellow-passengers, Falsten, the engineer, and Ruby, the merchant, whom I had observed to be often in company, were engaged in conversation almost close to me.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000920","text":"What they said was evidently not intended for my hearing, but my attention was directed toward them by some very emphatic gestures of dissatisfaction on the part of Falsten, and I could not forbear listening to what followed.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000921","text":"\"Preposterous! shameful!\" exclaimed Falsten; \"nothing could be more imprudent.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000922","text":"\"Pooh! pooh!\" replied Ruby, \"it's all right; it is not the first time I have done it.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000923","text":"\"But don't you know that any shock at any time might cause an explosion?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000924","text":"\"Oh, it's all properly secured,\" said Ruby, \"tight enough; I have no fears on that score, Mr. Falsten.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000925","text":"\"Just because if I had informed him, he would not have taken the case on board.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000926","text":"The wind dropped for a few seconds; and for a brief interval I could not catch what passed; but I could see that Falsten continued to remonstrate, while Ruby answered by shrugging his shoulders. At length I heard Falsten say.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000927","text":"\"Well, at any rate, the captain must be informed of this, and the package shall be thrown overboard. I don't want to be blown up.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000928","text":"Evidently he had not the remotest suspicion that the cargo was already on fire.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000929","text":"In another moment the words \"picrate of potash\" brought me to my feet, and with an involuntary impulse I rushed up to Ruby, and seized him by the shoulder.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000930","text":"Curtis received the information as coolly as it was delivered, and after I had made him acquainted with all the particulars said, \"Not a word of this must be mentioned to anyone else, Mr.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000931","text":"Ruby and Falsten were sitting just as I had left them. Curtis walked straight up to Ruby, and asked him whether what he had been told was true.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000932","text":"\"Yes, quite true,\" said Ruby, complacently, thinking that the worst that could befall him would be that he might be convicted of a little smuggling.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000933","text":"He had not informed the captain of the dangerous nature of the contents of the package, because he was perfectly aware that he would have been refused permission to bring the package on board.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000934","text":"\"Anyway,\" he said, with a shrug of his shoulders, \"you can't hang me for it; and if the package gives you so much concern, you are quite at liberty to throw it into the sea. My luggage is insured.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000935","text":"I was beside myself with fury; and not being endowed with Curtis's reticence and self-control, before he could interfere to stop me, I cried out:","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000936","text":"He was paralyzed with terror; his limbs stiffened convulsively; his eye was dilated; he gasped for breath, and was speechless.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000937","text":"All of a sudden he threw up his arms, and, as though he momentarily expected an explosion, he darted down from the poop, and paced frantically up and down the deck, gesticulating like a madman, and shouting:","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000938","text":"On hearing the outcry, all the crew, supposing that the fire had now in reality broken out, rushed on deck; the rest of the passengers soon joined them, and the scene that ensued was one of the utmost confusion.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000939","text":"Kear fell down senseless on the deck, and her husband, occupied in looking after himself, left her to the tender mercies of Miss Herbey.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000940","text":"Curtis endeavored to silence Ruby's ravings, whilst I, in as few words as I could, made M.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000941","text":"Letourneur aware of the extent to which the cargo was on fire.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000942","text":"The father's first thought was for Andre, but the young man preserved an admirable composure, and begged his father not to be alarmed, as the danger was not immediate.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000943","text":"Meanwhile the sailors had loosened all the tacklings of the long-boat, and were preparing to launch it, when Curtis's voice was heard peremptorily bidding them to desist; he assured them that the fire had made no further progress; that Mr.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000944","text":"Ruby had been unduly excited and not conscious of what he had said; and he pledged his word that when the right moment should arrive he would allow them all to leave the ship; but that moment, he said, had not yet come.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000945","text":"At the sound of a voice which they had learned to honor and respect, the crew paused in their operations, and the long-boat remained suspended in its place.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000946","text":"As it was, only Curtis, Falsten, and myself were cognizant of the terrible secret.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000947","text":"As soon as order was restored, the mate and I joined Falsten on the poop, where he had remained throughout the panic, and where we found him with folded arms, deep in thought, as it might be, solving some hard mechanical problem.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000948","text":"He promised, at my request, that he would reveal nothing of the new danger to which we were exposed through Ruby's imprudence.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000949","text":"Curtis himself took the responsibility of informing Captain Huntly of our critical situation.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000950","text":"In order to insure complete secrecy, it was necessary to secure the person of the unhappy Ruby, who, quite beside himself, continued to rave up and down the deck with the incessant cry of \"Fire!","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000951","text":"fire!\" Accordingly Curtis gave orders to some of his men to seize him and gag him; and before he could make any resistance the miserable man was captured and safely lodged in confinement in his own cabin.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000952","text":"OCTOBER 22.--Curtis has told the captain everything; for he persists in ostensibly recognizing him as his superior officer, and refuses to conceal from him our true situation.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000953","text":"Captain Huntly received the communication in perfect silence, and merely passing his hand across his forehead as though to banish some distressing thought, re-entered his cabin without a word.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000954","text":"Curtis, Lieutenant Walter, Falsten, and myself have been discussing the chances of our safety, and I am surprised to find with how much composure we can all survey our anxious predicament.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000955","text":"\"There is no doubt,\" said Curtis, \"that we must abandon all hope of arresting the fire; the heat toward the bow has already become well-nigh unbearable, and the time must come when the flames will find a vent through the deck.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000956","text":"Falsten and I agreed with what he said, and I pointed out to him that he had quite overlooked the fact of there being thirty pounds of explosive matter in the hold.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000957","text":"\"No,\" he gravely replied, \"I have not forgotten it, but it is a circumstance of which I do not trust myself to think.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:relationships","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000958","text":"I dare not run the risk of admitting air into the hold by going down to search for the powder, and yet I know not at what moment it may explode.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:courage","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000959","text":"No; it is a matter that I cannot take at all into my reckoning; it must remain in higher hands than mine.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000960","text":"We bowed our heads in a silence which was solemn. In the present state of the weather, immediate flight was, we knew, impossible.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000961","text":"After considerable pause, Mr. Falsten, as calmly as though he were delivering some philosophic dogma, quietly observed:","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000962","text":"\"The explosion, if I may use the formula of science, is not necessary, but contingent.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000963","text":"\"But tell me, Mr. Falsten,\" I asked, \"is it possible for picrate of potash to ignite without concussion?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000964","text":"\"Certainly it is,\" replied the engineer. \"Under ordinary circumstances, picrate of potash although not MORE inflammable than common powder, yet possesses the SAME degree of inflammability.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000965","text":"We now prepared to go on deck. As we left the saloon, in which we had been sitting, Curtis seized my hand.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000966","text":"\"It is just this,\" he answered deliberately, \"we are over a mine, and already the match has been applied to the train. How long that train may be, 'tis not for me to say.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000967","text":"The other passengers, in common with the crew, are still in entire ignorance of the extremity of peril to which we are exposed, although they are all aware that there is fire in the hold.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000968","text":"Miss Herbey, however, is unrelaxing in her attentions, and the unremitted diligence with which she fulfills her offices of duty, commands my highest admiration.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000969","text":"OCTOBER 23.--This morning, Captain Huntly sent for Curtis into his cabin, and the mate has since made me acquainted with what passed between them.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000970","text":"\"Curtis,\" began the captain, his haggard eye betraying only too plainly some mental derangement, \"I am a sailor, am I not?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000971","text":"\"Certainly, captain,\" was the prompt acquiescence of the mate.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000972","text":"\"I do not know how it is,\" continued the captain, \"but I seem bewildered; I can not recollect anything. Are we not bound for Liverpool? Ah! yes! of course. And have we kept a northeasterly direction since we left?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000973","text":"\"No, sir, according to your orders we have been sailing southeast, and here we are in the tropics.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000974","text":"\"Yes, yes, the Chancellor, so it is. Well, Curtis, I really can't take her back to the north. I hate the sea, the very sight of it makes me ill, I would much rather not leave my cabin.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000975","text":"Curtis went on to tell me how he had tried to persuade him that with a little time and care he would soon recover his indisposition, and feel himself again; but the captain had interrupted him by saying:","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","audience:recovery","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000976","text":"\"Well, well; we shall see by-and-by; but for the present you must take this for my positive order; you must, from this time, at once take the command of the ship, and act just as if I were not on board.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000977","text":"My brain is all in a whirl, you can not tell what I am suffering;\" and the unfortunate man pressed both his hands convulsively against his forehead.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000978","text":"\"I weighed the matter carefully for a moment,\" added Curtis, \"and seeing what his condition too truly was, I acquiesced in all that he required and withdrew, promising him that all his orders should be obeyed.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000979","text":"After hearing these particulars, I could not help remarking how fortunate it was that the captain had resigned of his own accord, for although he might not be actually insane, it was very evident that his brain was in a very morbid condition.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000980","text":"\"I succeeded him at a very critical moment,\" said Curtis thoughtfully; \"but I shall endeavor to do my duty.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000981","text":"A short time afterward he sent for his boatswain and ordered him to assemble the crew at the foot of the main-mast. As soon as the men were together, he addressed them very calmly, but very firmly.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000982","text":"\"My men,\" he said, \"I have to tell you that Captain Huntly, on account of the dangerous situation in which circumstances have placed us, and for other reasons known to myself, has thought right to resign his command to me. From this time forward, I am captain of this vessel.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000983","text":"Thus quietly and simply was the change effected, and we have the satisfaction of knowing that the Chancellor is now under the command of a conscientious, energetic man, who will shirk nothing that he believes to be for our common good.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000984","text":"Falsten, and myself immediately offered him our best wishes, in which Lieutenant Walter and the boatswain most cordially joined.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000985","text":"The ship still holds her course southwest, and Curtis crowds on all sail and makes as speedily as possible for the nearest of the Lesser Antilles.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000986","text":"OCTOBER 24 to 29.--For the last five days the sea has been very heavy, and although the Chancellor sails with wind and wave in her favor, yet her progress is considerably impeded.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000987","text":"Here on board this veritable fire-ship I cannot help contemplating with a longing eye this vast ocean that surrounds us.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000988","text":"\"Why not bore the deck?\" I said to Curtis. \"Why not admit the water by tons into the hold? What could be the harm? The fire would be quenched; and what would be easier than to pump the water out again?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000989","text":"\"I have already told you, Mr. Kazallon,\" said Curtis, \"that the very moment we admit the air, the flames will rush forth to the very top of the masts. No; we must have courage and patience; we must wait. There is nothing whatever to be done, except to close every aperture.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:courage","theme:mindfulness","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000990","text":"The fire continued to progress even more rapidly than we had hitherto suspected.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000991","text":"The heat gradually drove the passengers nearly all on deck, and the two stern cabins, lighted, as I said, by their windows in the aft-board were the only quarters below that were inhabitable.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000992","text":"Kear occupied one, and Curtis reserved the other for Ruby, who, a raving maniac, had to be kept rigidly under restraint.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000993","text":"I went down occasionally to see him, but invariably found him in a state of abject terror, uttering horrible shrieks, as though possessed with the idea that he was being scorched by the most excruciating heat.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000994","text":"He was always calm and spoke quite rationally on any subject except his own profession; but in connection with that he prated away the merest nonsense.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000995","text":"He suffered greatly, but steadily declined all my offers of attention, and pertinaciously refused to leave his cabin.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000996","text":"To-day, an acrid, nauseating smoke made its way through the panelings that partition off the quarters of the crew.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000997","text":"At once Curtis ordered the partition to be enveloped in wet tarpaulin, but the fumes penetrated even this, and filled the whole neighborhood of the ship's bows with a reeking vapor that was positively stifling.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000998","text":"As we listened, too, we could hear a dull rumbling sound, but we were as mystified as ever to comprehend where the air could have entered that was evidently fanning the flames.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-000999","text":"Only too certainly, it was now becoming a question not of days nor even of hours before we must be prepared for the final catastrophe.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001000","text":"The sea was still running high, and escape by the boats was plainly impossible.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001001","text":"It is now a fortnight since the fire was first discovered, and the proper working of the ship has gradually become a more and more difficult matter.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001002","text":"Even with thick shoes any attempt to walk upon deck up to the forecastle was soon impracticable, and the poop, simply because its floor is elevated somewhat above the level of the hold, is now the only available standing-place.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001003","text":"Water began to lose its effect upon the scorched and shriveling planks; the resin oozed out from the knots in the wood, the seams burst open, and the tar, melted by the heat, followed the rollings of the vessel, and formed fantastic patterns about the deck.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001004","text":"Then to complete our perplexity, the wind shifted suddenly round to the northwest, whence it blew a perfect hurricane.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001005","text":"To-day, the 29th, the tempest seemed to reach its height; the waves appeared to us mountains high, and dashed the spray most violently across the deck. A boat could not live a moment in such a sea.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001006","text":"We all wait in silence, some few on the forecastle, the great proportion of us on the poop.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001007","text":"As for the picrate, for the time we have quite forgotten its existence; indeed it might almost seem as though its explosion would come as a relief, for no catastrophe, however terrible, could far exceed the torture of our suspense.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001008","text":"About eight o'clock in the evening, a noise is heard, distinct even above the raging of the hurricane.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001009","text":"The panels of the deck are upheaved, and volumes of black smoke issue upward as if from a safety-valve.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001010","text":"A universal consternation seizes one and all; we must leave the volcano which is about to burst beneath our feet.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001011","text":"He hesitates; looks first at the huge and threatening waves; looks then at the boats.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001012","text":"The long-boat is there, suspended right along the center of the deck; but it is impossible to approach it now; the yawl, however, hoisted on the starboard side, and the whale-boat suspended aft, are still available.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001013","text":"\"Stop, stop,\" shouts Curtis; \"do you mean to cut off our last and only chance of safety? Would you launch a boat in such a sea as this?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001014","text":"A few of them, with Owen at their head, give no heed to what he says. Rushing to the poop, and seizing a cutlass, Curtis shouts again:","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001015","text":"\"Touch the tackling of the davit, one of you; only touch it, and I'll cleave your skull.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001016","text":"Awed by his determined manner, the men retire, some clambering into the shrouds, while others mount to the very top of the masts.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001017","text":"At eleven o'clock, several loud reports are heard, caused by the bursting asunder of the partitions of the hold.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001018","text":"Clouds of smoke issue from the front, followed by a long tongue of lambent flame that seems to encircle the mizzen-mast.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001019","text":"Kear, who, shrieking wildly, is brought on deck by Miss Herbey.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001020","text":"A moment more, and Silas Huntly makes his appearance, his face all blackened with the grimy smoke; he bows to Curtis, as he passes, and then proceeds in the calmest manner to mount the aft-shrouds, and installs himself at the very top of the mizzen.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001021","text":"The sight of Huntly recalls to my recollection the prisoner still below, and my first impulse is to rush to the staircase and do what I can to set him free.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001022","text":"But the maniac has already eluded his confinement, and with singed hair and his clothes already alight, rushes upon deck.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001023","text":"Like a salamander he passes across the burning deck with unscathed feet, and glides through the stifling smoke with unchoked breath.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001024","text":"Another loud report; the long-boat is shivered into fragments; the middle panel bursts the tarpaulin that covered it, and a stream of fire, free at length from the restraint that had held it, rises half-mast high.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001025","text":"\"The picrate! the picrate!\" shrieks the madman; \"we shall all be blown up! the picrate will blow us all up.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001026","text":"And in an instant, before we can get near him, he has buried himself, through the open hatchway, down into the fiery furnace below.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001027","text":"OCTOBER 20.--Night.--The scene, as night came on, was terrible indeed. Notwithstanding the desperateness of our situation, however, there was not one of us so paralyzed by fear, but that we fully realized the horror of it all.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001028","text":"Poor Ruby, indeed, is lost and gone, but his last words were productive of serious consequences.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001029","text":"The sailors caught his cry of \"Picrate, picrate!\" and being thus for the first time made aware of the true nature of their peril, they resolved at every hazard to accomplish their escape.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001030","text":"Beside themselves with terror, they either did not, or would not, see that no boat could brave the tremendous waves that were raging around, and accordingly they made a frantic rush toward the yawl.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:courage","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001031","text":"Curtis again made a vigorous endeavor to prevent them, but this time all in vain; Owen urged them on, and already the tackling was loosened, so that the boat was swung over to the ship's side.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001032","text":"For a moment it hung suspended in mid-air, and then, with a final effort from the sailors, it was quickly lowered into the sea.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001033","text":"But scarcely had it touched the water, when it was caught by an enormous wave which, recoiling with resistless violence, dashed it to atoms against the Chancellor's side.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001034","text":"Longboat and yawl both gone, there was nothing now remaining to us but a small whale-boat.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001035","text":"Not a word was spoken; not a sound was heard but the hoarse whistling of the wind, and the mournful roaring of the flames.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001036","text":"From the center of the ship, which was hollowed out like a furnace, there issued a column of sooty vapor that ascended to the sky.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001037","text":"All the passengers, and several of the crew, took refuge in the aft-quarters of the poop.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001038","text":"Kear was lying senseless on one of the hen-coops, with Miss Herbey sitting passively at her side; M.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001039","text":"I saw Falsten calmly consult his watch, and note down the time in his memorandum-book, but I was far from sharing his composure, for I was overcome by a nervous agitation that I could not suppress.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001040","text":"As far as we knew, Lieutenant Walter, the boatswain, and such of the crew as were not with us, were safe in the bow; but it was impossible to tell how they were faring, because the sheet of fire intervened like a curtain, and cut off all communication between stem and stern.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001041","text":"\"No, sir, not yet,\" he replied, \"now that the panel is open we will set to work, and pour water with all our might down into the furnace, and may be, we shall put it out, even yet.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001042","text":"\"But how can you work your pumps while the deck is burning? and how can you get at your men beyond that sheet of flame?\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001043","text":"He made no answer to my impetuous questions, and finding he had nothing more to say, I repeated that it was all over now.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001044","text":"After a pause, he said, \"As long as a plank of the ship remains to stand on, Mr. Kazallon, I shall not give up my hope.\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001045","text":"But the conflagration raged with redoubled fury, the sea around us was lighted with a crimson glow, and the clouds above shone with a lurid glare.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001046","text":"Long jets of fire darted across the hatchways, and we were forced to take refuge on the taffrail at the extreme end of the poop.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001047","text":"Miss Herbey persisting to the last in retaining her post by her side.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001048","text":"No pen could adequately portray the horrors of this fearful night.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001049","text":"The Chancellor under bare poles, was driven, like a gigantic fire-ship with frightful velocity across the raging ocean; her very speed as it were, making common cause with the hurricane to fan the fire that was consuming her.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001050","text":"Soon there could be no alternative between throwing ourselves into the sea, or perishing in the flames.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001051","text":"But where, all this time, was the picrate? Perhaps, after all, Ruby had deceived us and there was no volcano, such as we dreaded, below our feet.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001052","text":"At half-past eleven, when the tempest seems at its very height, there is heard a peculiar roar distinguishable even above the crash of the elements. The sailors in an instant recognize its import.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001053","text":"Curtis leaps on to the netting, casts a rapid glance at the snow-white billows, and turning to the helmsman shouts with all his might, \"Starboard the helm!\"","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001054","text":"But it is too late. There is a sudden shock; the ship is caught up by an enormous wave; she rises upon her beam ends; several times she strikes the ground; the mizzen-mast snaps short off level with the deck, falls into the sea, and the Chancellor is motionless.","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001055","text":"THE night of the 29th continued.--It was not yet midnight; the darkness was most profound, and we could see nothing. But was it probable that we had stranded on the coast of America?","author":"Epictetus","source":"Discourses of Epictetus","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001056","text":"Being the Record of a Voyage of Exploration of the Ship \"Fram\" 1893-96 and of a Fifteen Months' Sleigh Journey by Dr. Nansen and Lieut. Johansen","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001057","text":"About 120 Full-page and Numerous Text Illustrations 16 Colored Plates in Facsimile from Dr. Nansen's Own Sketches, Etched Portrait, and Photogravures","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001058","text":"I. We Prepare for the Sledge Expedition 1 II. The New Year, 1895 41 III. We Make a Start 90 IV. We Say Good-bye to the \"Fram\" 132 V. A Hard Struggle 157 VI. By Sledge and Kayak 236 VII. Land at Last 308 VIII. The New Year, 1896 454 IX. The Journey Southward 487","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001059","text":"Report of Captain Otto Sverdrup on the Drifting of the \"Fram\" from March 14, 1895.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001060","text":"I. March 15 to June 22, 1895 601 II. June 22 to August 15, 1895 633 III. August 15 to January 1, 1896 648 IV. January 1 to May 17, 1896 668 V. The Third Summer 683 Conclusion 707 Index 715","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001061","text":"Sailing Kayaks (Photogravure) Frontispiece Hjalmar Johansen Facing p.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001062","text":"2 At the Supper-table (February 14, 1895) 9 Scott-Hansen's Observatory 17 Musical Entertainment in the Saloon 35 Captain Sverdrup in His Cabin 49 The \"Fram\" in the Ice (Photogravure) Facing p.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001063","text":"162 Over Difficult Pressure-mounds (April, 1895) 165 \"I Went on Ahead on Snow-shoes\" 169 \"On Tolerably Good Ground\" 171 Our Northernmost Camp, 86° 13.6' N.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001064","text":"178 Rest (April, 1895) 181 Johansen Carving our Names in a Stock of Driftwood 185 Peculiar Ice Stratification (April, 1895) 187 \"We Made Fairly Good Progress\" 203 Repairing the Kayaks 240 A Coign of Vantage.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:justice","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001065","text":"South of Cape Richthofen (June 6, 1896) 507 \"I Managed to Swing One Leg Up\" 515 \"It Tried to Upset Me\" 520 Our Last Camp 523 Franz Josef Land 528 Meeting of Jackson and Nansen 531 Mr.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001066","text":"Jackson at Elmwood 569 Johansen in Jackson's Saloon 571 Cape Flora.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001067","text":"Farewell to Franz Josef Land 577 \"We Stood Looking over the Sea\" 580 Arrival at Hammerfest 587 The \"Windward\" Leaving Tromsö 591 Tailpiece 597 Original Map of Kaiser Franz Josef Land 599","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001068","text":"Digging Out the \"Fram\" (March, 1895) 603 The \"Fram\" when Dug Out of the Pressure-mound at the End of March, 1895 607 Fitting the Hand-sledges with Runners (July, 1895) 611 View over the Drift-ice.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001069","text":"Light Phenomena in the Polar Night (November 22, 1893) 96 X.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001070","text":"Moon-ring with Mock Moons, and a Suggestion of Horizontal Axes (November 24, 1893) 248 XII.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001071","text":"Moonlight Phenomena at the Beginning of the Polar Night (November, 1893) 320 XIII.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001072","text":"Sverdrup and I have tested each other before at this sort of work, and we could manage very well; but we cannot both leave the Fram: that is perfectly clear without further argument.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001073","text":"One of us must remain behind to take on himself the responsibility of bringing the others home in safety; but it is equally clear that one of us two must conduct the sledge expedition, as it is we who have the necessary experience.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001074","text":"Sverdrup has a great desire to go; but I cannot think otherwise than that there is more risk in leaving the Fram than in remaining on board her.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001075","text":"Consequently if I were to let him go, I should be transferring to him the more dangerous task, while keeping the easier one to myself.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001076","text":"If he perished, should I ever be able to forgive myself for letting him go, even if it was at his own desire?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001077","text":"He is nine years older than I am; I should certainly feel it to be a very uncomfortable responsibility.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001078","text":"And as regards our comrades, which of us would it be most to their interest to keep on board?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001079","text":"I think they have confidence in both of us, and I think either of us would be able to take them home in safety, whether with or without the Fram.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001080","text":"But the ship is his especial charge, while on me rests the conduct of the whole, and especially of the scientific investigations; so that I ought to undertake the task in which important discoveries are to be made.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001081","text":"Those who remain with the ship will be able, as aforesaid, to carry on the observations which are to be made on board.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001082","text":"I have chosen Johansen to be my companion, and he is in all respects well qualified for that work.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001083","text":"He is an accomplished snow-shoer, and few can equal his powers of endurance--a fine fellow, physically and mentally.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001084","text":"I have not yet asked him, but think of doing so soon, in order that he may be prepared betimes.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001085","text":"Blessing and Hansen also would certainly be all eagerness to accompany me; but Hansen must remain behind to take charge of the observations, and Blessing cannot desert his post as doctor.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:gratitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001086","text":"Several of the others, too, would do quite well, and would, I doubt not, be willing enough.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001087","text":"This expedition to the north, then, is provisionally decided on. I shall see what the winter will bring us. Light permitting, I should prefer to start in February.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:leadership","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001088","text":"It seems as if I could not properly realize the idea that I am really to set out, and that in three months' time.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001089","text":"Sometimes I delude myself with charming dreams of my return home after toil and victory, and then all is clear and bright.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001090","text":"Then these are succeeded by thoughts of the uncertainty and deceptiveness of the future and what may be lurking in it, and my dreams fade away like the northern lights, pale and colorless.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001091","text":"Before every decisive resolution the dice of death must be thrown.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001092","text":"There is more to be gained, at all events, than there is here.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001093","text":"Besides, there is only one to whom I am responsible, and she...?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001094","text":"'Be thou true unto death, and thou shalt inherit the crown of life.'","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001095","text":"Then down we sink again in disgust at the worthlessness of it all.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001096","text":"\"'As a grain of dust on the balance is the whole world; as a drop of morning dew that falls on the ground.' If man has two souls, which then is the right one?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001097","text":"\"It is nothing new to suffer from the fact that our knowledge can be but fragmentary, that we can never fathom what lies behind.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001098","text":"But suppose, now, that we could reckon it out, that the inmost secret of it all lay as clear and plain to us as a rule-of-three sum, should we be any the happier?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001099","text":"Is it not in the struggle to attain knowledge that happiness consists?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001100","text":"I am very ignorant, consequently the conditions of happiness are mine.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001101","text":"\"No, the pipe is not a success. Twist tobacco is not delicate enough for airy dreams. Let me get a cigar. Oh, if one had a real Havana!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001102","text":"as if dissatisfaction, longing, suffering, were not the very basis of life.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001103","text":"Without privation there would be no struggle, and without struggle no life, that is as certain as that two and two make four.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001104","text":"And now the struggle is to begin; it is looming yonder in the north.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001105","text":"\"'In amongst the fragrant birch, In amongst the flowers' perfume, Deep into the pine-wood's church.'","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001106","text":"Confounded affectation all this Weltschmerz; you have no right to be anything but a happy man.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001107","text":"And if you feel out of spirits, it ought to cheer you up simply to go on deck and look at these seven puppies that come frisking and springing about you, and are ready to tear you to pieces in sheer enjoyment of life.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001108","text":"Life is sunshine to them, though the sun has long since gone, and they live on deck beneath a tent, so that they cannot even see the stars.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001109","text":"There is 'Kvik,' the mother of the family, among them, looking so plump and contented as she wags her tail.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001110","text":"Ten minutes later I heard a dog howling, a more long-drawn, uncomfortable kind of howl than was usual when they were fighting, and at the same moment the mill slowed down.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001111","text":"There I saw a puppy right in the axle, whirling round with it and howling piteously, so that it cut one to the soul.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001112","text":"Bentzen was hanging on to the brake-rope, hauling at it with all his might and main; but still the mill went round.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001113","text":"My first idea was to seize an axe that was lying there to put the dog out of its misery, its cries were so heartrending; but on second thoughts I hurried on to help Bentzen, and we got the mill stopped.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001114","text":"At the same moment Mogstad also came up, and while we held the mill he managed to set the puppy free.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001115","text":"Apparently there was still some life in it, and he set to work to rub it gently and coax it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001116","text":"The hair of its coat had somehow or other got frozen on to the smooth steel axle, and the poor beast had been swung round and bumped on the deck at every revolution of the wheel.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001117","text":"At last it actually raised its head, and looked round in a dazed way.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001118","text":"It had made a good many revolutions, so that it is no wonder if it found some difficulty in getting its bearings at first.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001119","text":"Then it raised itself on its fore-paws, and I took it aft to the half-deck and stroked and patted it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001120","text":"Soon it got on all four legs again, and began shambling about, without knowing where it was going.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001121","text":"\"'It is a good thing it was caught by the hair,' said Bentzen, 'I thought it was hanging fast by its tongue, as the other one did.' Only think of being fixed by the tongue to a revolving axle--the mere notion makes one shudder!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001122","text":"I took the poor thing down into the saloon and did all I could for it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001123","text":"It soon got all right again, and began playing with its companions as before.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001124","text":"A strange life to rummage about on deck in the dark and cold; but whenever one goes up with a lantern they come tearing round, stare at the light, and begin bounding and dancing and gambolling with each other round it, like children round a Christmas-tree.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001125","text":"This goes on day after day, and they have never seen anything else than this deck with a tarpaulin over it, not even the clear blue sky; and we men have never seen anything else than this earth!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001126","text":"\"The last step over the bridge of resolution has now been taken.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001127","text":"In the forenoon I explained the whole matter to Johansen in pretty much the same terms as I have used above; and then I expatiated on the difficulties that might occur, and laid strong emphasis on the dangers one must be prepared to encounter.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001128","text":"It was a serious matter--a matter of life or death--this one must not conceal from one's self.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001129","text":"He must think the thing well over before determining whether he would accompany me or not.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001130","text":"If he was willing to come I should be glad to have him with me; but I would rather, I said, he should take a day or two to think it well over before he gave me his answer.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001131","text":"He did not need any time for reflection, he said; he was quite willing to go.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001132","text":"Sverdrup had long ago mentioned the possibility of such an expedition, and he had thought it well over, and made up his mind that if my choice should fall on him he would take it as a great favor to be permitted to accompany me.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001133","text":"Hansen must see about appointing another meteorological assistant.'","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001134","text":"This evening I delivered an address to the whole ship's company, in which I announced the determination that had been arrived at, and explained to them the projected expedition.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001135","text":"The object of the expedition was to accomplish this drift across the unknown sea, and to pursue investigations there.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001136","text":"I pointed out to them that these investigations would be of equal importance whether the expedition actually passed across the Pole itself or at some distance from it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001137","text":"\"I had the impression that every one was deeply interested in the projected expedition, and that they all thought it most desirable that it should be attempted.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001138","text":"The greatest objection, I think, they would have urged against it, had they been asked, would have been that they themselves could not take part in it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001139","text":"This done, we might say, without fear of contradiction, that it was well done.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001140","text":"So now the die is cast, and I must believe that this expedition will really take place.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001141","text":"So we set about our preparations for it in downright earnest.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001142","text":"I have already mentioned that at the end of the summer I had begun to make a kayak for a single man, the frame of which was of bamboo carefully lashed together.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001143","text":"It was rather slow work, and took several weeks, but it turned out both light and strong.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001144","text":"It was afterwards covered with sail-cloth by Sverdrup and Blessing, when the whole boat weighed 30 pounds.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:gratitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001145","text":"After finishing this I had intrusted Mogstad with the task of building a similar one.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001146","text":"These kayaks were 3.70 metres (12 feet) long, about O.7 metre (28 inches) wide in the middle, and one was 30 centims.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001147","text":"This is considerably shorter and wider than an ordinary Eskimo kayak, and consequently these boats were not so light to propel through the water.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001148","text":"But as they were chiefly intended for crossing over channels and open spaces in the ice, and coasting along possible land, speed was not of much importance.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001149","text":"The great thing was that the boats should be strong and light, and should be able to carry, in addition to ourselves, provisions and equipments for a considerable time.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001150","text":"If we had made them longer and narrower, besides being heavier they would have been more exposed to injury in the course of transport over the uneven ice.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001151","text":"As they were built they proved admirably adapted for our purpose.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001152","text":"When we loaded them with care we could stow away in them provisions and equipment for three months at least for ourselves, besides a good deal of food for the dogs; and we could, moreover, carry a dog or two on the deck.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:leadership","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001153","text":"In other respects they were essentially like the Eskimo kayaks, full decked, save for an aperture in the middle for a man to sit in.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001154","text":"This aperture was encircled by a wooden ring, after the Eskimo fashion, over which we could slip the lower part of our sealskin jackets, specially adjusted for this purpose, so that the junction between boat and jacket was water-tight.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001155","text":"When these jackets were drawn tight round the wrists and face the sea might sweep right over us without a drop of water coming into the kayak.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001156","text":"We had to provide ourselves with such boats in case of having to cross open stretches of sea on our way to Spitzbergen, or, if we chose the other route, between Franz Josef Land and Novaya Zemlya.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001157","text":"These trap-doors, however, could be closed so as to be quite water-tight.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001158","text":"Therefore I preferred to steep it in a mixture of paraffin and tallow, which added somewhat to the weight of the kayaks, so that altogether they came to weigh about 36 pounds apiece.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001159","text":"I had, moreover, some hand-sledges made especially for this expedition; they were supple and strong, designed to withstand the severe tests to which an expedition with dogs and heavy freights over the uneven drift-ice would necessarily expose them.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001160","text":"Two of these sledges were about the same length as the kayaks--that is, 12 feet.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001161","text":"I also made several experiments with respect to the clothes we should wear, and was especially anxious to ascertain whether it would do to go in our thick wolfskin garments, but always came to the conclusion that they were too warm.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001162","text":"Thus, on November 29th I write: \"Took another walk northward in my wolfskin dress; but it is still too mild (-37.6° C.).","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001163","text":"I sweated like a horse, though I went fasting and quite gently.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001164","text":"It is rather heavy going now in the dark when one cannot use snowshoes.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001165","text":"On December 9th again we went out on snow-shoes. \"It was -41° C. (-41.8° Fahr.). Went in wolfskin dress, but the perspiration poured down our backs enough to turn a mill. Too warm yet; goodness knows if it ever will be cold enough.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001166","text":"Of course, we made some experiments with the tent and with the cooking apparatus.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001167","text":"On December 7th I write: \"I pitched the silk tent we are going to take, and used our cooking apparatus in it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001168","text":"(-31° Fahr.), we boiled 3 litres of water (5 1/4 pints), and at the same time melted 5 litres (8 3/4 pints) in an hour and a half, with a consumption of about 120 grammes of snowflake petroleum.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001169","text":"Next day we boiled 2 1/2 litres of water (over 4 pints), and melted 2 1/2 litres in one hour with 100 grammes of snowflake petroleum.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001170","text":"Yesterday we made about two litres of excellent oatmeal porridge, and at the same time got some half-melted ice and a little water in little over half an hour, with 50 grammes of snowflake petroleum.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001171","text":"Thus there will be no very great consumption of fuel in the day.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001172","text":"Later on, in the list of our equipments, I shall give the final result of my deliberations on this matter.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001173","text":"Besides all this, we had, of course, to consider and test the instruments to be taken with us, and to go into many other matters, which, though perhaps trifles in themselves, were yet absolutely necessary.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001174","text":"It is on the felicitous combination of all these trifles that ultimate success depends.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001175","text":"We two passed the greater portion of our time in these preparations, which also kept many of the others pretty busy during the winter.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001176","text":"Mogstad, for instance, found steady employment in making sledges and fitting them with runners, etc.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001177","text":"Sverdrup busied himself in making sleeping-bags and many other things.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001178","text":"Juell was appointed dog-tailor, and when he was not busy in the galley, his time was devoted to taking the measurements of the dogs, making harness for them and testing it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001179","text":"Blessing, too, fitted up for us a small, light medicine-chest, containing selected drugs, bandages, and such other things as might be of use.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:gratitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001180","text":"One man was constantly employed in copying out all our journals and scientific observations, etc., etc., on thin paper in a contracted form, as I wanted, by way of doubly assuring their preservation, to take a copy of them along with me.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001181","text":"Hansen was occupied in preparing tabular forms necessary for our observations, curves of the movement of our chronometers, and other such things.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001182","text":"Besides this, he was to make a complete chart of our voyage and drifting up to the present time.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001183","text":"I could not, however, lay too great a claim on his valuable time, as it was necessary that he should continue his scientific observations without interruption.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001184","text":"During this autumn he had greatly increased the comfort of his work by building, along with Johansen, an observation-hut of snow, not unlike an Eskimo cabin.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001185","text":"He found himself very much at his ease in it, with a petroleum lamp hanging from the roof, the light of which, being reflected by the white snow walls, made quite a brilliant show.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001186","text":"Here he could manipulate his instruments quietly and comfortably, undisturbed by the biting wind outside.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001187","text":"He thought it quite warm there, too, when he could get the temperature up to something like 20° below freezing-point, so that he was able without much inconvenience to adjust his instruments with bare hands.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001188","text":"Here he worked away indefatigably at his observations day after day, watching the often mysterious movements of the magnetic needle, which would sometimes give him no end of trouble.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001189","text":"One day--it was November 24th--he came into supper a little after 6 o'clock quite alarmed and said, \"There has just been a singular inclination of the needle to 24°, and, remarkably enough, its northern extremity pointed to the east.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001190","text":"I cannot remember ever having heard of such an inclination.\" He also had several others of about 15°.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001191","text":"At the same time, through the opening into his observatory he noticed that it was unusually light out-of-doors, and that not only the ship, but the ice in the distance, was as plainly visible as if it had been full moonlight.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001192","text":"No aurora, however, could be discerned through the thick clouds that covered the sky.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001193","text":"It would appear, then, that this unusual inclination was in some way connected with the northern lights, though it was to the east and not to the west, as usual.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001194","text":"This theory, therefore, is entirely excluded, and the whole matter seems to me, for the present, to be incomprehensible.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001195","text":"Certainly it was so light that we could see the lanes in the ice astern quite plainly; but there was nothing remarkable in that, it happened often enough.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001196","text":"The bear had come from the east, trotting very gently along the lane, on the newly frozen ice, but he must have been scared by something or other ahead of the vessel, as he had gone off again with long strides in the same direction in which he had come.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001197","text":"Strange that living creatures should be roaming about in this desert.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001198","text":"If only one had such a stomach one could at least stand a journey to the Pole and back without a meal.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001199","text":"We shall probably have him back again soon--that is, if I understand his nature aright--and then perhaps he will come a little closer, so that we may have a good look at him.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001200","text":"It was 348 paces across, and maintained the same width for a considerable distance eastward; nor can it be much narrower for a great distance to the west.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001201","text":"Now, when one bears in mind that the lane behind us is also of considerable width, it is rather consoling, after all, to think that the ice does permit of such large openings.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001202","text":"There must be room enough to drift, if we only get wind--wind which will never come.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001203","text":"On the whole, November has been an uncommonly wretched month.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001204","text":"Driven back instead of forward--and yet this month was so good last year.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001205","text":"But one can never rely on the seasons in this dreadful sea; taking all in all, perhaps, the winter will not be a bit better than the summer.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001206","text":"\"The skies are clouded with a thick veil, through which the stars barely glisten.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001207","text":"It is darker than usual, and in this eternal night we drift about, lonely and forsaken, 'for the whole world was filled with a shining light and undisturbed activity.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001208","text":"Above those men alone brooded nought but depressing night--an image of that gloom which was soon to swallow them up.'","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001209","text":"\"This dark, deep, silent void is like the mysterious, unfathomable well into which you look for that something which you think must be there, only to meet the reflection of your own eyes.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001210","text":"the worn-out thoughts you can never get rid of become in the end very wearisome company.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001211","text":"Is there no means of fleeing from one's self, to grasp one single thought--only a single one, which lies outside one's self--is there no way except death?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001212","text":"But death is certain; one day it will come, silent and majestic; it will open Nirvana's mighty portal, and we shall be swept away into the sea of eternity.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:buddhism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001213","text":"Sverdrup has now been ill for some days; during the last day or two he has been laid up in his berth, and is still there.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001214","text":"I trust it is nothing serious; he himself thinks nothing of it, nevertheless it is very disquieting.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:relationships","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001215","text":"It is an intestinal catarrh, which he probably contracted through catching cold on the ice.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001216","text":"However, he is now improving, so that probably it will soon pass off; but it is a warning not to be over-confident.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001217","text":"I went for a long walk this morning along the lane; it is quite a large one, extending a good way to the east, and being of considerable breadth at some points.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001218","text":"Even if I have not felt warm before, I break out into a perspiration after going a short distance over the rough ice.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001219","text":"One cannot use snow-shoes; it is so dark that it is difficult enough to grope one's way about with ordinary boots, and even then one stumbles about or slips down between great blocks of ice.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001220","text":"\"I am now reading the various English stories of the polar expeditions during the Franklin period, and the search for him, and I must admit I am filled with admiration for these men and the amount of labor they expended.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001221","text":"I remember reading these stories as a lad, and all my boyish fancies were strangely thrilled with longing for the scenery and the scenes which were displayed before me.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001222","text":"I am reading them now as a man, after having had a little experience myself; and now, when my mind is uninfluenced by romance, I bow in admiration.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001223","text":"There was grit in men like Parry, Franklin, James Ross, Richardson, and last, but not least, in M'Clintock, and, indeed, in all the rest.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001224","text":"How well was their equipment thought out and arranged, with the means they had at their disposal!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001225","text":"Most of what I prided myself upon, and what I thought to be new, I find they had anticipated.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001226","text":"It was not their fault that they were born in a country where the use of snow-shoes is unknown, and where snow is scarcely to be found throughout the whole winter.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001227","text":"No one has surpassed and scarcely any one approached them, unless, perhaps, the Russians on the Siberian coast; but then they have the great advantage of being natives of a country where snow is not uncommon.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001228","text":"\"Friday, December 14th. Yesterday we held a great festivity in honor of the Fram as being the vessel which has attained the highest latitude (the day before yesterday we reached 82° 30' north latitude).","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001229","text":"\"The bill of fare at dinner was boiled mackerel, with parsely-butter sauce; pork cutlets and French pease; Norwegian wild strawberries, with rice and milk; Crown malt extract; afterwards coffee.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001230","text":"The culminating point of the entertainment was reached when a steaming hot and fragrant bowl of cherry-punch was carried in and served round amidst general hilarity.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001231","text":"Our spirits were already very high, but this gave color to the whole proceedings.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001232","text":"The greatest puzzle to most of them was where the ingredients for the punch, and more particularly the alcohol, had come from.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001233","text":"First, a long and festive one to 'The Fram,' which had now shown what she was capable of.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001234","text":"It ran somewhat to this effect: 'There were many wise men who shook their heads when we started, and sent us ominous farewell greetings.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001235","text":"But their head-shakings would have been less vigorous and their evil forebodings milder if they could have seen us at this moment, drifting quietly and at our ease across the most northerly latitudes ever attained by any vessel, and still farther northward.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001236","text":"And the Fram is now not only the most northerly vessel on the globe, but has already passed over a large expanse of hitherto unknown regions, many degrees farther north than have ever been reached in this ocean on this side of the Pole.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001237","text":"But we hope she will not stop here; concealed behind the mist of the future there are many triumphs in store for us--triumphs which will dawn upon us one by one when their time has come.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001238","text":"But we will not speak of this now; we will be content with what has hitherto been achieved, and I believe that the promise implied in Björnson's greeting to us and to the Fram, when she was launched, has already been fulfilled, and with him we can exclaim:","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001239","text":"\"'\"Hurrah for the ship and her voyage dread! Where never before a keel has sped, Where never before a name was spoken, By Norway's name is the silence broken.'\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001240","text":"Yes, truly, I think we have every reason to be satisfied with our voyage so far and with the Fram, and I trust we shall be able to bring something back to Norway in return for the trust, the sympathy, and the money which she has expended on us.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001241","text":"But let us not on this account forget our predecessors; let us admire them for the way in which they struggled and endured; let us remember that it is only through their labors and achievements that the way has been prepared for the present voyage.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001242","text":"On board this vessel we try to cull the fruits of all our predecessors' experiences.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001243","text":"It has taken years to collect them; but I felt that with these I should be enabled to face any vicissitude of fate in unknown waters.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001244","text":"I think we are all of the opinion that there is no imaginable difficulty or obstacle before us that we ought not to be able to overcome with the means and resources we possess on board, and be thus enabled to return at last to Norway safe and sound, with a rich harvest.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001245","text":"\"Next there followed some musical items and a performance by Lars, the smith, who danced a pas seul, to the great amusement of the company.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001246","text":"Lars assured us that if he ever reached home again and were present at a gathering similar to those held at Christiania and Bergen on our departure, his legs should be taxed to their uttermost.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001247","text":"\"The festivity continued with music and merriment throughout the evening, and our good humor was certainly not spoiled when our excellent doctor came forward with cigars--a commodity which is getting highly valued up here, as, unfortunately it is becoming very scarce.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001248","text":"The only cloud in our existence is that Sverdrup has not yet quite recovered from his catarrh.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","audience:recovery","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001249","text":"He must keep strict diet, and this does not at all suit him, poor fellow!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001250","text":"He is only allowed wheaten bread, milk, raw bear's flesh, and oatmeal porridge; whereas if he had his own way he would eat everything, including cake, preserves, and fruit.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001251","text":"But he has returned to duty now, and has already been out for a turn on the ice.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001252","text":"\"It was late at night when I retired to my cabin, but I was not yet in a fit mood to go to sleep.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001253","text":"I felt I must go out and saunter in the wonderful moonlight.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001254","text":"Around the moon there was, as usual, a large ring, and above it there was an arc, which just touched it at the upper edge, but the two ends of which curved downward instead of upward.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001255","text":"It looked as if it were part of a circle whose centre was situated far below the moon.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001256","text":"At the lower edge of the ring there was a large mock moon, or, rather, a large luminous patch, which was most pronounced at the upper part, where it touched the ring, and had a yellow upper edge, from which it spread downward in the form of a triangle.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001257","text":"It looked as if it might be an arc of a circle on the lower side of, and in contact with, the ring.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001258","text":"Right across the moon there were drifting several luminous cirrus streaks.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001259","text":"The same southeasterly wind has turned into a regular storm, howling and rattling cheerily through the rigging, and we are doubtless drifting northward at a good rate.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001260","text":"If I go outside the tent on deck, the wind whistles round my ears, and the snow beats into my face, and I am soon covered with it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001261","text":"From the snow-hut observatory, or even at a lesser distance, the Fram is invisible, and it is almost impossible to keep one's eyes open, owing to the blinding snow.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001262","text":"But I am afraid this joy will not be a lasting one; the barometer has fallen alarmingly, and the wind has generally been up to 13 or 14 metres (44 or 50 feet) per second.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001263","text":"About half-past twelve last night the vessel suddenly received a strong pressure, rattling everything on board.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001264","text":"I could feel the vibration under me for a long time afterwards while lying in my berth.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001265","text":"Finally, I could hear the roaring and grating caused by the ice-pressure.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001266","text":"I told the watch to listen carefully, and ascertain where the pressure was, and to notice whether the floe on which we were lying was likely to crack, and whether any part of our equipment was in danger.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001267","text":"He thought he could hear the noise of ice-pressure both forward and aft, but it was not easy to distinguish it from the roar of the tempest in the rigging.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001268","text":"the Fram received another violent shock, even stronger than that we had experienced during the night.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001269","text":"There was another shake a little later; I suppose there has been a pressure aft, but could hear nothing for the storm.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001270","text":"It is odd about this pressure: one would think that the wind was the primary cause; but it recurs pretty regularly, notwithstanding the fact that the spring-tide has not yet set in; indeed, when it commenced a few days ago it was almost a neap-tide.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001271","text":"In addition to the pressure of yesterday and last night, we had pressure on Thursday morning at half-past nine and again at half-past eleven.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001272","text":"It was so strong that Peter, who was at the sounding-hole, jumped up repeatedly, thinking that the ice would burst underneath him.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001273","text":"It is very singular, we have been quiet for so long now that we feel almost nervous when the Fram receives those shocks; everything seems to tremble as if in a violent earthquake.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001274","text":"Wind still unchanged, and blowing equally fresh, up to 13 or 14 metres (44 or 47 feet).","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001275","text":"The snow is drifting and sweeping so that nothing can be distinguished; the darkness is intense.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001276","text":"Abaft on the deck there are deep mounds of snow lying round the wheel and the rails, so that when we go up on deck we get a genuine sample of an Arctic winter.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001277","text":"This morning Pettersen, who has had charge of the dogs this week, came down to the saloon and asked whether some one would come out with him on the ice with a rifle, as he was sure there was a bear.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001278","text":"The dogs left off barking when we arrived on the scene, and commenced to play with each other.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001279","text":"But Pettersen was right in saying that it was 'horrid weather,' it was almost enough to take away one's breath to face the wind, and the drifting snow forced its way into the mouth and nostrils.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001280","text":"The barometer had been falling steadily and rapidly, but at last it has commenced to rise slightly.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001281","text":"In the afternoon it rose steadily until it registered -21.3°C.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001282","text":"Now it appears to be falling again a little, but the wind still keeps exactly in the same quarter.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001283","text":"It has surely shifted us by now a good way to the north, well beyond the 83d degree.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001284","text":"It is quite pleasant to hear the wind whistling and rattling in the rigging overhead.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001285","text":"\"About midnight the mate, who has the watch, comes down and reports that the ice has cracked just beyond the thermometer house, between it and the sounding-hole.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001286","text":"This is the same crack that we had in the summer, and it has now burst open again, and probably the whole floe in which we are lying is split from the lane ahead to the lane astern of us.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001287","text":"The thermograph and other instruments are being brought on board, so that we may run no risk of losing them in the event of pressure of ice.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001288","text":"But otherwise there is scarcely anything that could be endangered.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001289","text":"The sounding apparatus is at some distance from the open channel, on the other side.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001290","text":"The only thing left there is the shears with the iron block standing over the hole.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001291","text":"Christmas has come round again, and we are still so far from home.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001292","text":"An explorer's lot is, perhaps, hard and his life full of disappointments, as they all say; but it is also full of beautiful moments--moments when he beholds the triumphs of human faith and human will, when he catches sight of the haven of success and peace.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001293","text":"\"I am in a singular frame of mind just now, in a state of sheer unrest.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001294","text":"I have not felt inclined for writing during the last few days; thoughts come and go, and carry me irresistibly ahead.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001295","text":"I can scarcely make myself out, but who can fathom the depths of the human mind.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001296","text":"The brain is a puzzling piece of mechanism: 'We are such stuff as dreams are made of.' Is it so?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001297","text":"I almost believe it--a microcosm of eternity's infinite 'stuff that dreams are made of.'","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001298","text":"\"This is the second Christmas spent far away in the solitude of night, in the realm of death, farther north and deeper into the midst of it than any one has been before.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:mortality","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001299","text":"There is something strange in the feeling; and then this, too, is our last Christmas on board the Fram.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001300","text":"The vessel is like a second home, and has become dear to us.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001301","text":"Perhaps our comrades may spend another Christmas here, possibly several, without us who will go forth from them into the midst of the solitude.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001302","text":"This Christmas passed off quietly and pleasantly, and every one seems to be well content.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001303","text":"By no means the least circumstance that added to our enjoyment was that the wind brought us the 83d degree as a Christmas-box.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001304","text":"Our luck was, this time, more lasting than I had anticipated; the wind continued fresh on Monday and Tuesday, but little by little it lulled down and veered round to the north and northeast.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001305","text":"Well, we must put up with it; one cannot help having a little contrary wind at times, and probably it will not last long.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001306","text":"\"Christmas-eve was, of course, celebrated with great feasting.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001307","text":"The table presented a truly imposing array of Christmas confectionery: 'Poor man's' pastry, 'Staghorn' pastry, honey-cakes, macaroons, 'Sister' cake, and what not, besides sweets and the like; many may have fared worse.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001308","text":"The others seemed to enjoy it too, and, of course, many toasts were drunk in this noble beverage.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001309","text":"Quantities of illustrated books were then brought forth; there was music, and stories, and songs, and general merriment.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001310","text":"After dinner coffee and curaçao made here on board, and Nordahl then came forward with Russian cigarettes.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001311","text":"At night a bowl of cloudberry punch was served out, which did not seem by any means unwelcome.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001312","text":"Mogstad played the violin, and Pettersen was electrified thereby to such a degree that he sang and danced to us.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001313","text":"He really exhibits considerable talent as a comedian, and has a decided bent towards the ballet.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001314","text":"It is astonishing what versatility he displays: engineer, blacksmith, tinsmith, cook, master of ceremonies, comedian, dancer, and, last of all, he has come out in the capacity of a first-class barber and hair-dresser.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001315","text":"There was a grand 'ball' at night; Mogstad had to play till the perspiration poured from him; Hansen and I had to figure as ladies.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001316","text":"He faithfully and solemnly vowed that if he has a pair of boots to his feet when he gets home he will dance as long as the soles hold together.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001317","text":"\"Day after day, as we progressed with a rattling wind, first from S.E.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001318","text":"and E., we felt more anxious to know how far we had got; but there had always been a snow-storm or a cloudy sky, so that we could not make any observations.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001319","text":"We were all confident that we must have got a long way up north, but how far beyond the 83d degree no one could tell.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001320","text":"Suddenly Hansen was called on deck this afternoon by the news that the stars were visible overhead.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001321","text":"But when he came down he had only observed one star, which, however, was so near the meridian that he could calculate that, at any rate, we were north of 83° 20' north latitude, and this communication was received with shouts of joy.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001322","text":"If we were not yet in the most northerly latitude ever reached by man, we were, at all events, not far from it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001323","text":"This was more than we had expected, and we were in high spirits.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001324","text":"About 4 o'clock this morning the vessel received a violent shock which made everything tremble, but no noise of ice-packing was to be heard.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001325","text":"At about half-past five I heard at intervals the crackling and crunching of the pack-ice which was surging in the lane ahead.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001326","text":"At night similar noises were also heard; otherwise the ice was quiet, and the crack on the port-side has closed up tight again.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001327","text":"I went out in the morning to have a look at the crack on the port side which has now widened out so as to form an open lane.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001328","text":"Of course, all the dogs followed me, and I had not got far when I saw a dark form disappear.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001329","text":"This was 'Pan,' who rolled down the high steep edge of the ice and fell into the water.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001330","text":"In vain he struggled to get out again; all around him there was nothing but snow slush, which afforded no foothold.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001331","text":"I could scarcely hear a sound of him, only just a faint whining noise now and then.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001332","text":"I leaned down over the edge in order to get near him, but it was too high, and I very nearly went after him head-first; all that I could get hold of was loose fragments of ice and lumps of snow.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001333","text":"When he fell in they all rushed forward, looking at me and whining; they evidently felt sorry for him and wished me to help him.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001334","text":"They said nothing, but just ran up and down along the edge until he got out.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001335","text":"At another moment, perhaps, they may all unite in tearing him to pieces; such is canine and human nature.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001336","text":"'Pan' was allowed to dry himself in the saloon all the afternoon.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001337","text":"\"A little before half-past nine to-night the vessel received a tremendous shock.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001338","text":"However, the wind howled so in the rigging that it was not easy to distinguish any other sound.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001339","text":"At half-past ten another shock followed; later on, from time to time, vibrations were felt in the vessel, and towards half-past eleven the shocks became stronger.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001340","text":"It was clear that the ice was packing at some place or other about us, and I was just on the point of going out when Mogstad came to announce that there was a very ugly pressure-ridge ahead.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001341","text":"Fifty-six paces from the bow there extended a perpendicular ridge stretching along the course of the lane, and there was a terrible pressure going on at the moment.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001342","text":"It roared and crunched and crackled all along; then it abated a little and recurred at intervals, as though in a regular rhythm; finally it passed over into a continuous roar.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001343","text":"It seemed to be mostly newly frozen ice from the channels which had formed this ridge; but there were also some ponderous blocks of ice to be seen among it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001344","text":"It pressed slowly but surely forward towards the vessel; the ice had given way before it to a considerable distance and was still being borne down little by little.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001345","text":"The floe around us has cracked, so that the block of ice in which the vessel is embedded is smaller than it was.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001346","text":"I should not like to have that pressure-ridge come in right under the nose of the Fram, as it might soon do some damage.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001347","text":"Although there is hardly any prospect of its getting so far, nevertheless I have given orders to the watch to keep a sharp lookout; and if it comes very near, or if the ice should crack under us, he is to call me.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001348","text":"Probably the pressure will soon abate, as it has now kept up for several hours.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001349","text":"At this moment (12.45 A.M.) there have just been some violent shocks, and above the howling of the wind in the rigging I can hear the roar of the ice-pressure as I lie in my berth.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001350","text":"Never before have I had such strange feelings at the commencement of the new year.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001351","text":"It cannot fail to bring some momentous events, and will possibly become one of the most remarkable years in my life, whether it leads me to success or to destruction.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001352","text":"Years come and go unnoticed in this world of ice, and we have no more knowledge here of what these years have brought to humanity than we know of what the future ones have in store.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001353","text":"In this silent nature no events ever happen; all is shrouded in darkness; there is nothing in view save the twinkling stars, immeasurably far away in the freezing night, and the flickering sheen of the aurora borealis.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001354","text":"I can just discern close by the vague outline of the Fram, dimly standing out in the desolate gloom, with her rigging showing dark against the host of stars.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001355","text":"Like an infinitesimal speck, the vessel seems lost amidst the boundless expanse of this realm of death.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. I","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001356","text":"E-text prepared by Julia Miller, Mary Meehan, and the Online Distributed Proofreading Team (http://www.pgdp.net) from page images generously made available by Internet Archive/American Libraries (http://www.archive.org/details/americana)","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001357","text":"Note: Project Gutenberg also has an HTML version of this file which includes the original illustrations. See 34121-h.htm or 34121-h.zip: (https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/34121/pg34121-images.html) or (https://www.gutenberg.org/files/34121/34121-h.zip)","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001358","text":"Images of the original pages are available through Internet Archive/American Libraries. See http://www.archive.org/details/calavartheknight00birdrich","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001359","text":"Escucha pues, un rato, y dire cosas Estranas y espantosas, poco a poco.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001360","text":"Redfield 110 And 112 Nassau Street, New York. Third Edition.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001361","text":"Entered according to the act of Congress in the year 1834, by Carey, Lea, & Blanchard, in the clerk's office of the district court for the eastern district of Pennsylvania.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001362","text":"It was a part of the original design to prepare the way for a history of Mexico, which the author meditated; a design which was, however, soon abandoned.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001363","text":"There was then little interest really felt in Mexican affairs, which presented, as they have always done since the first insurrection of Hidalgo, a scene of desperate confusion, not calculated to elevate republican institutions in the opinions of the world.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001364","text":"Even the events in Texas had not, at that time, attracted much attention.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001365","text":"Mexico was, in the popular notion, regarded as a part of _South_ America, the _alter ego_ almost of Peru,--beyond the world, and the concerns of Americans.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001366","text":"There was little thought, and less talk, of \"the halls of the Montezumas;\" and the ancient Mexican history was left to entertain school-boys, in the pages of Robertson.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001367","text":"\"Calavar\" effected its more important purpose, as far as could be expected of a mere work of fiction.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001368","text":"The revolution of Texas, which dismembered from the mountain republic the finest and fairest portion of her territory, attracted the eyes and speculations of the world; and from that moment, Mexico has been an object of regard.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001369","text":"There is, indeed, a remarkable parallel between the invasions of the two great captains.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001370","text":"We might say, perhaps, that there is the same purpose of conquest: but we do not believe that the American people aim at, or desire, the subjugation of Mexico.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001371","text":"\"Calavar\" was designed to describe the first campaign, or first year, of Cortes in Mexico.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001372","text":"The republication has, indeed, been suggested and called for by numerous persons desirous to obtain copies of the book, which has been for some time out of print.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001373","text":"The revival of the romance might have furnished its author an opportunity to remove many faults which, he is sensible, exist in it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001374","text":"Long dialogues might have been contracted, heavy descriptions lightened or expunged, and antiquated phraseology modernized, with undoubted benefit.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001375","text":"He gazed and mused, until fancy peopled the scene around him with spectral life, and his spirit's eye was opened on spectacles never more to be revealed to the corporeal organ.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001376","text":"It opened on the day when the land was a wilderness, shaking for the first time under the foot of a stranger; and he beheld, as in a vision, the various emigrations and irruptions into the vale, of men born in other climates.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001377","text":"They came like the tides of ocean, and, as such, passed away,--like shadows, and so departed; the history of ages was compressed into the representation of a moment, and an hundred generations, assembled together as one people, rushed by in successive apparitions.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001378","text":"Thus they rested and multiplied, until the barbarians of the hills,--the earlier races, and perhaps the aborigines of the land,--descended to take counsel of their wisdom, and follow in the ways of civilization.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001379","text":"From the eastern hills came the voice of the Old World--the sound of the battle-trumpet; the smoke of artillery rolled over the lake; and, in a moment more, the shout of conquest and glory was answered by the groan of a dying nation.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001380","text":"As for this fair valley of Mexico, there was scarcely an object either of beauty or utility, the creation of Christian wants or Christian taste, to be seen, for which his memory could not trace a rival, or superior, which existed in the day of paganism.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:justice","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001381","text":"The question was one to which the rambler could not conceive an answer without pain.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001382","text":"'The ways of Providence,' he murmured, 'are indeed inscrutable; the designs of Him who layeth the corner-stone and buildeth up the fabric of destiny, unfathomable.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001383","text":"Two mighty empires,--the only states which seemed to be leading the new world to civilization,--were broken, and at an expense of millions of lives, barbarously destroyed; and for what purpose?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001384","text":"How much better or happier are the present races of Peru and Mexico, than the past?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001385","text":"The traveller muttered the conclusion of his speculations aloud, and, insensibly to himself, in the Spanish tongue, totally unconscious of the presence of a second person, until made aware of it by a voice exclaiming suddenly, as if in answer, and in the same language--","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001386","text":"\"Right! very right! _pecador de mi!_ sinner that I am, that _I_ should not have thought it, for the honour of God and my country!\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001387","text":"The stranger turned, and perceived that the words came from a man dressed in a long loose surtout or gown of black texture, none of the newest, with a hat of Manilla grass, umbrageous as an oak-top.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001388","text":"He looked old and infirm; his person was very meager; his cheeks were of a mahogany hue, and hollow, and the little hair that stirred over them in the evening breeze, was of a sable silvered: his eyes were large, restless, exceedingly bright, and irascible.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001389","text":"The whole air of the man was unique, but not mean; and the traveller did not doubt, at the first glance, that he belonged to some inferior order of ecclesiastics, and was perhaps the curate of a neighbouring village.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001390","text":"you have said the truth!\" he continued, regarding the traveller eagerly, and, as the latter thought, with profound veneration; \"I must speak with you, very learned stranger, for I perceive you are a philosopher.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001391","text":"In a single word, you have revealed the secret that has been the enigma of a long life, made good the justice of heaven, and defended the fame of my country.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:justice","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001392","text":"I am grateful to your wisdom: you speak like a saint: you are a philosopher!\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:gratitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001393","text":"\"Father,\" said he, \"reverend father--for I perceive you are one of the clergy----\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001394","text":"\"The poor licentiate, Cristobal Johualicahuatzin, curate of the parish of San Pablo de Chinchaluca,\" interrupted the ecclesiastic meekly, and in fact with the greatest humility.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001395","text":"\"Then, indeed, very excellent and worthy father Cristobal,\" resumed the stranger, courteously, \"though I do not pretend to understand you----\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001396","text":"The padre raised his head; his meekness vanished; he eyed the traveller with a sharp and indignant frown:","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001397","text":"\"_Gachupin!_\" he cried; \"you are a man with two souls: you are wise and you are foolish, and you speak bad Spanish!--Why do you insult me?\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001398","text":"The stranger stared at his new acquaintance with fresh amazement.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001399","text":"\"Insult you, father!\" he exclaimed. \"I declare to you, I have, this moment, woke out of a revery; and I scarcely know what you have said or what I have answered, or what you are saying and what I am answering. If I have offended you, I ask your pardon.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001400","text":"right!\" said the curate, with an air of satisfaction; \"you are a philosopher; you are right.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001401","text":"You have instructed my ignorance, and appeased my repining; you have taught me the answer to a vast and painful riddle; and now I perceive why Providence hath given over my native land to seeming ruin, and permitted it to become a place of dust and sand, of dry-rot and death.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001402","text":"The day of darkness shall come again,--it is coming; man merges again into gloom, and now we fall into the age of stone, when the hearts of men shall be as flint.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001403","text":"This then shall be the valley of resuscitation, after it is first _plenus ossibus_, full of skeletons, an ossuary--a place of moral ossification.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001404","text":"and you shall know my gratitude: for great joy is it to the child of Moteuczoma, to know there shall be an end to this desolation, this anarchy, this horror!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:gratitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001405","text":"Came I into the world to watch in sorrow and fear for ever? _Hijo mio!_ give me thy hand; I love thee. The vale of Anahuac is not deformed for nothing; Christian man has ruined it, but not for a long season!\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001406","text":"The Cura delivered this rhapsody with extreme animation; his eye kindled, he spoke with a rapid and confused vehemence; and the stranger began to doubt the stability of his understanding.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001407","text":"He flung his bundle to the earth, and grasped the hand of the philosopher, who, until this moment, was ignorant of the depth of his own wisdom.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001408","text":"\"It is very true; I regret it no longer, but it cannot be denied: The cutting through yonder hill of Nochistongo has given the last blow in a system of devastation; the canal of Huehuetoca has emptied the golden pitcher of Moteuczoma.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001409","text":"It has converted the valley into a desert, and will depopulate it.--Men cannot live upon salt.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001410","text":"do you pretend to deny it?\" cried the Cura, picking up his bundle, and thumping it with energy.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001411","text":"\"I aver, and I will prove it to your satisfaction, out of these books, which--But hold!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001412","text":"No; you are not of Mexico: the cameo on your breast bears the device of stars, the symbol of intellectual as well as political independence.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001413","text":"I reverence that flag; I saw it, when your envoy, attacked by an infuriated mob, in his house in yonder very city, (I stole there in spite of them!) sprang upon the balcony, and waved it abroad in the street.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001414","text":"Frenzy vanished at the sight: it was the banner of man's friend!--No!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001415","text":"you are no fool with a free arm, a licentious tongue, and a soul in chains.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001416","text":"The bondmen of the old world wake from sleep and live, while we, in the blessed light of sunshine, wrap the mantle round our eyes, sleep, and perish!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001417","text":"By revolution, other nations are liberated, but we, by revolution, are enslaved.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001418","text":"\"It is true,\" said the American. \"But let us not speak of this: it is galling to be able to inveigh against folly without possessing the medicament for its cure.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001419","text":"\"Thou art an American of the North,\" said the Cura; \"thy people are wise, thy rulers are servants, and you are happy!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:leadership","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001420","text":"I thought thee a sage, but, I perceive, thou hast the rashness of youth.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001421","text":"\"And what, then, are these?\" demanded the traveller, curiously, laying his hand on the bundle, \"which can teach Americans to admire the beauty of a republic, and yet are not given to thine own countrymen?\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001422","text":"\"They are,\" said the curate, \"the fruits of years of reflection and toil, of deep research and profound speculation.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001423","text":"A history wherein,\" continued the padre, with great complacency, \"I flatter myself, though Mexicans have found much to detest, Americans will discover somewhat to approve.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001424","text":"\"What is it,\" said the rambler, \"which your people have found so objectionable?\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001425","text":"\"Listen,\" said the padre, \"and you shall be informed. In me,\"--here he paused, and surveyed his acquaintance with as much majesty as he could infuse into his wasted figure and hollow countenance,--\"in me you behold a descendant of Moteuczoma Xocojotzin.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001426","text":"Perhaps you are also ignorant of the great names of Tizoc, of Xocotzin, and of Ixtlilxochitl?\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001427","text":"\"I have no doubt,\" replied the American, with courteous humility, \"that in the histories of Mexico, which I have ever delighted to read,--in the books of De Solis, of Clavigero, of Bernal Diaz del Castillo, and especially in that of Dr.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001428","text":"Robertson,--I have met these illustrious names; but you must allow, that, to one ignorant of the language, and of the mode of pronouncing such conglomerated grunts, it must be extremely difficult, if not wholly impossible, to rivet them in the memory.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001429","text":"The curate snatched up his bundle, and surveyed the stranger with a look in which it was hard to tell whether anger or contempt bore the greater sway.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001430","text":"\"De Solis! Diaz! Clavigero! Robertson!\" he at last exclaimed, irefully. \"_Basta! demasiado?_ What a _nino_, a little child, a _pobre Yankee_, have I fallen upon! That I should waste my words on a man who studies Mexican history out of the books of these jolterheads!\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001431","text":"The padre was about to depart, without bestowing another word on the offender.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001432","text":"The American was amused at the ready transition of the curate from deep reverence to the most unbounded contempt.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001433","text":"He was persuaded the wits of the poor father were unsettled, and felt there was the greater need to humour and appease him: and, besides, he was curious to discover what would be the end of the adventure.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001434","text":"\"Father,\" said he, with composure, \"before you condemn me for acquiring my little knowledge from these books, you should put it in my power to read better.\"--The padre looked back.--\"What information should be expected from incompetent writers?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001435","text":"When I have perused the histories of father Cristobal, it will then be _my_ fault, if I am found ignorant of the names of his imperial ancestors.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001436","text":"\"_Ay de mi!_\" said the curate, striking his forehead; \"why did I not think of that before?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001437","text":"_Santos santisimos!_ I am not so quick-witted as I was before.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001438","text":"I could forgive you more readily, had you not named to me that infidel Scotchman, who calls the superb Moteuczoma a savage, and all the Tlatoani, the great princes, and princesses, the people and all, barbarians!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001439","text":"\"Say nothing about it; form or creed, ceremony or canon, you are in the way to be lost.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001440","text":"Open your ears, unbind your eyes--hear, see, and believe!--Poor, miserable darkened creature!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001441","text":"how can your heretical understanding be made to conceive and profit by the great principles of philosophy, when it is blind to the truths of religion?\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001442","text":"\"Reverend padre,\" said the traveller, drily, \"my people are a people of heretics, and yours of Catholic believers. Which has better understood, or better practised, the principles of the philosophy you affect to admire?\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001443","text":"The padre smote his forehead a second time: \"The sneer is, in this case, just!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001444","text":"But let us not waste time in argument: as babes may be made the organs of wisdom, so may heretics be suffered as the instruments of worldly benefaction.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001445","text":"What thou sayest, is true; unbelievers as ye are, ye will comprehend and be instructed by truths, which, in this land, would be misconceived and opposed; and from you may the knowledge you gain, be reflected back on my own people.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001446","text":"In these books, which I commit to you for a great purpose, you will learn who were those worthies of whom I spoke.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001447","text":"You will perceive how Ixtlilxochitl, the king of Tezcuco, was descended from the house that gave birth to Moteuczoma.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001448","text":"With its glory, it has conferred the penalty to be suspected, opposed, and trampled.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001449","text":"Three historians of the name, my ancestors, have already written in vain; jealousy has locked up their works in darkness, in the veil of manuscript; the privilege of chronicling and perverting the history of the land is permitted only to Spaniards, to strangers, to Gachupins.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001450","text":"Twenty years since, and more, the books I composed, wherein the truth was told, and the injustice of Spanish writers made manifest, were condemned by ignorance and bigotry to such flames as consumed, at Tezcuco, all the native chronicles of Anahuac.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:justice","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001451","text":"But what was written in my books, was also recorded in the brain; fire could not be put to my memory.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001452","text":"here is my history; I give it to you.--My enemies must be content with the ashes!\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001453","text":"The padre rubbed his hands with exultation, as the traveller surveyed the bundle.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001454","text":"\"Why should you fear a similar fate for these volumes, now?\" said the latter. \"Times are changed.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001455","text":"Hide them, let no man see them; or the pile will be kindled again; all will be lost--I cannot repair the loss a second time, for now I am old!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001456","text":"Five years have I borne them with me, night and day, seeking for some one cunning and faithful, wise like thyself, to whom to commit them.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001457","text":"I have found thee; thou art the man; I am satisfied: _buen provecho_, much good may they do you,--not you only, but your people,--not your people alone, but the world!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001458","text":"Affection for country is love of mankind; true patriotism is philanthropy.--Five years have I borne them with me, by night and by day.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001459","text":"\"Really, I think that this betokened no great fear for their safety.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001460","text":"The padre laughed. \"Though the Gachupin and the bigot would rob me of a Spanish dissertation, yet neither would envy me the possession of a few rolls of hieroglyphics.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001461","text":"As he exhibited his treasure, he looked up for approbation to the American.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001462","text":"\"Father,\" said he, \"you have succeeded to admiration, under this goodly disguise, not only in concealing your wisdom from the penetration of your countrymen, but, as I think, the whole world.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001463","text":"The padre raised his finger to his nose very significantly, saying, with a chuckle of delight,--the delight of a diseased brain in the success of its cunning,--","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001464","text":"\"This time, I knew I should throw dust in their eyes, even though they might demand, for their satisfaction, to look into my work.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001465","text":"You perceive, that this volume, done up after the true manner of ancient Mexican books, unrolls from either end.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001466","text":"The first pages, and the last, of each volume, contain duplicates of the first and the last chapters, done in Mexican characters: the rest is in Spanish, and, I flatter myself, in very choice Spanish.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001467","text":"_Hoc ego recte_--I knew what I was about.--One does not smuggle diamonds in sausages, without stuffing in some of the minced meat.--Here is the jewel!\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001468","text":"So saying, and spreading the sheet at its full length, so as to discover his hidden records, the padre rose to his feet, and began to dance about with exultation.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001469","text":"\"And what am _I_ to do with these volumes?\" said the traveller, after pondering awhile over the manuscripts.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001470","text":"Take them, hide them in your bosom, as you would the soul of some friend you were smuggling into paradise.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001471","text":"Leave this land forthwith, on any pretence; bear them with you; translate them into your own tongue, and let them be given to the world.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001472","text":"As for my countrymen, were it even possible they could be persuaded to spare these pages, and to read them, they would read them in vain.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001473","text":"They are a thousand years removed from civilization, and the wisdom of this book would be to them as folly.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001474","text":"The barbaric romance which loiters about the brains even of European nations, is the pith and medulla of a Mexican head.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001475","text":"The poetry of bloodshed, the sentiment of renown,--the first and last passion, and the true test, of the savage state,--are not yet removed from us.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001476","text":"We are not yet civilized up to the point of seeing that reason reprobates, human happiness denounces, and God abhors, the splendour of contention.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001477","text":"Your own people--the happiest and most favoured of modern days,--are, perhaps, not so backward.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001478","text":"The heretic sighed.--The padre went on, and with the smile of generosity,--tying, at the same time, the string that secured the volume, and knotting it again into the bundle.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001479","text":"\"The profits which may accrue from the publication, I freely make over to you, as some recompense for the trouble of translation, and the danger you run in assuming the custody.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001480","text":"you shake your head!--What a pity, I am compelled to entrust this great commission to a man who refuses to be a Christian!\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001481","text":"\"Buen padre, let us say nothing about that: judge me not by the creed I profess, but by the acts I perform.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001482","text":"Let us despatch this business: the moon is bright, but the air is raw and unwholesome.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001483","text":"I would willingly do your bidding, not doubting that the world will be greatly advantaged thereby.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001484","text":"But, father, here is the difficulty:--To do justice to your composition, I should, myself, possess the skill of an author; but, really, I feel my incompetency--I am no bookmaker.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001485","text":"\"And am I?\" said the descendant of Moteuczoma, indignantly; \"I am an historian!\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001486","text":"\"And who said you were?\" demanded the historian, with contempt.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001487","text":"\"Do I expect of you the qualifications or the labours of an historian?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001488","text":"to wade through the fathers of stupidity, until your brain turns to dough, and your eyes to pots of glue?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001489","text":"to gather materials with the labour of a pearl-diver, and then to digest and arrange, to methodise and elucidate, with the patient martyrdom of an almanac-maker?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001490","text":"I ask you to read and render,--to translate;--to do the tailor's office, and make my work a new coat!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001491","text":"\"Father,\" said the traveller, \"your arguments are unanswerable; do me the favour to send, or to bring, your production to the city, to the Calle----\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001492","text":"Know, that by the sentence of the archbishop and the command of the viceroy, I am interdicted from the city: and know that I would sooner put my soul into the keeping of a parrot, than my books into the hands of a messenger!\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001493","text":"It has been many long years since a king's ape has played his delegated antics in Mexico.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001494","text":"\"May I die,\" said the philosopher, in no little embarrassment, \"but this lunatic Cura has left me to lug away his lucubrations,--his hieroglyphical infants, for which I am to make new coats,--on my own shoulders!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001495","text":"I can but carry them to the city, and seek some means of restoring them to his friends, or commit them to a more fitting depository.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001496","text":"Pray heaven I meet no drunken Indian, or debauched soldado on my way.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001497","text":"By great good fortune, he was able, in a few days, with the assistance of a friendly Mexican, to solve the secret of the padre's confidence.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001498","text":"\"You have seen him then?\" said the excellent Senor Don Andres Santa-Maria de Arcaboba, laughing heartily at the grave earnestness with which his heretical friend inquired after the eccentric padre.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001499","text":"Ever his books in his hand, much praise with the offer, and seven times seven maledictions when you refuse his bantlings.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001500","text":"\"_Demonios!_ were you long finding it out? Ever since the old archbishop burned his first heathenish volumes, he has done naught but----\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001501","text":"\"I beg your pardon.--Burn his books?--the old archbishop?--Pray enlighten me a little on the subject of the good father's history.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001502","text":"\"'Tis done in a moment,\" said Don Andres; \"the only wonder is that he did not himself give you the story; that being, commonly, the prelude to his petition.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001503","text":"The mother of Don Cristobal was an Indian _damisela_, delighting in the euphonical cognomen of Ixtlilxochitl; a name, which, I am told, belonged to some old pagan king or other, the Lord knows who--as for myself, I know nothing about it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001504","text":"But this set the padre mad, or, what's the same thing, it made him an historian.--'Tis a silly thing to trouble one's noddle about the concerns of our granddads: let them sleep!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001505","text":"rest to their bones--_Asi sea!_--They made him a licenciado, and then Cura of some hacienda or other, out among the hills--I know nothing about it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001506","text":"He wrote a book, in which he proved that the old heathen Montezuma, the great Cacique, was a saint, and Hernan Cortes, who conquered the land, a sinner.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001507","text":"This was before the revolution--that is, before the first: (we have had five hundred since;--I never counted them.) Somehow, the viceroy Vanegas took a dislike to the book, and so did the archbishop.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001508","text":"So they burned it, and commanded Johualicahuatzin--(that's another Indian king--so he calls himself.--His father was the Senor Marhojo, a creole, a lieutenant in the viceroy's horse, a very worthy Christian, who was hanged somewhere, for sedition.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001509","text":"But Cristobal writes after his mother's name, as being more royal.)--What was I saying?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001510","text":"Then, what became of him, the lord knows; I don't.--Then came Hidalgo, the valiant priest of Dolores, with his raggamuffin patriots,--(I don't mean any reflection, being a patriot myself, though no fighter; but Hidalgo had a horrid crew about him!) Where was I?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001511","text":"Oh, ay,--Hidalgo came to knock the city about our ears; and Cristobal, being seized with a fit of blood-thirstiness, joins me the gang.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001512","text":"They say, he came with an old sabre of flint--I don't know the name; it belonged to some king in the family.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001513","text":"Then Calleja, whom they made viceroy--the devil confound him!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001514","text":"(He cut my uncle's throat, with some fourteen thousand others, at Guanaxuato, one day, to save powder.)--Calleja chased Hidalgo to Aculco, and, there, he beat him.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001515","text":"Cristobal's brother (he _had_ a brother, a very fine young fellow, a patriot major;) was killed at Cristobal's side; Cristobal was knocked on the head,--somebody said, with his own royal weapon:--I don't know,--where's the difference?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001516","text":"Being a notorious crazy man, and very savagely mauled, they did not hang him.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001517","text":"He writes histories, and, to save them from viceroys, (he takes all our presidents for viceroys: to my mind, they _are_; but that's nothing.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001518","text":"\"_Fuego!_ you took them? Ha, ha! now will the poor padre die happy!\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001519","text":"they are all in heaven; he is the last of the Ixtlilxochitls!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001520","text":"I beg your pardon; but if you offer them to any body, never believe me, but folks will take you for Cristobal the Second, _el segundo maniatico_, or some one he has hired to do the work of donation.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001521","text":"Burn them; or take them to America, to your North, and deposit them in a museum, as the commonplace books of Montezuma.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001522","text":"_Vamos; que me manda vm.?_ will you ride to the Alameda?--Pobre Cristobal!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001523","text":"The traveller returned to his own land: he bore with him the books of Cristobal.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001524","text":"The task of collating and methodising the disjointed portions, required, in the words of the padre himself, the devotedness which he had figured as 'the patient martyrdom of an almanac-maker;' it was entirely too much for the traveller.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001525","text":"He laid the riddle aside for future investigation: but Cristobal was not forgotten.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001526","text":"A year afterwards, in reading a Mexican gazette, which had fallen into his hands, his eye wandered to the little corner which appeals so placidly to the feelings of the contemplative,--the place of obituaries.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001527","text":"His attention was instantly captivated by a name in larger characters than the others.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001528","text":"Pobre Cristobal!--'_El Licenciado_ Cristobal Santiago Marhojo y Ixtlilxochitl, _Cura de la Hacienda de_ Chinchaluca, _ordinariamente llamado_ El Maniatico Historiador'----.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001529","text":"the common immortality of a long paragraph?--The heretic rubbed his eyes.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001530","text":"if thy work be at all readable, departed padre, it shall have the new coat!'","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001531","text":"Great was the surprise of the philosopher, when having, at the suggestion of the gazetteer, cut the folded sheet of a volume, he beheld the chaos of history reduced to order.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001532","text":"There they were, the annals of Aztecs and Toltecs, of Chechemecs and Chiapanecs, and a thousand other _Ecs_, from the death of Nezahualcojotl, the imperial poet, up to the confusion of tongues.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001533","text":"\"Here's a nut for the philosophers,\" quoth the traveller; \"but now for a peep at Montezuma!--Poor Cristobal!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001534","text":"How many days and nights were given to the examination of the history, we do not think fit to record.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001535","text":"It is enough, that the inheritor of this treasure discovered with satisfaction, that, if Cristobal had been mad, he had been mad after a rule,--dramatically so: he was sane in the right places.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001536","text":"A thousand eccentricities were, indeed, imbodied in his work, the result, doubtless, of a single aberration, in which he persuaded himself that men were yet barbarians, and that civilization, even to the foremost of nations, was yet unknown.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001537","text":"In other respects, he was sane, somewhat judicious, and, as far as could be expected in an historian, a teller of the truth.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001538","text":"His work consisted of several divisions; it was, in fact, a series of annals, relating to different epochs.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:leadership","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001539","text":"Of these, that volume which treated of the Conquest of Mexico, had the most charms for the traveller; and he thought it would possess the most interest for the world.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001540","text":"It differed greatly from common histories in one particular; it descended to minutiae of personal adventure, and was, indeed, as much a general memoir of the great _Conquistadores_ as a history of the fall of Tenochtitlan.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001541","text":"_Por Cristobal Johualicahuatzin Santiago Marhojo y Ixtlilxochitl_;\"--that is to say, 'A Chronicle of the Conquest of Mexico, and true History of the Conquerors, especially of those Cavaliers who were neglected by the ancient authors.'","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001542","text":"The first portion of this,--for there were several,--treated of those events which occurred between the departure of the first army of invasion from Cuba, and its expulsion from Mexico, and this portion the executor of Cristobal resolved to present to the world.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001543","text":"In pursuance of this resolution, he instituted a long and laborious comparison of the MS.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001544","text":"It is true, the narrative was more diffuse, perhaps we should say, verbose; but Cristobal lived in an age of amplification.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001545","text":"He shaved, therefore, and he cut, he amputated and he compressed; and he felt the joy of an editor, when exercising the hydraulic press of the mind.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001546","text":"This will be excused in him. He expunged as much of the philosophy as he could. The few principles at variance with worldly propensities, which he left in the book, must be referred to another responsibility.--The hallucinations of philanthropy are, at the worst, harmless.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001547","text":"For the title adopted in this, the initial chronicle, he confesses himself answerable.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001548","text":"The peculiar appetites of the literary community, the result of intellectual dyspepsia, require and justify empiricism in nomenclature.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001549","text":"If it should be objected, that he has called the _Historia Verdadera_ a romance, let it be remembered, that the world likes romance better than truth, as the booksellers can testify; and that the history of Mexico, under all aspects but that of fiction, is itself----a romance.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001550","text":"In his language, for example, the G, when before the vowels E and I, the J always, and, in certain cases, the X, have the value of the aspirate.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001551","text":"Thus, the name of the city, the chief scene of our history, has been spelled, at different times, _Mexico_, _Mejico_, and _Megico_; yet is always pronounced _May-he-co_.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001552","text":"The sound of our W he represents by HU,--as _Huascar_, for Wascar; and, indeed, JU has nearly the same sound, as in _Juan_.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001553","text":"The names Johualicahuatzin, Anahuac, Xocojotzin, Mexitli, and Chihuahua, pronounced Howalicawatzin, Anawac, Hocohotzin, Meheetlee, and Chewawa, will serve for examples.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001554","text":"But this is a thing not to be insisted on, so much as the degree of belief which should be accorded to the relation.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001555","text":"Esto importa poco a nuestro cuento: basta que en la narracion de el, no se salga un punto de la verdad.--_Don Quijote._","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001556","text":"He had seen, in the revolution of a day, the strange transformations which a few years had brought upon all the climes and races of his love.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001557","text":"He passed on his course: the breakers that dashed upon the sands of Africa, were not whiter than the squadrons that rolled among them; the chapel was built on the shore, and under the shadow of the crucifix was fastened the first rivet in the slavery of her miserable children.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001558","text":"The fate of Mexico was in the scales of destiny; the second army of invaders had been poured upon her shores.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001559","text":"Of the four-score individuals who crowded the decks of the little caravel, there was not one whose countenance, at that spectacle, did not betray a touch of the enthusiasm,--the mingled lust of glory and of lucre,--which had already transformed so many ruffians into heroes.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001560","text":"In addition to these badges of devotion, he wore a cross of gold, pointed like the former, and suspended to his neck by a chain of such length and massiveness, as to imbue his companions with high notions of his rank and affluence.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001561","text":"The only point in which he exhibited any feeling in common with his companions, was in admiration of the noble prospect that stretched before him, and which was every moment disclosing itself with newer and greater beauty, as the wind wafted his little vessel nearer to it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001562","text":"His cheek flushed, his eye kindled, and smiting his hands together, in his ardour, he dropped so much of his dignity as to address many of his exclamations to the obsequious but not ungentle master.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001563","text":"\"By St. John! senor Capitan,\" he cried, with rapture, \"this is a most noble land to be wasted upon savages!\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001564","text":"\"True, senor Don Amador,\" replied the thrice-honoured master; \"a noble land, a rich land, a most glorious land; and, I warrant me, man has never before looked on its equal.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001565","text":"\"What then will be your admiration, noble cavalier,\" said the captain, \"when you have passed this sandy shore, and yonder rugged hills, and find yourself among the golden valleys they encompass!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001566","text":"for all those who have returned from the interior, thus speak of them, and declare upon the gospels and their honour, no man can conceive properly of paradise, until he has looked upon the valleys of Mexico.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001567","text":"Hark'ee, good captain: I know not by what sort of miracle I shall surmount yonder tall and majestic pinnacles; but it will be some consolation, while stumbling among them, to be able at least to pronounce their names.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001568","text":"What call you yon mountain to the north, with the huge, coffer-like crag on its summit?\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001569","text":"\"Your favour has even hit the name, in finding a similitude for the crag,\" said the captain.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001570","text":"\"The Indians call it by a name, which signifies the Square Mountain; but poor mariners like myself, who can scarce pronounce their prayers, much less the uncouth and horrible articulations of these barbarians, are content to call it the Coffer Mountain.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001571","text":"It lies hard by the route to the great city; and is said to be such a desolate, fire-blasted spot as will sicken a man with horror.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001572","text":"\"And yon kingly monster,\" continued the cavalier, \"that raises his snowy cone up to heaven, and mixes his smoke with the morning clouds,--that proudest of all,--what call you him?\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001573","text":"\"A most heathenish and damning belief!\" said the youth, with a devout indignation; \"and I do not marvel that heaven has given over to bondage and destruction a race stained with such beastly idolatry.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001574","text":"\"And yet they say,\" continued the captain, \"that there is a mountain of fire even taller and nobler than this, and that hard by the great city. But your worship will see this for yourself, with many other wonders, when your worship fights the savages in the interior.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001575","text":"Truly, senor caballero, these Mexicans are a warlike people.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001576","text":"The master of the caravel regarded Don Amador with admiration for a moment, and then said, with much emphasis, \"May I die the death of a mule, if I am not of your way of thinking, most noble Don Amador.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mindfulness","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001577","text":"There is neither honour nor wealth to be had in Tenochtitlan.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001578","text":"provided one have the heart to contest for them with men who fight like the wolves of Catalonia, and die with their brows to the battle!\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001579","text":"John of Jerusalem!\" said Amador, kindling with enthusiasm, \"that is a path which, as I am a true Christian and Castilian, I should be rejoiced to tread.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001580","text":"For the gold of which you speak, it might come if it would, for gold is a good thing, even to one who is neither needy nor covetous; but I should be an idle hand to gather it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001581","text":"But for the renown of subduing a nation of such valiant Pagans as those you speak of, and of converting them to the true faith!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001582","text":"\"Your favour,\" said the captain, \"has heard of the great island, Florida, and of the renowned senor Don Ponce de Leon, its discoverer?\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001583","text":"Of the extraordinary beauty and fertility of the land of Florida, thus discovered, I will say nothing.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001584","text":"Your favour will delight more to hear me speak of its inhabitants.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001585","text":"These were men of a noble stature, and full of such resolution, that we were no sooner ashore, than they fell upon us; and I must say, we found we were now at variance with a people in no wise resembling those naked idiots of Cuba, or these cowardly hinds of Mexico.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001586","text":"They cared not a jot for swordsman, arcubalister, or musketeer.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001587","text":"\"What you have said,\" quoth Don Amador, \"convinces me that these savages of Florida are a warlike people, and worthy the wrath of a brave soldier; but you have said nothing of the ores and diadems, whereof, I think, you first spake, and which, heaven save the mark!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:courage","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001588","text":"by some strange mutation of mind, have made a deeper impression on my imagination than such trifles should.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001589","text":"Wherefore, it is clear, that marvellous Fountain must be in the country of the fire-worshippers.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001590","text":"But notwithstanding all these things, senor, our commander Don Ponce, would resolve upon naught but to return to the Bahamas, where our ships were divided, each in search of the island called Bimini.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001591","text":"I was even compelled to obey them, and conduct them to Cuba.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001592","text":"\"Senor,\" said the Captain earnestly, \"I have navigated the deep for, perhaps, more years than your favour has lived; and it was my fortune to be with the Admiral----\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001593","text":"And, in after times, the words of the admiral were proved to be just; for there his captain, the young Pinzon, found the great river Oronoko.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001594","text":"\"There is no man,\" said Don Amador, \"who more reverences the memory of the admiral than I; and I feel the more regard for yourself, that you have sailed with him on his discoveries.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001595","text":"Moreover, I beg your pardon, insomuch as I have been slow to unravel your meaning.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001596","text":"But now, I perceive, you think you had reached that river of the infidel fire-worshippers, whom God confound with fire and flame!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001597","text":"\"I could not prevail upon any cavaliers, rich enough for the undertaking,\" said the master, \"to league with me in it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001598","text":"Men liked not the spirit of the northern savages; and, in truth, there were a thousand other lands where the barbarians could be subdued with less peril, and, as they thought, with a better hope of gain.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001599","text":"And yet, by our lady, that river bore with it the evidences of the wealth on its banks; for what were those scorched trees, but the relics of the fires with which the kings of the land were smelting their ores?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001600","text":"and what quantity of gold must there not have been where such prodigious furnaces were kindled!\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001601","text":"\"By the mass!\" said Amador, with ardour, \"you speak the truth; it is even a most wonderful land; and if a few thousand pesoes would float an expedition, by my faith, I think I could find them.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001602","text":"\"A few thousand pesoes, and the countenance of such a leader as Don Amador de Leste, a knight of the holy and valiant order of San Juan----\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:leadership","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001603","text":"\"And is it truly believed,\" said Amador, eagerly, \"that such waters are to be found in these heathen lands?\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001604","text":"But I know Don Ponce; the draught of youth is not for him; he will seek the fountain on his great island of Florida, and find it not: it will bubble only to the lips of those who seek it near the great river of the great continent.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001605","text":"\"By heaven!\" said Don Amador, \"what might not a man do, who could drink of this miraculous fountain!","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001606","text":"A draught of it would have carried the great Alejandro so far into the East, as to have left but small work for the knaves of Portugal.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001607","text":"But hold, senor Capitan--a thought strikes me: have you ever heard the opinion of a holy clergyman on this subject?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001608","text":"\"By my faith,\" replied the master, \"I have never heard priest or layman advance an argument against its lawfulness: and I know not how it should be criminal, since Providence hath given us the privilege to drink of any well, whose waters are not to our misliking.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001609","text":"and how should a man keep from sinning, who had no fear of death and the devil?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001610","text":"and, finally, how should we ever receive any of the benefits of the most holy atonement, after drinking such a life-preserving draught?--for it is my opinion, senor Capitan, no man would wish to go to heaven, who had the power of remaining on earth.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001611","text":"\"By my soul,\" said the captain earnestly, \"this is a consideration which never occupied me before; and I shall take counsel upon it with the first holy man I meet.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001612","text":"\"At all events,\" said the cavalier, \"there is inducement enough to make search after this river, were it only to fight the fire-worshippers, convert them to the true faith, and see what may be the curiosities of their land.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001613","text":"Yet I must give you warning, it will rest with another whom I am now seeking, whether I may league with you in this enterprise or not.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001614","text":"Give me his consent and leading, and I will take leave of these poor rogues of Tenochtitlan, as soon as I have looked a little upon their wonders; and then, with the blessing of God and St.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:gratitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001615","text":"John, have at the valiant fire-worshippers, with all my heart!--But, how now, senor Capitan?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001616","text":"What means your pilot to cast anchor here among the fleet, and not carry us forthwith to the shore?\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001617","text":"\"I dare not proceed farther,\" said the captain, \"without the authority of the senor Cavallero, admiral of this squadron, and governor of this harbour of San Juan de Ulua.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:courage","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001618","text":"It is necessary I should report myself to him for examination, on board the _Capitana_, and receive his instructions concerning my cargo and fellow-voyagers.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001619","text":"\"His instructions concerning your fellow-voyagers!\" said Don Amador, sternly.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001620","text":"\"Your favour has no cause for anger,\" said the master, moderately.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001621","text":"\"This is the custom and the law, and it becomes the more necessary to enforce it, in the present situation of things.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001622","text":"This, senor, is only a form of courtesy, such as one cavalier should expect of another, and no more.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001623","text":"\"Truly, then, if you assure me so,\" said Don Amador, complacently, \"I will not refuse to go myself in person to his excellency, the admiral; and the more readily that, I fancy, from the name, there is some sort of blood-relationship between his excellency and myself.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001624","text":"But, by heaven, I would rather, at present, be coursing Fogoso over yon glittering sand, than winding a bolero on my cousin's deck, though he were a king's admiral.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001625","text":"\"If I do not err,\" said the admiral, with a bow of great reverence, and a smile of prodigious suavity, \"I behold, in the senor Don Amador de Leste, a gentleman of Valencia, whom I make free, as I shall be proud, to welcome as my countryman and kinsman?\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001626","text":"\"Senor Almirante,\" replied Amador, with equal amenity, \"my mother was a Valencian, and of the house of Cavallero.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001627","text":"\"Surely,\" said the admiral courteously, and seemingly with great frankness, \"I will only presume to question you as a friend and relative, and, as such, no farther than it may suit your pleasure to allow.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001628","text":"My office I will only use so far as it may enable me to assist you in your objects, if, as I will make bold to believe, you may need such assistance in this land of Mexico.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:courage","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001629","text":"My superior and governor, the worthy and thrice-honoured Velasquez, (whom God grant many and wiser counsellors!) is rather hot of head and unreasonable of temper; and has, doubtless, thrown some obstructions in the way of your visit to this disturbed land.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001630","text":"But you should remember, that the junction of so brave a cavalier as Don Amador de Leste with the mutinous bands of the senor Cortes, is a thing to excite both dread and opposition.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:courage","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001631","text":"\"I give you praise for your fidelity and affection,\" said the senor Cavallero, \"which, I think, will stand the knight in good stead, if it be his pleasure to remain longer in this wild country.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001632","text":"But tell me, Don Amador:--as a Cavallero of Valencia, I could not be ignorant of the misfortune of our very renowned cousin; yet was I never able to compass the cause of his melancholy.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001633","text":"I remember that when he fleshed his boyish sword for the first time among the Moors of the Alpujarras, he was accounted not only of valour, but of discretion, far beyond his years.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001634","text":"\"Thou hast heard it suggested,\" said Cavallero, significantly, \"that, in the matter of the Alpujarras, his heart was hotter, and his hand redder than became a Christian knight, even when striking on the hearth of the Infidel?\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001635","text":"But I say this not so much to justify, as, in part, to excuse those idle impertinents, who are so free with their innuendoes.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001636","text":"It gave me great pain, and caused me no little marvel, to find he had come and vanished with so little of the retinue of his rank, and of the attendance necessary to one in his condition, that two or three ignorant grooms were his only attendants.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001637","text":"\"I have no doubt,\" said Amador, \"I can allay your wonder as to these matters.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001638","text":"Your excellency need not be told that the banner of the Turk now floats over the broken ramparts of Rhodes, and over the corses of those noble knights of San Juan, who defended them for more than two hundred years, and at last perished among their ruins.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001639","text":"This is a catastrophe that has pealed over all Christendom like the roar of a funeral bell, and its sound has even pierced to these lands of twilight.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001640","text":"No knight among all that band of warriors and martyrs, as I am myself a witness, did more brave and heroical actions throughout the black and bloody siege, than my lord and kinsman, Calavar.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:courage","theme:creativity","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001641","text":"But the good and ever-gracious Saint, the patron of this most ancient and chivalric brotherhood, saved him, with a few other knights, out of the jaws of destruction, and restored him again to his own country.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001642","text":"Rhodes was fallen, there was no longer a home for the destitute knights; they wandered over Europe, whithersoever their destinies listed, but particularly wheresoever there was an infidel to be slain.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001643","text":"Our monarch of Spain contemplated a crusade among the Moors of Barbary, the descendants of that accursed--(why should I not say wretched?","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001644","text":"for they are exiles;)--that wretched race who had once o'ermastered our own beloved land; the knight Calavar entered into this project with alacrity, and set himself to such preparations as should win him good vengeance for the blood of his brothers lost at Rhodes.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001645","text":"There was nothing left for me but to follow him in the first ship that sailed on the same adventure.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001646","text":"This I have done: I have tracked my leader from Palos to Cuba; from Cuba to this barren coast; and now, with your good leave and aidance, I will take the last step of the pursuit, and render myself up to his authority in the barbaric city, Tenochtitlan.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:leadership","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001647","text":"\"I respect your motive, and praise your devotion, most worthy cousin,\" said the admiral with much kindness; \"and yet you must forgive me, if I dare to express to you some degree of pity.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001648","text":"My long acquaintance with these countries, both of isle and main, has well instructed me what you have to expect among them; and I can truly conceive what sacrifices you have made for the good knight's sake.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001649","text":"In any case, I beg leave to apprise you, you can command all my services, either to persist in seeking him, or to return to Spain.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001650","text":"I do not say I come hither to condescend to this ignoble warfare,--though if it be worthy my good knight, _I_ shall have no reason to scorn it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001651","text":"\"Your journey will be neither so long nor so wearisome as you imagine,\" said Cavallero: \"but, I fear me, will present more obstructions than you may be prepared to encounter.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001652","text":"I take it for granted, the governor Velasquez has furnished you with no commands to his general Don Panfilo de Narvaez, since he gave you none to myself.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001653","text":"\"This is even the fact,\" said Amador; \"I entered the caravel which brought me here, as I thought, in defiance of his authority, and not without apprehensions of being obliged to cut off the ears of some dozen or two of his rogues, who might be ordered to detain me.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001654","text":"Nevertheless, I left the island without a contest, and equally without aidance of any kind from this discourteous ruler.\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001655","text":"\"I must give thee some counsel, then,\" said the admiral, \"for I apprehend the governor did, very perfidiously as I esteem it, when he ceased his opposition, rest much hope on that of his general. Thou art acquainted with the character of Narvaez?\"","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. II","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001656","text":"BY SAMUEL DILL, M.A. HON. LITT.D. DUBLIN, HON. LL.D. EDINBURGH, HON. FELLOW AND LATE TUTOR, C.C.C., OXFORD; PROFESSOR OF GREEK IN QUEEN’S COLLEGE, BELFAST; AUTHOR OF “ROMAN SOCIETY IN THE LAST CENTURY OF THE WESTERN EMPIRE”","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001657","text":"There must always be something arbitrary in the choice and isolation of a period of social history for special study.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001658","text":"No period can, from one point of view, be broken off and isolated from the immemorial influences which have moulded it, from the succession of coming ages which it will help to fashion.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001659","text":"And this is specially true of the history of a race at once so aggressive, yet so tenacious of the past, as the Roman.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001660","text":"The national fibre was so tough, and its tone and sentiment so conservative under all external changes, that when a man knows any considerable period of Roman social history, he may almost, without paradox, be said to know a great deal of it from Romulus to Honorius.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001661","text":"But as in the case of the drama, such a period should possess a certain unity and intensity of moral interest.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001662","text":"It should be a crisis and turning-point in the life of humanity, a period pregnant with momentous issues, a period in which the old order and the new are contending for mastery, or in which the old is melting into the new.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001663","text":"Above all, it should be one in which the great social and spiritual movements are incarnate in some striking personalities, who may give a human interest to dim forces of spiritual evolution.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001664","text":"Such a period, it seems to the writer of this book, is that which he now presents to the reader.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001665","text":"It opens with the self-destruction of lawless and intoxicated power; it closes with the realisation of Plato’s dream of a reign of the philosophers.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001666","text":"The revolution in the ideal of the principate, which gave the world a Trajan, a Hadrian, and a Marcus Aurelius in place of a Caligula and a Nero, may not have been accompanied by any change of corresponding depth in the moral condition of the masses.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001667","text":"But the world enjoyed for nearly a century an almost unexampled peace and prosperity, under skilful and humane government.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001668","text":"The civic splendour and social charities of the Antonine age can be revived by the imagination from the abundant remains and records of the period.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001669","text":"Its materialism and social vices will also sadden the thoughtful student of its literature and inscriptions.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001670","text":"To the writer of this book, this seems to give the Antonine age its great distinction and its deepest interest for the student of the life of humanity.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001671","text":"The influence of philosophy on the legislation of the Antonines is a commonplace of history.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001672","text":"But its practical effort to give support and guidance to moral life, and to refashion the old paganism, so as to make it a real spiritual force, has perhaps hardly yet attracted the notice which it deserves.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001673","text":"It is one great object of this book to show how the later Stoicism and the new Platonism, working in eclectic harmony, strove to supply a rule of conduct and a higher vision of the Divine world.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001674","text":"But philosophy failed, as it will probably fail till some far-off age, to find an anodyne for the spiritual distresses of the mass of men.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001675","text":"It might hold up the loftiest ideal of conduct; it might revive the ancient gods in new spiritual power; it might strive to fill the interval between the remote Infinite Spirit and the life of man with a host of mediating and succouring powers.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001676","text":"It was an esoteric creed, and the masses remained untouched by it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001677","text":"They longed for a Divine light, a clear, authoritative voice from the unseen world.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001678","text":"They sought it in ever more blind and passionate devotion to their ancient deities, and in all the curiosity of superstition.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001679","text":"But the voice came to them at last from the regions of the East.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001680","text":"It came through the worships of Isis and Mithra, which promised a hope of immortality, and provided a sacramental system to soothe the sense of guilt and prepare the trembling soul for the great ordeal on the verge of another world.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001681","text":"How far these eastern systems succeeded, and where they failed, it is one great purpose of this book to explain.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001682","text":"The writer, so far as he knows himself, has had no _arrière pensée_ in describing this great moral and spiritual movement.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001683","text":"Boissier has pointed out, the historian of the Antonine age is free to treat paganism apart from the growth of the Christian Church.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001684","text":"The pagan world of that age seems to have had little communication with the loftier faith which, within a century and a half from the death of M.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001685","text":"To Juvenal, Tacitus, and Pliny, to Plutarch, Dion Chrysostom, Lucian, and M.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001686","text":"Aurelius, the Church is hardly known, or known as an obscure off-shoot of Judaism, a little sect, worshipping a “crucified Sophist” in somewhat suspicious retirement, or more favourably distinguished by simple-minded charity.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001687","text":"The modern theologian can hardly be content to know as little of the great movement in the heathen world which prepared or deferred the victory of the Church.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001688","text":"It will be evident to any critical reader that the scope of this book is strictly limited.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001689","text":"As in a former work on the Society of the later Empire, attention has been concentrated on the inner moral life of the time, and comparatively little space has been given to its external history and the machinery of government.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001690","text":"The relation of the Senate to the Emperor in the first century, and the organisation of the municipal towns have been dwelt on at some length, because they affected profoundly the moral character of the age.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001691","text":"On the particular field which the writer has surveyed, Dean Merivale, Dr.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001692","text":"Capes have thrown much light by their learning and sympathy.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001693","text":"But these distinguished writers have approached the period from a different point of view from that of the present author, and he believes that he has not incurred the serious peril of appearing to compete with them.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001694","text":"He has, as a first duty, devoted himself to a complete survey of the literature and inscriptions of the period.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001695","text":"References to the secondary authorities and monographs which he has used will be found in the notes.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001696","text":"But he owes a special obligation to Friedländer, Zeller, Réville, Schiller, Boissier, Martha, Peter, and Marquardt, for guidance and suggestion.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001697","text":"Once more he has to offer his warmest gratitude to his learned friend, the Rev.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:gratitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001698","text":"Charles Plummer, Fellow of C.C.C., Oxford, for the patience and judgment with which he has revised the proof sheets.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001699","text":"Clark’s reader, for the scrupulous accuracy which has saved the author much time and labour.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001700","text":"Caesar, the Elder Pliny, Tacitus—The feeling of Hadrian—Epictetus on immortality—Galen—His probable influence on M.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001701","text":"The fascination of the worship of the Great Mother—It was still powerful in the days of S.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001702","text":"to repress the worship—A violent struggle with varying fortunes—The triumvirs in 42 B.C.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001703","text":"The period of social history which we are about to study is profoundly interesting in many ways, but not least in the many contrasts between its opening and its close.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001704","text":"It opens with the tyranny of one of the worst men who ever occupied a throne; it ends with the mild rule of a Stoic saint.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001705","text":"It begins in massacre and the carnage of civil strife; it closes in the apparent triumph of the philosophic ideal, although before the end of the reign of the philosophers the shadows have begun to fall.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001706","text":"The contrast of character between the two princes is generally supposed to find a correspondence in the moral character and ideals of the men over whom they ruled.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001707","text":"The accession of Vespasian which, after a deadly struggle, seemed to bring the orgies of a brutal despotism to a close, is regarded as marking not only a political, but a moral, revolution.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001708","text":"It was the dawn of an age of repentance and amendment, of beneficent administration, of a great moral revival.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001709","text":"Even among the old noblesse, whose youth had fallen on the age of wild licence, it is probable that a better tone asserted itself at the beginning of what was recognised by all to be a new order.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001710","text":"Yet neither the language of Tacitus nor the testimony from other sources justify the belief in any sudden moral revolution.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001711","text":"The Antonine age was undoubtedly an age of conscientious and humane government in the interest of the subject; it was even more an age of religious revival.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001712","text":"But whether these were accompanied by a corresponding elevation of conduct and moral tone among the masses may well be doubted.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001713","text":"On the other hand the pessimism of satirist and historian who had lived through the darkness of the Terror has probably exaggerated the corruption of the evil days.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001714","text":"If society at large had been half as corrupt as it is represented by Juvenal, it would have speedily perished from mere rottenness.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001715","text":"The Inscriptions, the Letters of the younger Pliny, even the pages of Tacitus himself, reveal to us another world from that of the satirist.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001716","text":"On countless tombs we have the record or the ideal of a family life of sober, honest industry, and pure affection.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","audience:recovery","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001717","text":"The worst period of the Roman Empire was the most glorious age of practical Stoicism.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001718","text":"The great Stoic doctrine of the brotherhood and equality of men, as members of a world-wide commonwealth, which was destined to inspire legislation in the Antonine age, was openly preached in the reigns of Caligula and Nero.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001719","text":"The old cruelty and contempt for the slave will not give way for many a generation; but the slave is now treated by all the great leaders of moral reform as a being of the same mould as his master, his equal, if not his superior, in capacity for virtue.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001720","text":"The peculiar distinction of the Antonine age is not to be sought in any great difference from the age preceding it in conduct or moral ideals among the great mass of men.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001721","text":"Nor can it claim any literary distinction of decided originality, except in the possession of the airy grace and half-serious mockery of Lucian.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001722","text":"Juvenal, Tacitus, and the younger Pliny, Suetonius and Quintilian, Plutarch and Dion Chrysostom, were probably all dead before Antoninus Pius came to the throne.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001723","text":"After Hadrian’s reign pure Roman literature, in any worthy sense, is extinct; it dies away in that Sahara of the higher intellect which stretches forward to the Fall of the Empire.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001724","text":"There is no great historian after Tacitus; there is no considerable poet after Statius and Juvenal, till the meteor-like apparition of Claudian in the ominous reign of Honorius.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001725","text":"The material splendour and municipal life of the Antonine age are externally its greatest glory.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001726","text":"From the wall of Hadrian to the edge of the Sahara towns sprang up everywhere with as yet a free civic life.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001727","text":"It was an age of engineers and architects, who turned villages into cities and built cities in the desert, adorned with temples and stately arches and basilicas, and feeding their fountains from the springs of distant hills.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001728","text":"The rich were powerful and popular; and never had they to pay so heavily for popularity and power.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001729","text":"The cost of civic feasts and games, of forums and temples and theatres, was won by flattery, or extorted by an inexorable force of public opinion from their coffers.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001730","text":"The poor were feasted and amused by their social superiors who received a deference and adulation expressed on hundreds of inscriptions.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001731","text":"And it must be confessed that these records of ambitious munificence and expectant gratitude do not raise our conception of either the economic or the moral condition of the age.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:gratitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001732","text":"The glory of classic art had almost vanished; and yet, without being able to produce any works of creative genius, the inexhaustible vitality of the Hellenic spirit once more asserted itself.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001733","text":"After a long eclipse, the rhetorical culture of Greece vigorously addressed itself in the reign of Hadrian to the conquest of the West.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001734","text":"Her teachers and spiritual directors indeed had long been in every family of note.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001735","text":"Her sophists were now seen haranguing crowds in every town from the Don to the Atlantic.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001736","text":"Philosophy became a religion, and devoted itself not only to the private direction of character and the preaching of a higher life, but to the justification and unification of pagan faith.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001737","text":"In spite of its rather bourgeois ideal of material enjoyment and splendour, the Antonine age, at least in its higher minds, was an age of a purified moral sense and religious intuition.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001738","text":"On the one hand, not only was the old ritual of classical polytheism scrupulously observed even by men like Plutarch and M.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001739","text":"Aurelius, but religious imagination was appropriating the deities of every province, almost of every canton, embraced by the Roman power.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001740","text":"At the same time the fecundity of superstition created hosts of new divinities and genii who peopled every scene of human life.(9) On the other hand syncretism was in the air.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001741","text":"Amid all the confused ferment of devotion a certain principle of unity and comprehension was asserting itself, even in popular religion.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001742","text":"The old gods were losing their sharp-cut individuality; the provinces and attributes of kindred deities tended to fade into one another, and melt into the conception of a single central Power.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001743","text":"The religions of Egypt and the remoter East, with their inner monotheism, supported by the promise of sacramental grace and the hope of immortality, came in to give impetus to the great spiritual movement.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001744","text":"The simple peasant might cling to his favourite god, as his Neapolitan descendant has his favourite saint.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001745","text":"But an Apuleius, an Apollonius, or an Alexander Severus(10) sought a converging spiritual support in the gods and mysteries of every clime.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001746","text":"Platonist philosophy strove to give rational expression to this movement, to reconcile cultivated moral sense with the worships of the past, to find a bond between the vagrant religious fancies of the crowd and the remote esoteric faith of the philosophic few.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001747","text":"On the higher minds, from whatever quarter, a spiritual vision had opened, which was strange to the ancient world, the vision of One who is no longer a mere Force, but an infinite Father, Creator, Providence and Guardian, from whom we come, to whom we go at death.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:leadership","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001748","text":"These were some of the religious ideas current among the best men, Dion Chrysostom, Plutarch, Maximus of Tyre, which the Neo-Platonic school strove to harmonise with the rites and legends of the past.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001749","text":"The means by which they tried to do so, and the measure of their success, it is one purpose of this book to explain.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001750","text":"The Antonine age saw for a brief space the dream of Plato realised, when kings should be philosophers, and philosophers should be kings.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001751","text":"Philosophy had given up its detached and haughty reserve, or outspoken opposition to imperial power.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001752","text":"Philosophy now began to inspire legislation and statesmanship.(13) Its professors were raised to the consulship and great prefectures.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001753","text":"Above all, it was incarnate, as it were, in the ruler who, whatever we may think of his practical success, brought to the duties of government a loftiness of spiritual detachment which has never been equalled by any ruler of men.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001754","text":"Whether there was any corresponding elevation of conduct or moral tone in the mass of men may well be doubted by any one who has studied the melancholy thoughts of the saintly emperor.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001755","text":"Aurelius seem to be as hopeless about the moral condition of humanity as Seneca and Petronius were in the darkest days of Nero’s tyranny.(14) Such opinions, indeed, have little scientific value.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001756","text":"They are often the result of temperament and ideals, not of trustworthy observation.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001757","text":"But it would be rash to assume that heightened religious feeling and the efforts of philosophy had within a hundred years worked any wide-spread transformation of character.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001758","text":"It was, however, a great step in advance that the idea of the principate, expounded by Seneca, and the younger Pliny, as a clement, watchful, infinitely laborious earthly providence had been realised since the accession of Trajan.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001759","text":"Aurelius than in the reign of Nero, and it was especially easier for a man of the highest social grade.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001760","text":"The example of the prince for good or evil must always powerfully influence the class who are by birth or office nearest to the throne.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001761","text":"And bad example will be infinitely more corrupting when it is reinforced by terror.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001762","text":"A fierce, capricious tyranny generates a class of vices which are perhaps more degrading to human dignity, and socially more dangerous, than the vices of the flesh.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:justice","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001763","text":"And the reign of such men as Caligula, Nero, and Domitian not only stimulated the grossness of self-indulgence, but superadded the treachery and servility of cowardice.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001764","text":"In order to appreciate fully what the world had gained by the mild and temperate rule of the princes of the second century, it is necessary to revive for a moment the terrors of the Claudian Caesars.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001765","text":"The power of Seneca as a moral teacher has, with some reservations, been recognised by all the ages since his time.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001766","text":"But equal recognition has hardly been given to the lurid light which he throws, in random flashes, on the moral conditions of his class under the tyranny of Caligula and Nero.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001767","text":"This may be due, perhaps, to a distrust of his artificial declamation, and that falsetto note which he too often strikes even in his most serious moments.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001768","text":"Yet he must be an unsympathetic reader who does not perceive that, behind the moral teaching of Seneca, there lies an awful experience, a lifelong torture, which turns all the fair-seeming blessings of life, state and luxury and lofty rank, into dust and ashes.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:gratitude","theme:justice","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001769","text":"There is a haunting shadow over Seneca which never draws away, which sometimes deepens into a horror of darkness.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001770","text":"In whatever else Seneca may have been insincere, his veiled references to the terrors of the imperial despotism come from the heart.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001771","text":"Seneca’s life almost coincides with the Julio-Claudian tyranny.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001772","text":"With a face betraying no sign of emotion, he was compelled to drink to the Emperor, while spies were eagerly watching every expression of his face.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001773","text":"He had another son.” Exiled to Corsica in the reign of Claudius,(20) Seneca bore the sentence with less dignity than he afterwards met death.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:justice","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001774","text":"He witnessed the reign of the freedmen, the infamies of Messalina, the intrigues of Agrippina, and the treacherous murder of Britannicus; he knew all the secrets of that ghastly court.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001775","text":"Installed as the tutor of the young Nero, he doubtless, if we may judge by the treatise on Clemency, strove to inspire him with a high ideal of monarchy as an earthly providence.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001776","text":"Domitius Ahenobarbus and Agrippina the fatal heritage of a vicious blood and the omens of a ghastly reign.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001777","text":"The young tiger was held on leash for the famous quinquennium by Burrus and Seneca.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001778","text":"It seemed only the device of a divine tragic artist, by a brief space of calm and innocence, to deepen the horror of the catastrophe.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001779","text":"He had to bear the unenviable distinction of a possible pretender to the principate.(23) He withdrew into almost monastic seclusion, and even offered to resign his wealth.(24) He strove to escape the evil eyes of calumny and imperial distrust by the most abject renunciation.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001780","text":"Seneca, like Tacitus, has a remarkable power of moral diagnosis.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001781","text":"He had acquired a profound, sad knowledge of the pathology of the soul.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001782","text":"It was a power which was almost of necessity acquired in that time of terror and suspicion, when men lived in daily peril from seeming friends.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001783","text":"There never was a period when men more needed the art of reading the secrets of character.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001784","text":"Nor was there ever a time when there were greater facilities for the study.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001785","text":"In his later years, if he became a recluse, he was also a spiritual director.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001786","text":"And his Letters leave little doubt that many a restless or weary spirit laid bare its secret misery to him, for advice or consolation.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001787","text":"Seneca is too often a rhetorician, in search of striking effects and vivid phrase.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001788","text":"At times he appears to regard his own age as having reached the very climax of insane self-indulgence.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001789","text":"Seneca’s state of nature is the antithesis of the selfish and materialised society in which he lived.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001790","text":"Our early ancestors were not indeed virtuous in the strict sense.(32) For virtue is the result of struggle and philosophic guidance.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001791","text":"But their instincts were good, because they were not tempted.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001792","text":"They enjoyed in common the natural bounties of mother earth.(33) Their fierceness of energy spent itself on the beasts of the chase.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001793","text":"They lived peaceably in willing obedience to the gentle paternal rule of their wisest and best, with no lust of gold or power, no jealousy and hatred, to break a contented and unenvious harmony.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001794","text":"In individualist cravings men lost hold on the common wealth of nature.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001795","text":"Such a theory of society has, of course, no value or interest in itself.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001796","text":"Its interest, like that of similar _à priori_ dreams, lies in the light which it sheds on the social conditions which gave it birth.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001797","text":"Like the Germany of Tacitus, and the Social Contract of Rousseau, Seneca’s theory of the evolution of humanity is an oblique satire on the vices of his own age.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001798","text":"And not even in Tacitus or Suetonius are to be found more ghastly revelations of a putrescent society, and the ennui and self-loathing which capricious sensualism generates in spirits born for something higher.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001799","text":"There is a universal lust of gold:(38) riches are the one ornament and stay of life.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001800","text":"And yet in those days a great fortune was only a splendid servitude.(39) It had to be guarded amid perpetual peril and envy.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001801","text":"The universal greed and venality are worthily matched by the endless anxiety of those who have won the prize.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mental-health","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001802","text":"Human life has become a scene of cruel and selfish egotism, a ferocious struggle of beasts of prey, eager for rapine, and heedless of those who go down in the obscene struggle.(40) It is an age when men glorify the fortunate and trample on the fallen.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001803","text":"The cunning and cruelty of the wild beast on the throne have taught a lesson of dissimulation to the subject.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001804","text":"At such a court it is a miracle to reach old age, and the feat can only be accomplished by accepting insult and injury with a smiling face.(41) For him who goes undefended by such armour of hypocrisy there is always ready the rack, the poisoned cup, the order for self-murder.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001805","text":"It is characteristic of the detachment of Seneca that he sees the origin of this hateful tyranny.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001806","text":"No modern has more clearly discerned the far-reaching curse of slavery.(42) Every great house is a miniature of the Empire under a Caligula or Nero, a nursery of pretenders capable of the same enormities.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001807","text":"And the system of household slavery enervated character while it made it heartless and cruel.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001808","text":"The Inscriptions confirm Seneca’s picture of the minute division of functions among the household, to anticipate every possible need or caprice of the master.(44) Under such a system the master became a helpless dependent.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001809","text":"There is real truth, under some ludicrous exaggeration, in the tale of a Roman noble, taking his seat in his sedan after the bath, and requiring the assurance of his slave that he was really seated.(45)","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001810","text":"It is little wonder that on such lives an utter weariness should settle, the disgust of oversated appetite, which even the most far-fetched luxuries of the orient, the most devilish ingenuity of morbid vice, could hardly arouse.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001811","text":"In reading Seneca’s writings, especially those of his last years, you are conscious of a horror which hardly ever takes definite shape, a thick stifling air, as it were, charged with lightning.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001812","text":"It is not so much that Seneca fears death itself, although we may suspect that his nerves sometimes gave the lie to his principles.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mortality","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001813","text":"The gloom of Seneca seems rather to spring from a sense of the terrible contrast between wealth and state and an ignominious doom which was ever ready to fall.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001814","text":"And to his fevered eye all stately rank seems at last but a precipice overhanging the abyss, a mark for treacherous envy or the spitefulness of Fortune.(55) “A great fortune is a great servitude,”(56) which, if it has been hard to win, is harder still to guard.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001815","text":"Pleasure is nearest neighbour to pain; the summer sea in a moment is boiling in the tempest; the labour of long years is scattered in a day; there is always terror lurking under our deepest peace.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001816","text":"The interest of all this lies, not in Seneca’s inconsistency, but in the nightmare which brooded on such minds in the reign of Nero.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001817","text":"Something of the gloom of Seneca was part of the evil heritage of a class, commanding inexhaustible wealth and assailed by boundless temptations to self-indulgence, which had been offered by the conquest of East and West.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001818","text":"The weary senses failed to respond to the infinite sensual seductions which surrounded the Roman noble from his earliest years.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001819","text":"If he did not succeed in squandering his fortune, he often exhausted too early his capacity for healthy joy in life, and the nemesis of sated appetite and disillusionment too surely cast its shadow over his later years.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mental-health","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001820","text":"Prurient slander was rife in those days, and we are not bound to accept all its tales about Seneca.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001821","text":"A soul so passionate in its renunciation may, according to laws of human nature, have been once as passionate in indulgence.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001822","text":"In his case, as so often in the history of the Church, the saint may have had a terrible repentance.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001823","text":"It is probable, however, that this pessimism is more the result of the contrast between Seneca’s ideal of the principate, and the degradation of its power in the hands of his pupil Nero.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001824","text":"It is very much the ideal of Pliny and Dion Chrysostom under the strong and temperate rule of Trajan.(66) Addressed to one of the worst emperors, it seems, to one looking back, almost a satire.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001825","text":"Yet we should remember that, strange as it may seem, Nero, with all his wild depravity, appears to have had a strange charm for many, even to the end.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001826","text":"But it is more probable that the piece is rather a warning than a prophecy.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001827","text":"The prophecy of the father as to the future of Agrippina’s son(70) found probably an echo in the fears of his tutor.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001828","text":"But, in spite of his forebodings, Seneca thought the attempt to save him worth making.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001829","text":"Nero has succeeded to a vicegerency of God on earth.(71) He is the arbiter of life and death, on whose word the fortunes of citizens, the happiness or misery of whole peoples depend.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:mortality","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001830","text":"His innocence raises the highest hopes.(72) But the imperial task is heavy, and its perils are appalling.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001831","text":"The emperor is the one bond by which the world-empire is held together;(73) he is its vital breath.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001832","text":"Man, the hardest of all animals to govern,(74) can only be governed long by love, and love can only be won by beneficence and gentleness to the frowardness of men.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001833","text":"In his god-like place, the prince should imitate the mercy of the gods.(75) Wielding illimitable power, he is yet the servant of all, and cannot usurp the licence of the private subject.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001834","text":"He is like one of the heavenly orbs, bound by inevitable law to move onward in a fixed orbit, unswerving and unresting.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001835","text":"If he relies on cruel force, rather than on clemency, he will sink to the level of the tyrant and meet his proper fate.(76) Cruelty in a king only multiplies his enemies and envenoms hatred.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001836","text":"The king, once dreaded by his people, loses his nerve and strikes out blindly in self-defence.(77) The atmosphere of treachery and suspicion thickens around him, and, in the end, what, to his maddened mind, seemed at first a stern necessity becomes a mere lust for blood.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001837","text":"It has been suggested that Seneca was really, to some extent, the cause of the grotesque or tragic failure of Nero.(78) The rhetorical spirit, which breathes through all Seneca’s writings, may certainly be an evil influence in the education of a ruler of men.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001838","text":"The habit of playing with words, of aiming at momentary effect, with slight regard to truth, may inspire the excitable vanity of the artist, but is hardly the temper for dealing with the hard problems of government.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001839","text":"And the dazzling picture of the boundless power of a Roman emperor, which Seneca put before his pupil, in order to heighten his sense of responsibility, might intoxicate a mind naturally prone to grandiose visions, while the sober lesson would be easily forgotten.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","audience:recovery","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001840","text":"The spectacle of “the kingdoms of the world and all the glory of them” at his feet was a dangerous temptation to a temperament like Nero’s.(79) Arrogance and cruelty were in the blood of the Domitii.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001841","text":"We need not lay too much stress on the innocence ascribed to him by Seneca.(82) Nor need we attribute to Nero’s initiative the sound or benevolent measures which characterised the beginning of his reign.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001842","text":"Even his quinquennial festival, inspired by the Greek contests in music and gymnastic,(85) represented a finer ideal of such gatherings, which was much needed by a race devoted to the coarse realism of pantomime and the butchery of the arena.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001843","text":"Fierce and incalculably capricious as he could be, Nero, at his best, had also a softer side.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001844","text":"He had a craving for love and appreciation(86); some of his cruelty was probably the revenge for the denial of it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001845","text":"He was singularly patient of lampoons and invective against himself.(87) Although he could be brutal in his treatment of women, he also knew how to inspire real affection, and perhaps in a few cases return it.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001846","text":"He seems to have had something of real love for Acte, his mistress.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001847","text":"And the strange, lingering superstition, which disturbed the early Church, and which looked for his reappearance down to the eleventh century, could hardly have gathered around an utterly mean and mediocre character.(89)","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001848","text":"When Nero uttered the words “Qualis artifex pereo,”(90) he gave not only his own interpretation of his life, he also revealed one great secret of its ghastly failure.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001849","text":"It may be admitted that Nero had a certain artistic enthusiasm, a real ambition to excel.(91) He painted with some skill, he composed verses not without a certain grace.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001850","text":"In spite of serious natural defects, he took endless pains to acquire the technique of a singer.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001851","text":"And, in spite of his arrogance and vanity, he had a wholesome deference for the artistic judgment of Greece.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001852","text":"Yet it is very striking that in the records of his reign, the most damning accusation is that he disgraced the purple by exhibitions on the stage.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001853","text":"A false literary ambition, born of a false system of education, was the bane of Roman culture for many ages.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001854","text":"The dilettante artist on the throne in the first century had many a successor in the literary arts among the grand seigneurs of the fifth.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001855","text":"They could play with their ingenious tricks of verse in sight of the Gothic camp-fires.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001856","text":"He could contend for the wreath at Olympia when his faithful freedman was summoning him back by the news that the West was seething with revolt.(94)","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001857","text":"Nero’s mother had dissuaded him from the study of philosophy; his tutor debarred him from the study of the manly oratory of the great days.(95) The world was now to learn the meaning of a false artistic ambition, divorced from a sense of reality and duty.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001858","text":"Aestheticism may be only a love of sensational effects, with no glimpse of the ideal.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001859","text":"It may be a hypocritical materialism, screening itself under divine names.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001860","text":"And yet he was in some respects in thorough sympathy with the masses.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001861","text":"His lavish games and spectacles atoned to some extent for his aberrations of Hellenism.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001862","text":"He was generous and wasteful, and he encouraged waste in others,(98) and waste is always popular till the bill has to be paid.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:courage","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001863","text":"He was a “cupitor incredibilium.”(99) The province of Africa was ransacked to find the fabled treasure of Dido.(100) Explorers were sent to pierce the mysterious barrier of the Caucasus, and discover the secret sources of the Nile.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001864","text":"Stained with the foulest enormities himself, he had a rooted conviction that virtue was a pretence, and that all men were equally depraved.(104) His surroundings gave him some excuse for thinking so.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001865","text":"He was born into a circle which believed chiefly in “the lust of the eye and the pride of life.” He formed a circle many of whom perished in the carnage of Bedriacum.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001866","text":"With a treasury drained by insane profusion, Nero resorted to rapine and judicial murder to replenish it.(105) The spendthrift seldom has scruples in repairing his extravagance.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001867","text":"Yet it is perhaps necessary to revive it once more to explain the suppressed terror and lingering agony of the last days of Seneca.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001868","text":"The impressions of the Terror which we receive from Seneca are powerful and almost oppressive.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001869","text":"A thick atmosphere of gloom and foreboding seems to stifle us as we turn his pages.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001870","text":"But Seneca deals rather in shadowy hint and veiled suggestion than in definite statement.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001871","text":"For the minute picture of that awful scene of degradation we must turn to Tacitus.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001872","text":"He wrote in the fresh dawn of an age of fancied freedom, when the gloom of the tyranny seemed to have suddenly vanished like an evil dream.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001873","text":"Yet he cannot shake off the sense of horror and disgust which fifteen years of ignoble compliance or silent suffering have burnt into his soul.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001874","text":"Even under the manly, tolerant rule of Trajan, he hardly seems to have regained his breath.(108) He can scarcely believe that the light has come at last.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001875","text":"His attitude to the tyranny is essentially different from that of Seneca.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001876","text":"The son of the provincial from Cordova views the scene rather as the cosmopolitan moralist, imperilled by his huge fortune and the neighbourhood of the terrible palace.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001877","text":"The feelings of Seneca express themselves rather in rhetorical self-pity.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001878","text":"The feelings of Tacitus find vent in words which sometimes veil a pathos too proud for effusive utterance, sometimes cut like lancet points, and which, in their concentrated moral scorn, have left an eternal brand of infamy on names of historic renown.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001879","text":"As a young boy, he must have often heard the tales of the artistic follies and the orgies of Nero, and the ghastly cruelties of the end of his reign.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001880","text":"As a lad of fifteen, he may have witnessed something of the carnival of blood and lust which appropriately closed the régime of the Julio-Claudian line.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001881","text":"It cannot be doubted from his own words that, as a senator, he had to witness tamely the Curia beset with soldiery, the noblest women driven into exile, and men of the highest rank and virtue condemned to death on venal testimony in the secret tribunal of the Alban Palace.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:mortality","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001882","text":"His hand helped to drag Helvidius to the dungeon, and was stained with the blood of Senecio.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001883","text":"He lived long enough under a better prince to leave an unfading picture of the tragedy of solitary and remorseless power, but not long enough to forget the horrors and degradation through which he had passed.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001884","text":"Moreover Tacitus, although originally not of the highest social rank,(121) belonged to the aristocratic class by sympathy and associations.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001885","text":"He mingled in those circles, which in every age disguise the meanness and bitterness of gossip by the airy artistic touch of audacious wit, polished in many social encounters.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001886","text":"He had himself witnessed the triumph of delation and the cold cruelty of Domitian.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001887","text":"He had shared in the humiliation of the Senate which had been cowed into acquiescence in his worst excesses.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001888","text":"He realised the difficulties of government and the unreasonableness of ordinary men.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001889","text":"Such an interpretation would be a grave mistake, which he would himself have been the first to correct.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001890","text":"The ideal which he is avenging is not a political, but a moral ideal.(126) The bitter sadness is that of the profound analyst of character, with a temperament of almost feverish intensity and nervous force.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001891","text":"The interest of history to Thucydides and Polybius lies in the political lessons which it may teach posterity.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001892","text":"Its interest to Tacitus lies in the discovery of hidden motives and the secret of character, in watching the stages of an inevitable degeneracy, the moral preparation for a dark, inglorious end.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001893","text":"And the analyst was a curiously vivid painter of character, the character of individuals, of periods, and of peoples.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001894","text":"His portraits burn themselves into the imaginative memory, so that the impression, once seized, can never be lost.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001895","text":"Tiberius and Claudius and Nero, Messalina and Agrippina, in spite of the most mordant criticism, will live for ever as they have been portrayed by the fervid imagination of Tacitus.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001896","text":"Nor is he less searching and vivid in depicting the collective feeling and character of masses of men.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001897","text":"The baths and brothels and taverns are crowded at the very hour when the neighbouring ways are piled with corpses and running with blood; the rush of indulgence paused not for a moment; men seemed to revel in the public disasters.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001898","text":"The key to the interpretation of Tacitus is to regard him as a moralist rather than a politician.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001899","text":"And he is a moralist with a sad, clinging pessimism.(136) He is doomed to be the chronicler of an evil time, although he will save from oblivion the traces and relics of ancient virtue.(137) He has Seneca’s pessimist theory of evolution.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001900","text":"The early equality and peace and temperance have been lost through a steady growth of greed and egotistic ambition.(138) It is in the past we must seek our ideals; it is from the past we derive our strength.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:justice","theme:mindfulness","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001901","text":"Aurelius had,(139) he holds vaguely a similar view of cycles in human affairs.(140) And probably the fairest hope which ever visited the mind of Tacitus was that of a return to the simplicity of a long gone age.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:justice","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001902","text":"He hailed the accession of Vespasian and of Trajan as a happy change to purer manners and to freedom of speech.(141) But the reign of Vespasian had been followed by the gloomy suspicious despotism of Domitian.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001903","text":"Tacitus hardly shared the enthusiasm and exuberant hopes expressed by his friend Pliny in his _Panegyric_.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001904","text":"It was a natural outbreak of joy at escaping from the dungeon, and the personal character of Trajan succeeded in partially veiling the overwhelming force of the emperor under the figment of the freely accepted rule of the first citizen.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001905","text":"But he did not share Pliny’s illusions as to the prince’s altered position under the new régime.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001906","text":"The old Republic was gone for ever.(143) It was still the rule of one man, on whose character everything depended.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001907","text":"He would never have joined Plutarch and Dion in exalting the emperor to the rank of vicegerent of God.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001908","text":"With his experience and psychologic skill, he was bound to regard all solitary power as a terrible danger both to its holder and his subjects.(144) “Capax imperii, nisi imperasset” condenses a whole disquisition on imperialism.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001909","text":"In truth, Tacitus, like many thoughtful students of politics, had little faith in mere political forms and names.(145) They are often the merest imposture: they depend greatly on the spirit and social tone which lie behind them.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001910","text":"In the abstract, perhaps, Tacitus would have given a preference to aristocracy.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001911","text":"But he saw how easily it might pass into a selfish despotism.(146) He had no faith in the people or in popular government, with its unstable excitability.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001912","text":"He admitted that the conquests of Rome, egotistic ambition, and the long anarchy of the Civil Wars had made the rule of one inevitable.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001913","text":"But monarchy easily glides into tyranny, and he accepts the Empire only as a perilous necessity which may be justified by the advent of a good prince.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001914","text":"The hereditary succession, which had been grafted on the principate of Augustus, had inflicted on the world a succession of fools or monsters.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001915","text":"The only hope lay in elevating the standard of virtue, and in the choice of a worthy successor by the forms of adoption.(147) The one had in his own time given the world a Domitian, and was destined within three generations to give it a Commodus.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001916","text":"The other secured to it the peace and order of the age of which Tacitus saw the dawn.(148)","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001917","text":"The motive of Tacitus was essentially ethical, and his moral standard was in many respects lofty.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001918","text":"Yet his standard was sometimes limited by the prejudices of his class.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001919","text":"He cherished the old Roman ideal of “virtus” rather than the Stoic gospel of a cosmopolitan brotherhood of man.(149) Like Pliny, he felt little horror at gladiatorial combats,(150) although he may have had a certain contempt for the rage for them.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001920","text":"His ideal of youthful chastity and of the pure harmony of a single wedded union, reveals to us another world from the scene of heartless, vagrant intrigue, on which Ovid wasted his brilliant gifts.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001921","text":"While Tacitus had a burning contempt for the nerveless cowardice and sluggishness which degraded so many of his order,(159) he may have valued even to excess, although it is hardly possible to do so, the virtues of the strenuous soldier.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001922","text":"Proud submission to authority, proud, cold endurance in the face of cruel hardship and enormous odds, readiness to sacrifice even life at the call of the State, must always tower over the safe aspirations of an untried virtue.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001923","text":"The soldier, though he never knows it, is the noblest of idealists.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001924","text":"Yet, after all, Tacitus was too great for such a limited ideal.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001925","text":"The deepest feeling of Tacitus about the early Empire seems to have been that it was fatal to character both in prince and subject.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001926","text":"This conviction he has expressed with the burning intensity of the artist.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001927","text":"He could never have penned one of those laborious paragraphs of Suetonius which seem transcribed from a carefully kept note-book, with a lifeless catalogue of the vices, the virtues, and the eccentricities of the subject.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001928","text":"For Tacitus, history is a living and real thing, not a matter of mere antiquarian interest.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001929","text":"He has seen a single lawless will, unchecked by constitutional restraints or ordinary human feeling, making sport of the lives and fortunes of men.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:evening","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001930","text":"And so, by a curse like that which haunted the Pelopidae in tragic legend, the monarchy, cradled in ambition and civil strife, has gone on corrupting and corrupted.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001931","text":"The lust of despotic power which Tacitus regards as the fiercest and most insatiable of human passions, has been intensified by the spectacle of a monarchy commanding, with practically unlimited sway, the resources and the fortunes of a world.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001932","text":"It was a dazzling prize, offering frightful temptations both to the holder and to possible rivals and pretenders.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001933","text":"The day on which a Nero or a Caligula awoke to all the possibilities of power was a fateful one.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001934","text":"And Tacitus, with the instinct of the tragic artist, has painted the steady, fatal corruption of a prince’s character by the corroding influence of absolute and solitary sway.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001935","text":"Of all the Caesars down to his time, the only one who changed for the better was the homely Vespasian.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001936","text":"In Tiberius, Caligula, and Nero, some of this deterioration of character must be set down to the morbid strain in the Julio-Claudian line, with its hard and cruel pride, and its heritage of a tainted blood, of which Nero’s father knew the secret so well.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001937","text":"Much was also due to the financial exhaustion which, in successive reigns, followed the most reckless waste.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001938","text":"It would be difficult to say whether the emperors or their nobles were the most to blame for the example of spendthrift extravagance and insane luxury.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001939","text":"We have the testimony of Pliny and Claudian,(176) separated by an interval of three hundred years, that the world readily conforms its life to that of one man, if that man is head of the State.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001940","text":"Nero’s youthful enthusiasm for declamation gave an immense impulse to the passion for rhetoric.(177) His enthusiasm for acting and music spread through all ranks, and the emperor’s catches were sung at wayside inns.(178) M.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001941","text":"Aurelius made philosophy the mode, and the Stoic Emperor is responsible for some of the philosophic imposture which moved the withering scorn of Lucian.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001942","text":"The extravagance of the Claudian Caesars and the last Flavian has become a piece of historic commonplace.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001943","text":"The Egyptian roses for a single banquet cost £35,000.(183) He is said never to have made a progress with less than a thousand carriages; his mules were shod with silver.(184) He would stake HS.400,000 on a single throw of the dice.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001944","text":"The description of his Golden House is like a vision of lawless romance.(185) The successors of Galba were equally lavish during their brief term.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001945","text":"Under Domitian, the spectacles and largesses lavished on the mob undid all the scrupulous finance of his father,(189) and Nerva had to liquidate the ruinous heritage by wholesale retrenchment, and the sale even of the imperial furniture and plate,(190) as M.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001946","text":"Aurelius brought to the hammer his household treasures, and even the wardrobe and jewels of the empress, in the stress of the Marcomannic war.(191)","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001947","text":"But the great imperial spendthrifts resorted to more simple and primitive methods of replenishing their coffers.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001948","text":"Self-indulgent waste is often seen linked with meanness and hard cruelty.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001949","text":"The epigram of Suetonius on Domitian, _inopia rapax, metu saevus_,(192) sums up the sordid history of the tyranny.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001950","text":"The cool biographer of Caligula, Nero, and Domitian, when in his methodical fashion, he has recorded their financial difficulties, immediately proceeds to describe the unblushing rapine or ingenious chicanery by which the needy tyrants annexed a coveted estate.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001951","text":"The emperors now generally protected the provinces from plunder,(193) but they applied all the Verrine methods to their own nobles.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001952","text":"It was not hard with the help of the sleuth hounds who always gather round the despot, to find plausible grounds of accusation.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001953","text":"A great part of the day was spent at morning receptions, in the Forum, the Campus Martius, the barber’s or bookseller’s shops, or in the colonnades where crowds of fashionable idlers gathered to relieve the tedium of life by gossip and repartee.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001954","text":"It was a city, says Tacitus, which knew everything and talked of everything.(197) Never was curiosity more eager or gossip more reckless.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"stoic-ext-001955","text":"And in the reign of Nero or Domitian, the risk was a very real one.","author":"Seneca","source":"Letters from a Stoic, Vol. III","tags":["audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."}]}